<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TVPurchase     02-07 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Purchase,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Files FCC Petition To Block Pension System Purchase Of TV
Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Guy Hunt filed a petition Monday
with the Federal Communications Commission to block the state
pension system from buying a television station, saying it raised
troubling First Amendment issues.
   Hunt objected to the $70 million purchase agreement on several
grounds, including freedom of press implications raised by a
state-funded agency gaining control of a major news outlet in the
seat of government.
   David Bronner, who manages the $8 billion portfolio of the
Retirement Systems of Alabama, has defended his decision to buy
WSFA-TV from Cosmos Broadcasting Inc. of Greenville, S.C. He said
there would be no tampering with the news product.
   ``We're glad the issue is before the FCC, where it ought to be,''
said Bill Stephens, an attorney for the retirment systems.
   Monday was the deadline for petitions to be filed concerning
transfer of the WSFA license. The Hunt petition asks the federal
agency to delay any decision until the courts in Alabama resolve
legal issues raised by the purchase agreement.
   The FCC petition by Hunt sets in motion what may be a protracted
legal fight. Bronner has said the purchase is a ``done deal,''
needing only FCC approval.
   ``It is not a done deal,'' said Hunt at a news conference Monday.
   The petition filed by Hunt contends the purchase of the
long-dominant commercial television station in the state capital
``raises clear and very troubling First Amendment issues.''
   The petition says the purchase also would violate Alabama law
barring government from entering the field of private enterprise. It
further says the deal would violate FCC rules by giving state
government two broadcast outlets in Montgomery, counting the state's
educational television operation.
   William Walsh, deputy secretary-treasurer of the retirement
systems, says pension program officials feel there is no conflict
with state law. Already, he said, ``the state is involved in the
whisky business, the state is in the hotel and motel business, the
state runs the state docks.''
   Walsh referred to the Alabama Alcoholic Beverage Control Board
that regulates liquor sales, most of which are sold from state-run
stores, and state-owned resorts that are part of Alabama's state
park system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
