<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugProgram     02-07 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Program,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medium-Sized Cities Targeted for Education, Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A health-care foundation announced Monday it will
give $26.4 million to medium-sized communities for education and
treatment programs aimed at reducing demand for drugs.
   The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, the nation's largest
health-care philanthropy, said the effort, titled ``Fighting Back,''
was aimed at communities of 100,000 to 250,000.
   Regions straddling more than one county or parts of bigger cities
are eligible to apply for the money.
   Up to 12 communities will receive one- or two-year planning
grants of $100,000 a year. Eight will be selected for subsequent
grants of $3 million each over five years.
   Dr. W. Anderson Spickard Jr., professor of medicine at Vanderbilt
University in Nashville, Tenn., will direct the program.
   ``To date, most communities have focused on limiting the supply
of illegal drugs and alcohol _ a crucially important endeavor,''
said Leighton E. Cluff, president of the Princeton, N.J.-based
foundation, in a news release. ``But efforts to reduce the demand
for these substances have been fragmented and short-lived.''
   He said the new initiative ``has been designed to help
communities fight back, using preventive education and treatment to
complement the important law enforcement efforts already under way.''
   Citizens' task forces must submit letters of intent by May 1 and
formally apply by Sept. 1. The initial grants will be awarded in
February 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
