<FIRST>r a PM-HomelessJackpot     02-07 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless Jackpot,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Wins $2.7 Million Jackpot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man who won a $2.7 million jackpot
says he plans to get an apartment but will continue to work at the
recycling plant he has called home for years.
   Don Sarbaugh said he also will continue his nightly habit of
gambling at a casino, but has no other firm plans for his new found
wealth.
   ``I'm no different today than I was a week ago,'' said the
54-year-old former vagrant. ``I'm still a reclamation engineer.''
   Sarbaugh was given his first installment of $137,500 on Monday
for hitting the jackpot on a Megabucks machine at the Palace Station
casino. He will be paid in annual installments for 20 years.
   Sarbaugh's boss, George Liquori, said most of the first check is
already spoken for.
   ``He's got a lot of money to repay to Uncle Sam and he has a lot
of debts to pay off,'' said Liquori, who operates Nova Recycling.
``We're going to get him an apartment and pay a year's rent in
advance to set him up. He's not going to have a lot left.''
   Liquori said Sarbaugh has worked and lived at the plant for
several years. He said his diligence at work separated him from the
other homeless people who dropped off cans and newspapers there.
   ``He was there every morning and he was always working hard,
which I respected,'' said Liquori. ``He pretty much lived at the
plant but we're going to find him an apartment now.''
   Sarbaugh appeared at a Monday press conference to announce the
jackpot victory, which occurred Friday night. For the press
conference, Sarbaugh had received a haircut, got his beard trimmed
and was wearing new clothes.
   Sarbaugh said he wouldn't call himself a compulsive gambler, but
admitted he gambled away most of his paychecks.
   ``I gamble because I enjoy it,'' he said. ``This is the first
time I've ever withdrawn something from the Palace Station.''
   Originally from Lancaster, Pa., Sarbaugh came to Las Vegas eight
years ago and has lived on the streets for most of that time. He has
no family in town and says he's been estranged from his two sons for
years.
   Sarbaugh said he may give some money to charity and perhaps take
a trip to the Bahamas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
