<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;LFraud     02-07 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Fraud,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plan Would Add S&amp;L Fraud Investigators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-S&amp;Ls Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's proposal for a $50 million
program to combat fraud in the savings and loan industry would
enable immediate deployment of extra investigators to probe 200
pending cases, the Justice Department says.
   ``If this were approved, these people could get right on the
job'' investigating some 200 cases of suspected savings-and-loan
fraud, David Runkel, a spokesman for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, said Monday.
   ``We need more people _ there is no doubt about it,'' Runkel said
after Bush announced that he will ask Congress to appropriate $50
million a year to set up a task force to investigate S&amp;L fraud.
   Bush proposed the ``financial institutions special team'' as part
of his broader plan to raise deposit insurance premiums to help
finance the $100 billion bailout of the troubled thrift industry.
   The $50 million, which must be approved by Congress, would
support deployment of ``a couple of hundred additional FBI agents''
and 80 to 85 more federal prosecutors assigned to S&amp;L fraud, Runkel
said.
   The extra people ``would double in general terms the criminal
division's field investment into this kind of activity,'' Runkel
said.
   After he took office last summer, Thornburgh sought a briefing on
the savings and loan crisis and ``as a result of that briefing
obtained a specific assessment of need,'' Runkel said.
   ``This $50 million was a response to that request by the
department to go after fraudulent activity,'' Runkel said.
   Runkel estimated that about 200 cases of savings-and-loan fraud
either are being investigated by the Justice Department or have been
reported to federal authorities. These include cases ``where we have
some suspicion or we have reason to believe'' that fraud occurred,
he said.
   Runkel declined to say how many of the 200 cases are under active
investigation.
   The special team envisioned by Bush would absorb two separate S&amp;L
fraud units that have investigated alleged wrongdoing by thrift
industry officials in Texas and Oklahoma.
</TEXT>
