<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     02-07 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Performs `Idomeneo'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMer planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Opera, which first performed
Mozart's ``Idomeneo'' in 1982 starring Luciano Pavarotti, brought it
back Monday night, without Pavarotti. Judging by the number of
people who left before it was over, ``Idomeneo'' isn't going to fare
too well without a superstar.
   There is beautiful music in the opera, which Mozart composed when
he was 24, but it's in the style of its time _ 1781 _ with little to
break up the long solo arias.
   The late Jean-Pierre Ponnelle, who designed the production, sets
and costumes, did a marvelous job. The backdrops look like gray
etchings, often serving as screens for projections of the watchful
stone face of Neptune, the sea god Idomeneo betrays.
   Center stairs are flanked by side stairs and pillars. The chorus
comes and goes with finesse and singers move around. Nobody just
stands and sings.
   Still, without superstar talent, nearly four hours of this bores
many modern operagoers, although conductor David Stivender shapes
the music beautifully.
   Siegfried Jerusalem, often featured in Wagnerian operas, sings
Idomeneo. His voice has splendid qualities, full, rich, shot through
with colors.
   He sounded wonderful in the first act Monday night but by Act 2
it was clear that his voice isn't really flexible enough for the
part. He was having to work hard and experiencing difficulties.
   A voice needs to stay clear and true on the long lyric lines of
this music plus sing ornamentation.
   Carol Vaness was the stylist of the evening, sailing through the
music with ease and grace. She sang Elettra, who loves Idomeneo's
son Idamante. But Idamante loves Ilia, sung on Monday by Marvis
Martin, with lovely tone and not enough volume.
   Idamante, written to be sung by a woman, was assigned to
Frederica von Stade, who was ill with the flu. She was replaced by
another top-drawer mezzo-soprano, Susan Quittmeyer. She had some
difficulty with pitch.
   This season, the Met is using a different version of ``Idomeneo''
than last time it staged the opera, in the 1985-86 season. Based on
the Munich premiere of 1781, with a couple of exceptions, it takes
three arias out, puts two arias and a recitative in and leaves one
aria the way Mozart revised it in 1786.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890207-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-FirstCrisis     02-07 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-First Crisis,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bringing in Congress Early Helps Bush with First Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush appears to be weathering the
first crisis of his presidency without jeopardizing his honeymoon
with Congress.
   Bush had warned that any proposal he devised for bailing out
insolvent savings and loan institutions ``would not be popular,''
but the plan he outlined Monday is winning respect if not enthusiasm
from Democrats and Republicans.
   Now that the first concrete legislative proposal to issue from
the Bush administration has given the president a chance to prove
his leadership, attention shifts to the larger challenge: his budget
address to Congress on Thursday.
   ``We're still waiting for the other shoe to drop,'' said Norman
Ornstein, a political analyst at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute. ``So much is going to revolve around the
budget that right now it is more of a test.''
   Bush's bailout, announced after consultation with top financial
aides and leading members of Congress, calls for increased insurance
fees on banks and savings and loans and the issuance of $50 billion
in special bonds to finance the cost of failing institutions.
   Absent is a controversial earlier proposal the administration
floated for a direct fee on depositors.
   However, when pressed on the subject at a news conference, Bush
conceded there was no way of guaranteeing that the insurance
increase wouldn't be passed along to depositors.
   ``Nothing is without pain when you come to solve a problem of
this magnitude,'' Bush said.
   His plan also would increase the Justice Department's budget by
$50 million to ``seek out and punish'' those whose mismanagement of
S&amp;Ls Bush blamed for much of the problem.
   Bush's plan, according to some analysts, was a relatively
skillful recovery from the awkwardness two weeks ago when his
administration's consideration of a direct fee on depositors became
known.
   A firestorm of criticism followed, both on Capitol Hill and from
the industry. And the criticism did not abate after some top
administration officials, including Chief of Staff John Sununu, kept
the controversy simmering by suggesting publicly that the fee
remained a live option.
   Steve Hess, an analyst on the presidency at the Brookings
Institute, a liberal research organization, said Bush's
self-proclaimed decision to ``face the problem squarely'' even
before his budget speech was ``an effort to regroup.''
   ``It wouldn't have happened had not his administration bungled it
last week,'' Hess said.
   Still, Hess said, Bush's relations with Congress remain good. But
``there's always a honeymoon when there's nothing on the table,'' he
said. ``It may end up as a two-week honeymoon.''
   Bush called his proposal ``the fairest system that the best minds
in this administration can come up with.''
   But, by including congressional budget leaders early on in the
process of developing the scheme, Bush gave the first solid evidence
of his inaugural address vow to extend ``an offered hand'' to
Congress.
   And, for that gesture, members of both parties voiced their
appreciation.
   ``I think the proposal is by and large a sensible proposal,''
said Sen. Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee.
   Rep. Trent Lott, R-Miss., predicted: ``The major portion of it
will fly.''
   And Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, exclaimed, ``I think you're going
to see some real bipartisanship here.''
   But Gramm added that, even though he supported the president's
approach, any answer to a multibillion-dollar problem wasn't
something you'd want to embrace and ``kiss on the mouth.''
   ``We have a big selling job,'' Bush conceded on Monday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers The White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
