<DOCNO> AP890207-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     02-07 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>T-Bill Rates Close to Four-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the latest auction to the highest level in nearly
four years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 8.57 percent, up from 8.33
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.53 percent, up from 8.39 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since March 18, 1985, when three-month
bills sold for 8.64 percent and April 8, 1985, when six-month bills
averaged 8.56 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.88 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,783.40 and 9.04 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,568.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 9.05 percent
last week, up from 8.97 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
