<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PayProcess     02-07 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Process,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pay Commission Established in 1967 to Take Congress off the Hot Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To help take themselves off the hot seat on the
pay issue, Congress in 1967 established a nine-member Commission on
Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries.
   The commission's job is to recommend to the president every four
years the appropriate pay levels for members of the House and
Senate, federal judges, the president and vice president, and the
top layers of executive-branch workers.
   Three members of the panel are appointed by the president, two by
the president of the Senate, two by the speaker of the House and two
by the chief justice. Their recommendations could be accepted,
rejected or modified by the president, who then includes his final
recommendations in the budget he submits to Congress.
   Under the procedure, unless both the House and Senate vote to
head them off, the recommended raises become law 30 days after the
president proposes them.
   This year's recommendations for a 51 percent pay raise for
members of Congress, and similar increases for other top federal
workers, came from a commission chaired by Lloyd Cutler, a
Washington attorney and former White House counsel to President
Carter.
   Cutler was appointed to the panel by President Reagan, along with
former postmaster general Preston R. Tisch and William Agee,
president of Morrison, Knudsen Corp.
   The president of the Senate _ then-vice president George Bush _
appointed former Sens. Thomas F. Eagleton, D-Mo., and Charles McC.
Mathias, R-Md., to the panel. Appointees of House Speaker Jim Wright
were John J. Creedon of the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. and
former Rep. William R. Ratchford, D-Conn. Chief Justice William
Rehnquist appointed James Lynn of Aetna Life &amp; Casualty Co. and Carl
Humelsine of the Colonial Williamsburg Foundation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
