<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-07 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips In Tokyo, Another Record Stock High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against the Japanese yen
today, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index climbed to yet
another record high.
   The dollar closed at 129.50 yen, down 0.20 yen from Monday's
129.70-yen finish. After opening at 129.37 yen, it stayed in a
narrow range between 129.30 yen and 129.55 yen.
   ``There was nothing going on in the Tokyo market today,'' said
Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank.
   He said market players were merely making small position
adjustments following dollar-selling intervention by central banks
in New York and Europe.
   Other Asian markets including Hong Kong and Singapore were closed
for the Chinese Lunar New Year holiday, which also prompted a
wait-and-see mood in Tokyo, he added.
   Singapore's market reopens Wednesday, Hong Kong's on Thursday.
   ``Although the market lacked incentives today, speculative
investors showed strong dollar-buying interest,'' Kinugasa said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added
51.90 points, or 0.16 percent, closing at 31,880.65, its third new
high in three consecutive trading days.
   Profit-taking selling in the afternoon check the index's rise
somewhat today, however.
   Stability in the currency market encouraged buying by individual
and foreign investors, said a dealer with a major securities firm in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In active trading, with first section volume estimated at 1.8
billion shares, construction issues, such as cement, were among the
gainers.
</TEXT>
