<DOCNO> AP890207-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-07 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Georgia decides to adopt one legislator's idea
of a state rock 'n' roll song, it'll be easy to remember the chorus:
``A wop bop alu bop a wop bam boom.''
   State Rep. Billy Randall said he planned to introduce a
resolution today to make Little Richard's ``Tutti Frutti'' the
state's official rock song.
   Georgia already has an official state song _ ``Georgia On My
Mind'' by Ray Charles. But Randall said he'd like to see the state
recognize some of its native rock 'n' roll pioneers.
   ``I chose Little Richard because he was the first of the great
rock 'n' roll stars to come out of the state of Georgia,'' the
legislator said. ``Little'' Richard Penniman, 53, was raised in
Macon, which Randall represents.
   ``I love the idea,'' Little Richard, who now lives in California,
said in a telephone interview Monday. ``Give my love to him
(Randall) and everybody there. God bless you.''
   ``Tutti-Frutti,'' a nonsensical tune that was Little Richard's
first big hit, reached No. 2 on the rhythm and blues charts in 1955
and later achieved classic status as a rock standard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicist Ed Wagner says he's found
evidence that trees talk to each other. If so, they probably say
nicer things than other scientists say about him.
   Wagner, who left academia to start his own research laboratory,
says trees ``talk'' in signals that he calls ``W-waves.''
   Explaining the phenomenon, Wagner pointed to a blip on a chart
recording a tree being chopped. ``It put out a tremendous cry of
alarm,'' he said. ``The adjacent trees put out smaller ones.''
   An abstract of his research was published last fall in Northwest
Science magazine.
   Wagner, 58, holds a doctorate in physics from the University of
Tennessee. He formerly worked at the Oak Ridge National Laboratories
in Tennessee and taught physics at California State Polytechnic
University for five years.
   He returned to his family home near Grants Pass in the 1970s to
establish the Wagner Research Laboratory ``so no one could tell me
what I was doing scientifically was right or wrong.''
   Wagner said his work has been greeted with skepticism, but he
remained confident it would be accepted one day.
   ``For some people, it's so contrary to what they think that they
won't bother to read the evidence,'' he said. ``But it's just a
matter of time.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baltimore County Judge Dana Levitz got to
thinking about the ancient philosophical question: Who will judge
the judges? So he asked the lawyers who appear in his courtroom to
do it.
   Levitz's effort to get evaluated _ which included sending 150
questionnaires to lawyers who have appeared before him _ was
prompted by his worries about how attorneys can change when they sit
on the bench.
   ``They can become pompous jerks in black robes,'' said Levitz,
40, who was a county prosecutor before he became a circuit judge
three years ago.
   ``I wondered if they were aware of it, and then when I got here,
I realized how easy it is to become unaware. There's no other job
where there's no supervision.''
   County bar association president Myles F. Friedman praised
Levitz's survey as ``fantastic'' and ``long overdue.'' But there was
no indication that the idea was going to catch on among Levitz's
colleagues.
   ``I care what they think of me as a judge, but I wouldn't do
it,'' said Judge Leonard S. Jacobsen. ``I don't think it does any
good that way.''
   Levitz said he feels ``very positive'' about the 60 responses
he's received so far. Some opened his eyes to problems he wasn't
aware of, he said.
   ``For those judges interested in evaluating their skills, I think
this is an excellent vehicle,'' he said. ``For those who aren't
interested, it wouldn't help.''
</TEXT>
