<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineDoctor     02-07 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Doctor,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milton Reder, M.D.: Doctor Nose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It apparently helped Marvin Mitchelson's
headaches, Sonny Bono's sciatica, Whitey Ford's sore shoulder and
David Brenner's bad back, but medical officials say prescribing
cocaine for pain has no place in medicine.
   The state has told Dr. Milton Reder and 20 other physicians to
stop prescribing what's called sphenopalatine ganglion block.
   But Reder, who developed the method, said Monday he won't quit.
   ``These days cocaine has a bad name. What can I do about that?''
he asked. ``I say it's the best local anesthetic.''
   Brenner, the comedian, accused the state Health Department and
the New York County Medical Society of ``a witch hunt. ... They
can't get Noriega, they can't get the crack dealers a few blocks
away, but they're going after an 89-year-old humanitarian.''
   For four decades, Reder has used cocaine, legally purchased from
pharmaceutical companies, to treat a variety of maladies. A liquid
solution containing 13 percent cocaine is applied with metal swabs
inserted through the nostrils against a nerve center at the base of
the brain. Reder, his patients, and some doctors say the procedure
relieves pain, although no one knows why.
   Reder's treatment was no secret. He has participated in medical
studies and been the subject of newspaper and magazine features,
which invariably focus on his many celebrated patients.
   The state Health Department's objections are these: Reder doesn't
always examine patients before treating them; he doesn't make sure
they are not former cocaine addicts who might become addicted again;
and he employs too much cocaine.
   Reder said that most of his patients have been examined many
times before they come to him, and that he does examine those who
have not. And he says he administers too small an amount of the drug
to hook anyone.
   He vigorously denied a Daily News report that state investigators
``found about a half-dozen patients who went to Reder's office just
to get high.''
   Thomas Coffey of the Health Department said ``prescribing cocaine
for non-specific pains is like taking a sledgehammer to a tack.''
   The state cites the New York County Medical Society's conclusion
in 1975 that Reder's procedure has ``no basis in scientific medicine
to warrant its use.'' But the society also conceded that the
procedure ``appears to help some patients'' and urged it be studied.
   Such an experiment is in fact planned by two Yale Medical School
pain specialists who say they have used Reder's method successfully
on two of three patients.
   Reder came to the attention of the Health Department because of
his large orders of pharmaceutical cocaine. After an investigation,
the department on March 1 ordered him and the other physicians to
stop the treatments.
   At first Reder agreed, but later wrote the department a letter
saying he had changed his mind and wanted the medical society to
review its opinion. In a statement Monday, the society said that in
1987 its peer review committee reconsidered and affirmed its 1975
ruling on the procedure, and planned no change. It also said it was
not considering legal or disciplinary action against Reder.
   State officials say they are still investigating and won't move
against Reder until they confer with the medical society.
   Meanwhile, Reder's patients stand by their man.
   Bono, who was treated for a pinched sciatica nerve, said: ``I
guarantee you'd get less drugs from him than you would from a
general (doctor).''
   Film critic Rex Reed, another Reder patient, said: ``You don't
feel stoned, you feel better. Wouldn't you rather give somebody $25
in cash and feel better than spend thousands of dollars and have no
results.''
   Ford, the former New York Yankees pitcher, said saloonkeeper
Toots Shor took him to Reder for treatment of a sore shoulder, which
felt better the next day. He said he didn't know the physician had
used cocaine.
   Mitchelson, the divorce lawyer who credited Reder as the only
doctor able to relieve his headaches, said: ``I've seen people go in
there crippled, in wheelchairs, and walk out.''
   Other patients, Reder says, have included Pablo Picasso, Henry
Fonda and Winston Churchill.
   Reder said Monday that news of the state investigation, which
appeared Sunday in the Daily News, had already brought him new
patients.
   ``They all want to be cured,'' he said. ``I'll treat them as long
as they let me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
