<FIRST>r a PM-Cocaine-MedicalUses     02-07 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Medical Uses,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Used Routinely By Doctors As Local Anesthetic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cocaine Doctor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine is used routinely by doctors as a local
anesthetic, and patients often don't know they have received it, an
anesthesiologist said.
   It is most commonly used to deaden nerves in the nose before
inserting a tube through a patient's nose into the airway, said Dr.
Kuntala Sinha, an anesthesiologist and director of the pain clinic
at New York University Medical Center.
   It is also used by plastic surgeons when doing nasal surgery. It
is dispensed as a liquid solution and applied inside the nose with
swabs, she said Monday.
   Cocaine's advantage over other local anesthetics such as
lidocaine is that it also constricts blood vessels, Sinha said.
``When you pre-treat the patient with cocaine, it serves a dual
purpose,'' she said.
   ``It will decrease the bleeding (by shrinking the blood vessels),
and it increases the size of the (nasal) passage because it
decreases the size of the blood vessels in the area. It makes it
easier to put in a large tube without bleeding. And, number two, it
is a very good local anesthetic.''
   Cocaine is a controlled substance, so it is kept locked in
hospital pharmacies and is given out only in limited quantities,
Sinha said.
   She said that anesthesiologists routinely administer doses three
or four times higher than those used by Dr. Milton Reder, who has
been ordered by the state to stop administering cocaine to treat
pain. And even at the higher doses, the cocaine does not produce a
``high,'' Sinha said.
   ``Patients have consistently never even known about it,'' she
said. Even when the patients are told they're getting cocaine ``they
don't get a false high,'' she said.
   Reder's treatments differ from standard medical practice in that
he uses cocaine to treat pain in places other than the nose, Sinha
said.
   She said that she has experimented with treatment similar to that
used by Reder, and she has found that it helps about half of the
patients who receive it. Furthermore, patients do not appear to
become addicted, she said.
   ``I don't think there's a problem with addiction, if that's what
the public is worried about,'' she said. ``The question is whether
it works and if you see side effects.'' Medical journals contain no
reports of serious side effects, she said.
   ``There probably is a role for this kind of treatment,'' she
said, referring to Reder's methods. ``It's probably not accurate to
dismiss it as a crazy idea.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
