<FIRST>r a PM-HighSeasSlaying     02-07 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High Seas Slaying,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Smuggler Acquitted of Murder on High Seas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An admitted drug smuggler accused of
killing a woman, then ordering her tied to an anchor and thrown
overboard off the Bahamas, was acquitted of murder on the high seas
by a federal jury.
   William ``Skip'' Walton of Delray Beach was acquitted Monday in
the death of Brenda Blum, 37, of Fort Lauderdale, during a
drug-smuggling trip six years ago.
   The foreman of the U.S. District Court jury said afterward that
the panel didn't believe the testimony of the government's two chief
witnesses, who admitted they participated in the killing.
   ``The government didn't prove its case beyond a reasonable
doubt,'' said foreman Louis Agnello of Pembroke Park. ``It was very
frustrating because there was no body, just the testimony of those
two witnesses.''
   Walton, 46, pleaded guilty to marijuana importation and
conspiracy charges before the start of the trial two weeks ago. He
seemed momentarily stunned at the verdict announcement, then smiled
and patted his attorney, Don Ferguson, on the shoulder.
   ``His reaction was relief,'' Ferguson said. ``All along he's
maintained his innocence.''
   Walton was quickly led away from the courtroom by U.S. marshals.
He will remain in custody without bond until his March 13 sentencing
on the drug charges.
   Walton, who was cleared of murder charges 15 years ago in an
unrelated case, faces a maximum 10 year prison sentence for the drug
charges. He would have faced a mandatory life sentence if convicted
of murder.
   Prosecutors said Walton forced Ms. Blum aboard his yacht, beat
her with a club and then ordered her tied to an anchor and thrown
into the Atlantic on Dec. 2, 1982.
   William Pryor, the boat's first mate, said he helped dump Ms.
Blum's body into the water after she demanded a share of the drug
cargo. He agreed to testify against Walton and plead guilty to a
reduced charge of second-degree murder.
   David Nesbit, Ms. Blum's friend, testified that Walton ordered
the woman thrown overboard and threatened to kill him if he didn't
participate. But after he was granted immunity from prosecution, he
testified he lied to authorities when he reported the murder.
</TEXT>
