<FIRST>r a PM-PanAmFamilies     02-07 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am Families,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families of Crash Victims Demand Resignation of FAA Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of relatives of Pan Am Flight 103 victims
has demanded the resignation of the head of the Federal Aviation
Administration, saying he failed to maintain security on the doomed
flight.
   At an emotional news conference Monday, 30 people who lost loved
ones on the downed jetliner accused the government and Pan Am of
negligence before the Dec. 21 bombing. They demanded the broadest
possible congressional investigation of the tragedy that killed 270
people.
   ``My husband was murdered on the flight,'' said a tearful Wendy
Giebler, widow of William Giebler Jr. ``He never would have got on
that flight if we had been given the facts. And what we need to know
is who is accountable.''
   The group chiefly demanded an accounting of why the government
had not made public a terrorist threat that a U.S. flight from
Frankfurt, West Germany, would be bombed in December. U.S. airlines
and embassy personnel were warned.
   ``The FBI says, well, the bomb threat was really nothing more
than a hoax,'' said Daniel Cohen, of Port Jervis, whose daughter was
aboard Flight 103. ``If it was a hoax, why did that plane blow up?
Why is my daughter dead?''
   Government officials have said they get similar unconfirmed
threats on a daily basis and would cripple the airline industry by
announcing them all. The relatives called that policy ``immoral and
possibly criminal.''
   Further, the group said in a statement that while the FAA
receives up to 500 threats annually, fewer than 25 are rated
``high-level,'' as it said the Frankfurt threat apparently was.
   The relatives specifically blamed FAA chief Alan McArtor for a
lack of security on the flight, and called for his resignation. They
asked Congress to make its investigation of the incident ``full and
complete.''
   An FAA spokesman did not return two telephone messages. Pamela
Hanlon, a Pan Am spokeswoman, noted that the threat had not
identified a specific flight and she said Pan Am had increased its
security after receiving the warning.
   In an outpouring of emotion and frustration, the relatives voiced
a litany of other complaints, ranging from their inability to
recover their loved ones' personal effects to the handling of the
victims' remains.
   The New York-bound flight, which originated in Frankfurt and
changed to a larger plane in London, exploded over Lockerbie,
Scotland. All 259 aboard died, as did 11 on the ground.
Investigators blamed plastic explosives that had been smuggled
aboard.
   Among the dead were 35 students returning from a Syracuse
University overseas study program. Syracuse announced plans Monday
to convert the university's main entrance into a memorial to the
students.
   The centerpiece of the $500,000 memorial will be a 4-foot-high,
semicircular limestone wall on which the names of the students will
be engraved, according to Virginia Denton, Syracuse's director of
design and construction. She said the project is to be completed by
fall.
</TEXT>
