<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-US     02-07 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-US,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Accepts Contra-Linked US Diplomat As New Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari has told the United States it would accept the appointment
of controversial career diplomat John Negroponte as the next U.S.
ambassador.
   Opposition leaders in Mexico say they oppose the choice of
Negroponte because he helped orchestrate the civil war in Nicaragua
and meddled unduly in Honduran affairs while ambassador to that
country from 1982 to 1985.
   Late Monday, the Foreign Ministry said it had sent a letter to
the Bush adminstration expressing support for the proposed
appointment of Negroponte, currently a deputy national security
advisor.
   The White House has not announced Negroponte's candidacy for the
job, but sources in Washington said last week that he would be
picked to replace Ambassador Charles Pilliod.
   As U.S. envoy to Honduras, Negroponte had a major role in
assisting the U.S.-backed Contra rebels seeking to overthrow
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinistas. Honduras was a major base of Contra
operations.
   In a statement, the Foreign Ministry said:
   ``By sending this letter, the government of Mexico expresses to
the United States of America its desire that this career diplomat be
chosen, contributing to the strengthening of bilateral ties with
equality and strict respect for the sovereignty of both countries.''
   It said Negroponte's designation would be ``within the spirit of
the declarations'' President Bush and Secretary State James Baker
have made concerning the future of relations between the United
States and Mexico.
   Negroponte, 50, was a close ally of the former head of the
Honduran armed forces, Gen. Gustavo Alvarez Martinez, known as the
godfather of the Contra movement.
   Alvarez, armed forces chief from 1982 until his overthrow in
1984, was shot to death in the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa last
month. A leftist group claimed responsibility.
   As head of the national police in 1981, Alvarez told then-CIA
Director William Casey that the Contras could operate from Honduran
territory, thus allowing the movement to grow. A preliminary
cease-fire was signed by the warring Nicaraguan parties last March,
but peace talks have since stalled.
   Mexico City daily newspapers have reacted angrily to Negroponte's
possible appointment.
   The daily Excelsior on Friday ran a lengthy front-page story
describing Negroponte as a diplomat who ``has earned a reputation
for being more astute and calculating than Machiavelli.''
   The liberal daily La Jornada called Negroponte's appointment ``an
ominous decision'' and compared him unfavorably to former Ambassador
John Gavin, who was extremely unpopular in Mexico City.
   La Jornada also began a three-part series Thursday on Negroponte
called ``The Path of an Ultra-Hawk.''
   Negroponte began his diplomatic career in Hong Kong in the early
1960s. He served in the U.S. Embassy in Saigon during the Vietnam
War and was a member of the U.S. negotiating team at the Paris peace
talks on that conflict.
   Later, Negroponte served at the U.S. Embassy in Quito, Ecuador,
and was a consul general in Greece.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
