<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Newman     02-07 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Newman,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Academy Award Winner Lionel Newman Dies At Age 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lionel Newman, who composed, conducted or
supervised the scores of more than 250 movies, including ``Hello,
Dolly,'' for which he won an Oscar, has died. He was 73.
   Newman died of a heart attack Friday at Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center, publicist Chuck Panama said.
   Newman's 11 Oscar nominations included for scoring the music of
such films as ``Doctor Doolittle,'' ``Mardi Gras,'' ``Let's Make
Love'' and ``The Pleasure Seekers,'' among others. His also wrote
the score for ``Love Me Tender,'' during which Elvis Presley made
his film debut, and conducted the scores for ``Cleopatra,'' ``Planet
of the Apes,'' and ``The Omen.''
   He shared the Academy Award with Lennie Hayton for musical
adaption of Jerry Herman's score of ``Hello, Dolly,'' the 1969 movie
that starred Barbra Streisand.
   Born Jan. 4, 1916, in New Haven, Conn., Newman moved to Hollywood
when he was a teen-ager. His first job was conducting for the Earl
Carroll Vanities, where he met his wife, Beverly Carroll.
   The musician then worked as Mae West's piano player until he
joined 20th Century Fox in 1943 as a rehearsal pianist. He remained
with Fox for more than 40 years.
   His first major hit was the song ``Again'' from the movie
``Roadhouse.''
   Newman, who in his later years at Fox oversaw the musical
segments for motion pictures and television, resigned in 1985. But
two years later he joined MGM-UA with similar responsibilities.
   Many of Newman's relatives were also active in the entertainment
industry, including his nephew, pop singer and songwriter Randy
Newman.
   In addition to his wife, Newman is survived by a brother three
sisters and three daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
