<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-07 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower in early European trading
today, pressured by Monday's central bank intervention and the
absence of many traders celebrating holidays in Asia and West
Germany, currency dealers said.
   Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the market was uncertain and a bit jumpy following
Monday's dollar sales by seven European central banks, the U.S.
Federal Reserve and the Bank of Canada.
   They said that while the sales seem small, the appearance of the
central banks confirmed their resolve to keep the dollar from
climbing too high.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.20 yen to a closing 129.50. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 129.58 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8693 West German marks, down from 1.8810
   _1.5885 Swiss francs, down from 1.5969
   _6.3620 French francs, down from 6.3950
   _2.1093 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1200
   _1,364.75 Italian lire, down from 1,370.50
   _1.1825 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1840
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7368, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.7345 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $391.75 a troy ounce, up
from $388.95 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $391.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $391.30, up from $387.50 bid late
Monday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.91 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.82.
   Financial markets are closed in Hong Kong until Thursday for the
Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations. Workers in parts of West
Germany were participating in carnival celebrations.
</TEXT>
