<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Great Lakes, Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow was falling in the Great Lakes and the Southwest and
freezing rain stretched from the Appalachians to Texas' Gulf Coast
after another day of record-breaking cold.
   Forty-one cities tied or set record lows Monday in 10 states,
mainly between the Pacific Coast and the Rockies. They included Ely,
Nev., where a reading of 30 degrees below zero was the lowest
temperature ever recorded there.
   Snow reached from northern New York state across the Great Lakes
region to Minnesota and North Dakota. Buffalo, N.Y., received 5
inches in the six hours that ended at 1 a.m. EST.
   Snow also was falling in northeast New Mexico and the Texas
Panhandle.
   Freezing rain was falling over parts of the Virginias, Tennessee,
Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and the lower Texas Gulf Coast. Rain
was scattered from southeast Louisiana to North Carolina.
   Winter storm warnings and advisories for sleet and freezing rain
have been posted from the southeast Texas, Louisiana, much of
Mississippi and northwest Alabama.
   Advisories for snow squalls have been posted over portions of
western and northern New York state. A snow advisory was issued for
southwest and south central New Mexico, and freeze warnings were
posted for southwest Arizona and the valleys and lower deserts of
Southern California.
   Today's forecast called for snow with some sleet scattered across
much of Arkansas, Tennessee and Kentucky, and freezing rain along
the Texas Gulf Coast and over interior portions of Louisiana and
Mississippi. Light snow was forecast to extend from Montana across
the Dakotas and northern Minnesota to Upper Michigan, and from New
York state to northern New England.
   Highs were expected to be in the teens in the central and
northern Rockies and in much of Nevada, Utah and Idaho; in the teens
and 20s in much of the Great Plains, the upper and middle
Mississippi Valley, the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes and northern
New England; in the 50s in the Desert Southwest and Southern
California; in the 50s and 60s from southern Alabama to much of
Georgia and the Carolinas; and in the 70s and lower 80s in southern
Georgia and Florida. Most other areas were expected to have highs in
the 30s and 40s.
   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 37 degrees below zero at
Craig, Colo., to 75 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 42 drizzle; Boston 30 cloudy; Buffalo 18 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 64 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 14 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 11 snow; Miami 73 fair; New York 34 cloudy; Philadelphia
32 cloudy; Pittsburgh 17 cloudy; Portland, Maine 20 cloudy;
Washington 35 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 13 fair; Chicago 7 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 21
fair; Denver 0 fair; Des Moines 3 fair; Indianapolis 8 snow; Kansas
City 6 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 6 fair; Nashville 20 partly
cloudy; New Orleans 36 drizzle; St. Louis 8 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 12 cloudy; Anchorage 16 cloudy; Las Vegas 23
fair; Los Angeles 42 cloudy; Phoenix 35 fair; Salt Lake City 7 fair;
San Diego 47 cloudy; San Francisco 34 fair; Seattle 27 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 18 cloudy; Toronto 18 cloudy.
</TEXT>
