<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StrandedDancers     02-07 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stranded Dancers,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ballet Troupe Stranded By Investor Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A troupe of 59 Soviet ballet dancers is stranded
at a hotel here, its 15-city U.S tour stalled until the producer
either finds enough money to continue or sends the dancers back home.
   The Donetsk Ballet was scheduled to move on to Detroit Monday.
But after big-name guest stars from major companies failed to appear
with the troupe last week, U.S. and Mexican investors reportedly
withdrew their backing.
   Producer Jan Urdzik said Monday that she had until today to find
other investors.
   ``We've not made an announcement that we've canceled. We're still
working on some things,'' Ms. Urdzik said.
   In the meantime, the Howard Gilman Foundation in New York said it
would advance the dancers' living expenses for a week.
   The Lyric Opera House, where the Ukrainian troupe put on five
performances before half-empty houses, has paid for three days'
worth of lunches for the troupe, and the theater's wardrobe staff
bought fruit for the dancers.
   ``Locally, they are being treated very well. All kinds of offers
of help have come in,'' said Tim Kroneberger, the theater's building
manager.
   Ms. Urdzik said the dancers have return tickets to Moscow and
that if the tour is canceled they will be put on flights back home.
</TEXT>
