<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedMarine 1stLd-Writethru a0511 02-07 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Marine, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Marine Found Negligent In Lance Corporal's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT spelling of `Mojave' and RESTORE
first reference to Rother. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, ``I'm just ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second Marine has been convicted of
negligence in the death of a soldier who had been left behind in the
Mojave Desert during a training exercise last summer.
   Sgt. Thomas Turnell was found guilty Monday and demoted to lance
corporal, the same punishment given last week to another sergeant in
the death of Lance Cpl. Jason Rother.
   Turnell was found innocent of two other counts _ the more serious
charge of failure to obey a lawful order and a lesser charge of
unauthorized absence.
   ``I'm just glad it wasn't any harder on my family,'' Turnell said
as he left court.
   The military jury deliberated about two hours before returning
the verdict.
   Turnell was accused of failing to follow the policies of his unit
by being absent without authorization for two days during Rother's
disappearance. He also was accused of negligence for failing to
account for the whereabouts and welfare of Rother, 19, of
Minneapolis, who was a member of Turnell's squad.
   Rother was left behind after being posted as a road guide for an
exercise at Twentynine Palms, Calif., on Aug. 30. His remains were
not found until December.
   Turnell's superior, Sgt. Christopher Clyde, was found guilty of
negligence last week for allowing Turnell special time off and for
failing to account for his men.
   In testimony Monday at Turnell's trial, Clyde acknowledged having
given Turnell permission to take two days' liberty.
   In closing arguments, Capt. Robert Nunally, the prosecutor, told
the jury that Turnell was only concerned with his two days' off, not
the whereabouts of Rother.
   ``If he had cared, or asked one question, maybe we wouldn't be
here today,'' Nunally said.
   But Turnell's civilian attorney, Guy Garand, said the
disappearance was not entirely the fault of his client.
   ``There are many people who are responsible for this incident,''
Garand said. He said there was poor communication in the entire
company, a reflection of poor leadership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
