<FIRST>r i PM-Zambia-Floods     02-07 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zambia-Floods,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Torrential Rains Leave 20,000 Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding caused by torrential rain has left
20,000 people homeless in Zambia's capital, Lusaka, a ruling party
official said today.
   Bautis Kapula, a senior member of the ruling United National
Indepedence Party, appealed to the government to provide emergency
assistance for people whose mud houses were washed away in
torrential rain Monday.
   He said $30,000 was needed to buy relief supplies for families
being housed in churches, schools and shelters in the city
showground.
   On Monday, police reported two children drowned in a water-filled
pothole during Zambia's heaviest rains in 10 years.
   Most of the destroyed houses were built from bricks of hardened
mud under a state self-help scheme allowing city dwellers to build
their own homes without adhering to standard building regulations.
It was an effort to relieve a chronic housing shortage.
</TEXT>
