<FIRST>u a PM-PreacherSentencing     02-07 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preacher Sentencing,0262</SECOND>
<BYLINE>REPEATING</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Evangelist Sentenced in Sodomy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An evangelist who admitted molesting at least
100 boys along the Southern revival circuit since the 1960s was
sentenced to 2{ years in prison today for sodomizing two teen-agers.
   ``I suppose the thing that troubles me most is somebody of the
cloth, who knows the truth, has openly and flagrantly lied,'' Judge
Kenneth Trabue told Mario ``Tony'' Leyva. ``There was an overt
effort to poison the jury on your behalf.''
   Leyva, a Pentecostal preacher from Columbus, Ga., testified at
his trial in state court in September that he never had sex with
children, but he later told the FBI he had sexually abused at least
100 boys beginning in the 1960s.
   Leyva took the stand briefly this morning and said he had lied at
his trial.
   He had faced up to 10 years on the state charges, but the jury
recommended 15 months for each count of child sodomy, and the judge
could not impose a higher sentence, said Assistant Commonwealth's
Attorney Randy Leach.
   In October, Leyva pleaded guilty to federal charges of conspiracy
and shipping minors across state lines for prostitution.
   Federal prosecutors said Leyva and two fellow preachers for years
used the Tony Leyva Evangelistic Association Inc., based in
Columbus, to gain access to boys for sexual purposes. The three
preachers are awaiting sentencing.
   Under the plea bargain, prosecutors will seek a maximum of 20
years in prison.
</TEXT>
