<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Violence 1stLd-Writethru   02-07 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0478,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist, Moslem Guerrillas Ambush Government Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to UPDATE with details of today's ambush;
picks up 4th graf pvs: ``Also Monday...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurgents killed at least 10 people,
including soldiers and a farmer, in three ambushes, the military
said today.
   Maj. Cayetano Ordinaria, army regional spokesman, said eight
Moslem guerrillas today attacked an army truck en route to market in
Bubong in Lanao del Sur province, about 510 miles southeast of
Manila.
   Three soldiers, including a lieutenant, were killed and two were
injured, he said. A farmer who was inspecting a nearby ricefield
also was killed by stray bullets, Ordinaria said.
   The guerrillas have been fighting the government for 17 years,
but the rebellion has tapered off in the past few years to
occasional skirmishes with government troops.
   On Monday, four government soldiers were shot to death when about
50 guerrillas of the communist New People's Army ambushed a truck
near the town of San Luis in Nueva Ecija, about 70 miles northeast
of Manila, a military report said. The report said two soldiers were
wounded.
   Also Monday, suspected communist rebels shot and killed a
Philippine constabulary major and his aide in an ambush in Rizal
province on the outskirts of the capital, the military said.
   It said an undetermined number of rebels in a truck fired at a
vehicle carrying Maj. Antonio Manalo and Sgt. Julian Guitan. They
were killed and another soldier was wounded.
   Manalo was the commanding officer of the 225th Philippine
Constabulary company based in Rizal province.
   The communist rebels have been waging a 20-year insurgency.
</TEXT>
