<FIRST>r a PM-LonesomeDoveRatings     02-07 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lonesome Dove Ratings,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lonesome Dove' Takes Top Spot in Weekly Ratings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first installment of CBS's ``Lonesome Dove''
was the highest-rated show of the week.
   Sunday night's premiere of the four-night Western drama had a
28.5 rating and a 42 share and was the highest-rated start for a
miniseries so far this season, according to A.C. Nielsen figures.
   Monday night's episode dropped in the overnight ratings from the
nation's 17 largest markets, getting a 20.2 rating and 29 share. But
the episode's ratings are expected to increase considerably when
figures from rural areas become available.
   Sunday night's installment had a 34 share in the overnights and a
42 share nationally.
   ``Lonesome Dove,'' starring Robert Duvall, Tommy Lee Jones and
Anjelica Huston, is based on the 1985 Pulitzer Prize-winning novel
by Larry McMurtry. It airs through Wednesday.
   NBC's movie ``The Sex Tapes,'' which ran against ``Lonesome
Dove'' on Sunday, was 25th in the ratings, with a 16.2 rating and 24
share.
   On Monday, NBC put up its highest-rated comedies, including
``Golden Girls,'' ``Empty Nest,'' ``Cheers'' and ``Night Court.''
They averaged a rating of 18.6. ABC's ``Columbo'' had an overnight
rating of 18.0.
   The national rating is a percentage of the 90.4 million U.S.
homes with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in use.
</TEXT>
