<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Barbara Tuchman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Tuchman, 77, a two-time Pulitzer
Prize-winning author of popular histories, died Monday after a
stroke.
   Tuchman began her writing career as an editorial assistant and
occasional correspondent for The Nation, which her father,
investment banker Maurice Wertheim, bought in 1935 to save from
bankruptcy. She covered President Roosevelt's 1936 campaign and the
Spanish Civil War.
   During World War II, Tuchman worked for the U.S. Office of War
Information.
   She wrote 11 books, winning the Pulitzer Prize for ``The Guns of
August'' in 1962 and ``Stilwell and the American Experience in
China'' in 1971.
   Tuchman's ``The First Salute,'' which looks at the American and
Dutch revolutions, has been on The New York Times best-seller list
