<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 2ndLd-Writethru a0540 02-07 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0540,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Complete Dress Rehearsal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with rehearsal complete. PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `Discovery was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's five astronauts completed
a successful practice countdown in the spaceship today as
technicians worked to replace three engine pumps in time to meet a
mid-March launch date, NASA said.
   Wearing bulky space suits, the crew of the 28th shuttle mission
entered the cabin for the final two hours of the rehearsal, which
concluded at 11:37 a.m., 37 minutes late because of minor
communications and computer problems.
   ``Everything appears to have been successful for today's terminal
countdown demonstration test,'' said NASA spokeswoman Lisa Malone.
   The countdown test, which began Sunday, duplicated much of the
actual count except that the fuel tank was not loaded and some
procedures were shortened.
   Discovery was powered up and its electronic, communications and
other systems were checked. The communications satellite to be
deployed by the crew was loaded in the cargo bay on Monday.
   As the countdown progressed, technicians at the base of the
launch pad continued removing the oxygen turbopumps from Discovery's
three main engines. The first was pulled Monday, and the second came
out early today.
   They will be replaced as a precaution because of two tiny cracks
discovered in the shuttle Atlantis after its flight in December.
Discovery has identical pumps.
   The repairs delayed the launch from Feb. 23 until March 10 at the
earliest. Officials said last week that if Discovery could not get
off the only available launch pad by March 18, the mission might
have to be delayed for months.
   That's because the next shuttle mission, that of Atlantis, must
take place between April 28 and May 28 in order for its crew to
dispatch the Magellan spacecraft to orbit Venus, which will not come
into proper position again until 1991.
   Astronaut Mike Coats, commander of the Discovery mission, said
Monday he is confident about a mid-March launch.
   ``We were discouraged about a week ago, because the first
analysis indicated it might take too long a time to get the new
pumps and that there would be no way we could launch in March,'' he
said. ``Now everybody we've talked to is very optimistic. We're
confident they've got a good fix on it now.''
   Arnold Aldrich, NASA national space transportation system
director, said in Washington on Monday he is certain of launching
Discovery without affecting the Atlantis launch.
</TEXT>
