<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Narcisse     02-07 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Narcisse,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Self-Styled Religious Leader with National Following Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis H. Narcisse, a flamboyant religious leader
who dressed in royal finery, was regarded as a king by his followers
and adopted as his motto ``It's nice to be nice,'' has died at age
67.
   Narcisse, who died of a heart attack Friday at Mount Carmel Mercy
Hospital, wore robes and a crown, carried a golden staff and was
known as His Grace.
   At church events and funerals, a red carpet would be rolled to
his Mercedes-Benz or Rolls-Royce.
   Narcisse bought a $3.5 million, 42-room mansion soon after he
moved to Detroit in 1971, said his son, the Rev. Prince Narcisse.
   In keeping with his motto, Narcisse allowed the homeless into his
mansion, and his churches led national relief efforts for the hungry.
   He was born and raised in Gretna, La., and ordained by
Metropolitan Spiritual Churches Inc. before his 1945 founding of
Mount Zion Spiritual Temple in Oakland, Calif.
   In 1956 in Oakland, Narcisse was crowned a king by bishops from
the Church of God in Christ and the Church of God. He built churches
in New Orleans, Sacramento, Orlando, Houston and Baton Rouge, the
younger Narcisse said.
   In 1987, Mayor Coleman Young gave him an Award of Merit.
   Funeral services will be Thursday.
</TEXT>
