<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Contras     02-07 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Contras,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Accused Of Planning Contra Commander's Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men arrested in the killing of a
Nicaraguan rebel commander admitted to roles in the assassination,
and one of them said the killing was planned by the Nicaraguan
Embassy in Honduras.
   Nicaragua today denied the accusation.
   Luis Fernandez Ordonez Reyes, one of three men under arrest in
the case, said Monday that he was a go-between for the Nicaraguan
Embassy security chief and a former Honduran police officer accused
in the Jan. 7 killing of Manuel Rugama, a commander of the
Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras.
   ``The plan to eliminate Rugama was prepared by the Nicaraguan
Embassy in Tegucigalpa,'' Ordonez said at a news conference
organized by the Honduran military.
   ``Luis Fernandez Ordonez Reyes' accusations are ridiculous and
completely removed from the truth. The embassy has no security
chief. We deny all involvement by our embassy in the assassination
of the Contra chief,'' Nicaraguan Embassy spokesman Juan Jose
Membreno said today by telephone.
   The Contras have blamed the Nicaraguan government for Rugama's
slaying. They said Rugama was to meet with other Contra leaders on
the day he died.
   Ordonez identified the Nicaraguan Embassy security chief as Jose
de Jesus Pena, and said he introduced Pena to one of Ordonez's
employees, Rigoberto Matute, a former police detective.
   Ordonez, a Nicaraguan who operated a money exchange in
Tegucigalpa, said Pena often visited his business and paid him
between $500 and $1,500 for information about anti-Sandinista rebels
in Honduras.
   Membreno denied that anyone named Jose de Jesus Pena worked for
the embassy.
   The other man presented at the news conference was Juan Bautista
Nunez Amador.
   Bautista Nunez said Matute told him he would pay Bautista Nunez
$20,000 to help in the killing. ``I was the first to fire at
Rugama,'' Bautista Nunez said.
   He said Matute and a third man he knew only by the last name Cano
Arteaga then joined in killing Rugama.
   Matute, Bautista Nunez and Ordonez are being held in the killing.
There was no indication why Matute did not attend the news
conference.
   Rugama apparently was alone when he was shot as he drove on a
highway west of the Honduran capital. Officers found his body on the
road. They said he had been shot 26 times.
   A doctor, Rugama had been a Contra for nine years and was one of
the organization's regional commanders.
</TEXT>
