<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--JerseyAds     02-07 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Jersey Ads,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soccer Club Wins Case to Advertise Condoms on Jerseys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soccer club on Tuesday won the
right to advertise condoms on its jerseys.
   The Frankfurt civil court ruled that the ads on the shirts of the
FC Homburg soccer team don't represent an ethical violation.
   The case went to court after the West German Soccer Federation
ruled last fall that FC Homburg was violating ``the basic principles
of ethics and morals in sport'' by advertising the brand name of the
London condom company on its uniforms.
   But in its decision in favor of the team, the court ruled against
that, saying ``morals have fundamentally changed'' in the past two
decades.
   The court also cited a federal Health Ministry campaign promoting
the use of condoms for safer sex. The court said the Health Ministry
advertising was much more direct in promoting condoms than the team.
   The ruling will permit the FC Homburg players to wear the
jerseys, which are inscribed with the brand name of the condoms
outlined by a double circle. The word ``condom'' does not appear.
   German soccer jerseys already advertise electronics goods, dairy
goods and other products.
</TEXT>
