<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IndianInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0430 02-07 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with testimony; picks up 8th graf pvs, MacDonald
Jr.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A friend of Navajo tribal chairman Peter
MacDonald Sr. said today he paid MacDonald thousands of dollars in
cash and gifts for arranging purchase of a 750,000-acre ranch and
that the chief participated in a cover-up of the transaction.
   Byron T. ``Bud'' Brown testified before a special Senate
committee that MacDonald asked him for $25,000 and a $55,000 BMW
automobile in exchange for arranging an inflated purchase price for
the Big Boquillas Ranch.
   Testifying with immunity from criminal prosecution, Brown told of
being wired by investigators in order to tape conversations he had
with MacDonald about the cover-up. He said the cover-up scheme began
after an investigation of the ranch sale by the local U.S. attorney.
   Brown arranged for the ranch to be purchased from Tenneco Corp.
for $26.2 million by businessman Tom Tracy and then sold immediately
to the Navajos for $33 million. Under the deal Tracy, Brown and
MacDonald split the $7.2 million profit, Brown testified.
   A portion of the MacDonald payment was made in $5,000 cash
increments by Brown, he said. The cover-up involved a $25,000
payment and the BMW car, Brown said.
   On Monday Peter MacDonald Jr. recounted the same story to the
committee, which is a special panel of the Senate Select Committee
on Indian Affairs. The cover-up called for the junior MacDonald to
be the recipient of the $25,000 and the car as a way of protecting
his father, he testified.
   The junior MacDonald also testified under immunity. His father
has not testified nor has he been told that he would get immunity if
he did testify, the committee staff said.
   The senior MacDonald's involvement in the ranch sale is being
investigated by a grand jury in Arizona. There also is a movement
underway by the Navajos to remove the senior MacDonald from his
$55,000-a-year job as chairman on the
   A Senate investigator, Eugene Twardowicz, gave the committee
documents Monday showing that the purchasers of the land had
incurred expenses in 1987 including the $25,000 loan to the
chairman, a $4,000 down payment for the leased car and two $900
monthly installments for the automobile.
   The younger MacDonald said he, his father and Brown met about
five times in 1988 to work out their story that MacDonald Jr. had
sought the loan and the car.
   MacDonald Jr., 33, said allowing it to appear that MacDonald Sr.
sought the money and the car ``looked bad,'' since Brown was
involved in the Boquillas deal. He said it was his father who asked
him to go ahead with the coverup.
   Asked by committee counsel Kenneth Ballen why he allowed himself
to become involved in the concocted story, MacDonald Jr. said,
``Because I love my father.''
   A Senate investigator who asked to not be identified said
planning to give a false story to authorities is illegal and could
qualify as obstruction of justice, obstruction of a congressional
investigator and conspiring to commit perjury.
   Brown and Tracy purchased the ranch for $26.2 million in July
1987 from the Tenneco West Co. Brown also received a $750,000
commission from Tenneco. The two men then sold the land to the
Navajo tribe for $33.4 million _ either the same day or a day or two
later, according to Twardowicz.
   Twardowicz said that based on his investigation of the finances
of Brown and Tracy, he believed the men could not have afforded to
buy the land from Tenneco unless they knew they would soon sell it
to the tribe.
   ``They had to know they coul flip _ when I say flip, I mean
re-sell it _ for a much higher amount, which they did,'' said
Twardowicz.
   Brown received 59 percent of the sale's profits and Tracy got 41
percent, according to a copy of the agreement between the two men
that Twardowicz gave the committee. The deal netted Brown $5 million
and Tracy $3 million, Twardowicz said.
   The investigator told the committee that Brown paid for a
November 1986 trip to Hawaii that MacDonald took with his family,
shortly after he was re-elected chairman of the Navajo.
   Twardowicz also said Brown signed a one-year, $5,500-per-month
consulting contract with MacDonald Jr. The chairman's son said that
agreement was merely a part of the coverup, designed to make Brown's
loan more plausible.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a committee member, said the land deal
was ``a questionable, if not fraudulent, transaction.''
   Another panel member, Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said, ``In
essence, the Navajo people paid $8 million more than they had to,
assuming they wanted the property in the first place.''
   The committee launched its hearings last week, following reports
of alleged fraud in The Arizona Republic.
   The panel has come under criticism by Indians for aiming its
probe at accusations against Navajo leaders rather than problems
within the Bureau of Indian Affairs and other government agencies.
   Richie Nez, MacDonald Sr.'s chief of staff who was attending the
hearing, told reporters afterward that ``this was a normal real
estate transaction,'' and that the Navajo thought the $33 million
acquisition was a good one.
   Asked if the alleged favors influenced the tribe's decision to
buy the land, he said, ``I can't comment on that.''
</TEXT>
