<FIRST>u w PM-Sullivan-HHS 1stLd-Writethru a0458 02-07 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan-HHS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0458,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Gives Up Severance Pay to Head HHS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs with hearing set for Thursday; picks up at pvs 4th
graf, A hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confirmation hearings for Cabinet nominee Louis
Sullivan, who put out a potential brush fire by deciding to forfeit
nearly $300,000 from his medical school presidency, will begin
Thursday, the White House said today.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the FBI had
completed its background check of the secretary-designate of health
and human services and found ``no adverse information as far as we
know.'' He said the White House expects Sullivan will be confirmed.
   The administration had asked Congress on Monday to set a new date
for Sullivan's hearing, a sign that it was satisfied with the
nominee's financial disclosure and FBI background investigation.
   A hearing scheduled last week by the Senate Finance Committee had
been postponed after the White House asked for a delay, citing
incomplete financial information from the nominee and an unfinished
FBI background check.
   But Sullivan's decision to take an unpaid leave of absence and
forgo $297,000 in severance pay from Morehouse School of Medicine in
Atlanta, the school he founded and heads as president, put his
hearing back on track and earned him praise on Capitol Hill.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said Sullivan's decision ``shows a major personal
commitment to public service.''
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said he admired Sullivan for not
taking the money, but he said people should not be pressured to give
up money to which they are legally entitled.
   ``We have so much pressure in the government, only those born
with two gold spoons in their mouth will be able to serve around
here pretty soon,'' he said. ``It is impossible for me to understand
this pressure that comes on people who were not born wealthy and who
have earned a certain right.''
   The White House had told Sullivan that if he cut his ties with
Morehouse, he could accept $297,000 in severance pay under terms of
his contract with the school, and Sullivan was prepared to do that,
according to a senior administration official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   But the nominee became concerned when news reports cast the
arrangement ``in an unfavorable light'' and raised questions about
potential conflicts of interest since Morehouse receives federal
funds from HHS, the officials said.
   Sullivan felt he was ``taking a beating in the press,'' decided
``on balance it was just not worth it,'' and told Morehouse he would
forfeit the severance pay, the official said. Instead, he would
resign as president and take an unpaid leave of absence as a
professor of medicine.
   As president of Morehouse, Sullivan earned an annual salary of
$172,000. As head of the largest federal department, he will make
$99,500. A pay-raise measure that was headed for defeat in Congress
today was to raise that to $155,000.
   Sullivan, who wants to keep his house in Atlanta while he is in
Washington, plans to borrow money while his wife, a lawyer, plans to
go back to work so they can make ends meet, the official said.
   The official said Sullivan ``simply accepted this as unfortunate,
but this is a cost of becoming part of the government.''
   Though Sullivan's decision to forgo the money surprised many in
the nation's capital, ethics officials say it is not unusual for
people entering government to give up large sums of money due them
from former employers.
   ``There are government people who give up unbelievable sums to
take government positions ... because they are afraid it could
create a problem for them,'' said Don Campbell, deputy director of
the Office of Government Ethics.
   However, others at Sullivan's level do take large sums from
former employers, including ``deferred income'' that was earned
before they came to the government.
   For example, the new agriculture secretary, Clayton K. Yeutter,
last year while he was U.S. trade representative received $561,602
from the Chicago Mercantile Exchange for an annual installment for
deferred earnings plus the after-tax proceeds of a lump sum
distribution. Yeutter had been president of the exchange before
joining the Reagan Cabinet.
   Sullivan, however, feared that the controversy over a paid leave,
in the wake of an outcry by conservative lawmakers over his
statements on abortion and the FBI's focus on his connection to a
Georgia politician convicted of extortion, could affect his
reputation and the credibility of the Bush administration, the
administration official said.
</TEXT>
