<HEAD>Argana Rules Out Presidential Bid, Endorses Rodriguez</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to UPDATE with Argana endorsing Rodriguez,
ruling out a delay of the elections; EDITS throughout to tighten; CHANGES
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Luis Maria Argana said
today he will urge the official Colorado Party to endorse coup
leader Andres Rodriguez for president in the national elections set
for May 1.
   Argana, who had been considered a front-runner for the office,
said at a news conference that he backed ``my friend'' Gen.
Rodriguez, who on Friday ousted dictator Gen. Alfredo Stroessner.
   There was no immediate response from Rodriguez.
   Asked Monday if he might be a candidate, Rodriguez said: ``It is
every Paraguayan's duty to serve his country. Being president is a
great honor. If I am called to serve, I will.''
   Colorado Party officials plan to hold a convention to select
candidates for president, the 72-member House of Deputies and the
36-member Senate.
   Opposition leaders, many of whom were exiled during Stroessner's
presidency and whose parties were banned, have asked that the
election be delayed to give them time to prepare. Argana ruled that
out.
   ``The period of time is imposed by the national constitution and
is the maximum,'' he said. ``The opposition itself has no interest
in extending the deadline because by extending the deadline we also
extend the arrival of democracy.''
   On Monday, Rodriguez issued a decree dissolving Congress.
   He said the new government would serve until August 1993, the
term of office for elections that were held in February 1988. Only
the Communist Party would be banned from fielding candidates,
Rodriguez said.
   Rodriguez, at his news conference Monday, denied rumors that he
is involved in drug trafficking, saying they ``were spread by people
trying to defame me.''
   He said Paraguay, reputedly a major transit point for cocaine,
would crack down on narcotics trafficking and cooperate in
international anti-drug campaigns, including those of the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration.
   Rodriguez also denied reports that as many as 300 people died the
coup. He said the dead and wounded together did not exceed 50.
   He promised democratic reforms shortly after taking power Friday,
but the opposition expressed skepticism about his hasty calling of
elections.
   ``I personally can't even be a candidate for anything because I'm
not registered'' to vote, said Domingo Laino, a former political
exile and leader of what is thought to be Paraguay's biggest
opposition group, the Authentic Radical Liberal Party.
   ``Our people are not registered'' either, he said, because
Stroessner outlawed the party.
   Stroessner, now in exile in Brazil, ruled Paraguay for nearly 35
years after seizing power in a 1954 coup.
   Laino suggested the May 1 election date ``could be interpreted as
a trap'' set by the Colorado Party, which after 41 years in power is
rich and well-organized.
   He also said one solution to the voter registration problem would
be to instead use the national identity card that all citizens are
required to carry.
   In setting the election date, Rodriguez cited a constitutional
clause stating that in the event of a president's resignation,
incapacitating illness or death, the provisional president must call
for elections within three months.
   The government's position is that Stroessner resigned.
   The Colorado Party, with 1.4 million members, counts on an
extensive political machine that extends to the smallest towns in
the countryside.
   The electoral code mandates that the party that gets the most
votes is entitled to two-thirds majority in the House and Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
