<FIRST>r i AM-GraveDesecrated     02-07 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grave Desecrated,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grave of Ben-Gurion, Israel's Founding Father, Desecrated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals believed to be Jewish extremists painted
swastikas and a Jewish star on the tombstone of David Ben-Gurion,
Israel's founding father and first prime minister, an official at
the memorial site said Tuesday.
   ``I was shocked,'' Motti Aberjil told Israel radio. ``Nothing
like this has ever happened.''
   The desecration apparently occurred Monday night and was
discovered by a gardener Tuesday, said Aberjil, deputy director of
the Ben-Gurion seminary the Sde Boker communal farm in the Negev
desert.
   Ben-Gurion, who died in 1973, is buried at Sde Boker, where he
had a home. The site also has a seminary that researches his works.
He was Israel's premier for 12 years after the nation was founded in
1948.
   Aberjil said the graffiti was signed ``Keshet,'' the name of a
Jewish extremist group that has attacked several secular Israeli
targets recently.
   Police arrested 10 suspected members of the group in Jerusalem on
Sunday in connection with bombings and arson attacks.
   Keshet members also are suspected of planting three firebombs on
the Jerusalem-Tel Aviv highway Dec. 31, apparently to disrupt
traffic on the sabbath, when religious Jews do not drive. The bombs
were found before they exploded.
   The group has been linked to desecrations of graves of other
Israeli leaders in Jerusalem. Ultra-Orthodox Jews believe a Jewish
state should exist only after the Messiah comes, and perform such
acts to show their contempt for the Zionist state.
   Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek, who worked with Ben-Gurion for more
than 35 years, said he felt ``shock and sorrow'' over the
desecration.
   ``I say with a heavy heart that they have gone far too far,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
