<SECOND>AM-BRF--Spain-Canaries,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snowfall in Canary Island Spares Coastal Zones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS PALMAS, Canary Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow covered the central
mountains of Grand Canary, but it stayed comfortably warm in coastal
tourist regions of this Spanish island off northwest Africa.
   Chief meteorologist Guillermo Rivero said it snowed Monday at
altitudes as low as 4,000 feet, while in Las Palmas, the capital,
and other coastal regions, temperatures dipped no lower than 59
degrees.
   ``Aside from the wind, which made the day less pleasant than
usual, the weather was normal,'' he said. ``There was some sleet in
Las Palmas, but that's not unusual this time of year.''
   On Tuesday, Las Palmas skies were partly sunny and daytime
temperatures topped 68 degrees.
   TV reports that it was the worst snowfall in 30 years were
exaggerated, Rivero said, although the snowline was much lower than
usual in the mountains, where snow was up to 8 inches deep.
