<FIRST>r a AM-LowHigh     02-07 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Low High,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town's `High' Lower Than `Low'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high temperature in Canyon de Chelly in
Arizona's northeastern corner was 4 and the low was 11, the National
Weather Service reported Tuesday.
   And that's not too unusual, forecaster Mike Franjevic said. He
noted a recent day when the high temperature in Phoenix was in the
50s and the low was in the 60s.
   Highs and lows are keyed to clock time as well as the weather, he
explained.
   The high for a day is the highest temperature reached from
midnight to midnight. The high from midnight Sunday to midnight
Monday was 4 in Canyon de Chelly, he said, noting that the previous
low was minus 5. Then after midnight, Tuesday morning, the low up to
the end of the first reporting period, 8 a.m., was 11.
   It happened because clouds moved in and there were some snow
flurries, reducing heat loss through radiation and the clouds
perhaps even reflecting some back, allowing the temperature rise,
Franjevic said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
