<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Legionnaires     02-07 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Legionnaires,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Briton Dies of Legionnaires' Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man has died in an outbreak of Legionnaires'
disease that has struck seven other people in central London, health
officials said Tuesday.
   Another 19 cases are suspected, but there was very little risk
anyone else would be infected, said environmental health officer Dr.
Deidre Cunningham.
   The outbreak was confined to an area southwest of Leicester
Square, where water samples were taken from 17 cooling systems, she
said. Most of the systems were shut down voluntarily, and those
operating have been cleaned and disinfected, she said.
   Waterborne bacteria that cause the pneumonia-like disease occur
in soil and water found in air conditioning ducts, storage tanks and
rivers.
   Ms. Cunningham and Dr. John Gabbay, medical officer in charge of
the investigation, said the victim died two weeks ago, but they did
not say why it was not announced until Tuesday.
   Gabbay said six patients are hospitalized, two in intensive care.
The seventh is recuperating at home.
   Between 100 and 200 cases of Legionnaires' disease are reported
each year in England and Wales.
</TEXT>
