<SECOND>AM-Box Office,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Three Fugitives' Tops `Rain Man' for No. 1 Spot at Box Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The comedy ``Three Fugitives'' has dethroned
1989 box-office champion ``Rain Man'' after the film about two
brothers learning about one another spent five weeks atop the movie
charts.
   According to figures released Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.,
``Three Fugitives,'' an action-comedy with Nick Nolte and Martin
Short as two bank robbers on the lam, grossed $5.48 million during
the weekend. ``Rain Man,'' the road movie featuring Dustin Hoffman
and Tom Cruise, took in $5.45 million.
   In third place was the new quasi-comedy ``Her Alibi,'' starring
Tom Selleck and model Paulina Porizkova in a did-she-or-didn't-she
murder mystery.
   Though critically panned, the film collected $5 million in its
opening weekend. It was followed in fourth by the drama ``Beaches,''
with Bette Midler and Barbara Hershey playing best friends, on
grosses of $4.2 million.
   ``Who's Harry Crumb?,'' a detective spoof starring John Candy as
an intrepid investigator, collected $3.9 million in its first week
of release to claim fifth place. ``Twins,'' a comedy about
non-identical twins played by Danny DeVito and Arnold
Schwarzenegger, finished in sixth place on ticket sales of $3.3
million.
   In seventh was the corporate success story ``Working Girl,''
starring Melanie Griffith, which collected $2.54 million. It was
pursued by the civil rights drama ``Mississippi Burning,'' in eighth
on grosses of $2.48 million.
   The Top 10 was rounded out by the crime comedy ``The Naked Gun:
From the Files of Police Squad!'' in ninth with receipts of $1.9
million and the moody romantic drama ``The Accidental Tourist'' in
tenth with sales of $1.5 million.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release. The figures for ``The Naked Gun'' are estimated.
   1. ``Three Fugitives,'' Disney, $5.48 million, 1,191 screens,
$4,591 per screen, $13.6 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $5.45 million, 1,573 screens,
$3,465 per screen, $96.3 million, eight weeks.
   3. ``Her Alibi,'' Warner Bros., $5 million, 1,429 screens, $3,524
per screen, $5 million, one week.
   4. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $4.2 million, 1,109 screens, $3,744 per
screen, $25.9 milion, seven weeks.
   5. ``Who's Harry Crumb?,'' Tri-Star, $3.9 million, 1,197 screens,
$3,227 per screen, $3.9 million, one week.
   6. ``Twins,'' Universal, $3.3 million, 1,610 screens, $2,080 per
screen, $90.8 million, nine weeks.
   7. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.54 million, 1,133
screens, $2,240 per screen, $41.7 million, seven weeks.
   8. ``Mississippi Burning,'' Orion, $2.48 million, 1,074 screens,
$2,305 per screen, $18.3 million, nine weeks.
   9. ``The Naked Gun,'' Paramount, $1.9 million, 1,258 screens,
$1,509 per screen, $71 million, 10 weeks.
   10. ``The Accidental Tourist,'' Warner Bros., $1.5 million, 756
screens, $2,036 per screen, $24 million, seven weeks.
