<FIRST>u a PM-TurnpikeExplosives 1stLd-Writethru a0521 02-07 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turnpike Explosives, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Terrorist Zigzagged Across 10 States, Authorities Said</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with sentencing hearing under way, color
and quotes; No pickup. Changes byline; PM lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected Japanese terrorist zigzagged
across 10 states buying bomb parts and visiting a New York office
building he planned to blow up in retaliation for the 1986 U.S.
attack on Libya, authorities said today.
   Yu Kikumura, whose sentencing began this morning under extreme
security, was seen by witnesses inside the Veterans Administration
building that houses a Navy recruiting center in New York City,
state Trooper Joseph Fuentes testified.
   The site was marked by felt-tip pen on a map found inside the
man's car when the suspected member of the terrorist Japanese Red
Army was arrested carrying three powerful bombs on the New Jersey
Turnpike April 12, authorities said.
   Kikumara's attorney, civil rights lawyer, William Kuntsler,
objected to the testimony from Fuentes, a member of the joint state
and federal Terrorism Task Force, saying he should have the right to
question any eyewitnesses.
   But U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner Jr. said such testimony
was admissable.
   Kikumura, 36, faces up to 100 years in prison for transporting
and possessing explosives. He was convicted Nov. 29.
   Investigators said they used hotel and store receipts to track
Kikumura's travels through New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Michigan, Illinois, Missouri, Tennessee, Kentucky and West Virginia
before his arrest.
   FBI agent Thomas Thurman said the bombs would have resulted in
``mass casualties and destruction to the point of the doors being
blown out ... chairs and tables in the room would be picked up and
shattered.''
   He testified under questioning from U.S. Attorney Samuel Alito,
who was making a rare appearance as the lead prosecutor in the case.
   Security was tight as Kikumura was brought from jail in New York
City to the courthouse. Prosecutors said the Japanese Red Army might
seek to kill him.
   Authorities closed a lane of the Holland Tunnel between New York
and New Jersey for 15 minutes in the morning, said Armando Arrastia,
spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and Jersey.
   ``We do it for sensitive VIP movements,'' he said. ``We do it for
people who might be a target of some other group, or people who need
to move through quickly.''
   Extra metal detectors were set up near the courtroom, and police
carried rifles and shotguns as he was led into the courthouse.
   Alito alleges Kikumura's bombing was to have been carried out in
conjunction with the April 14, 1988, attack on a USO club in Naples,
Italy, that killed five people, including a U.S. servicewoman.
Kikumura was arrested two days before the Naples blast, which was on
the second anniversary of the U.S. air strike against Libya.
   Found in his car were 3-foot steel canisters packed with
gunpowder and lead shot, electrical fusing devices, clocks and
precision tools, authorities said.
   ``His objective was to strike, not any person or private group,
but at the United States as a nation,'' Alito said in a
pre-sentencing report.
   Kunstler and co-counsel Ronald Kuby said the report makes only
``tenuous'' ties between their client and other terrorist incidents,
and they asked for a sentence of less than three years in prison.
</TEXT>
