<FIRST>u a PM-Husband-Guardian 1stLd-Writethru a0587 02-07 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Husband-Guardian, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0587,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules for Husband In Case of Comatose Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail, quotes from judge and attorney.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today gave a man the right to
authorize an abortion on his comatose wife in hopes of helping her
recover.
   State Supreme Court Justice Bernard McCaffrey put an immediate
stay on his ruling until an appeal can be heard this afternoon from
two anti-abortion activists asking to be named legal guardians of
the woman and the fetus.
   The judge granted Martin Klein's request to be named legal
guardian for his wife, Nancy, enabling him to authorize an abortion
on the 32-year-old woman.
   Mrs. Klein is 17 weeks' pregnant and has been in a coma at North
Shore University Hospital in Manhassett since an auto accident Dec.
13. The hospital refused to allow an abortion unless Klein was named
his wife's legal guardian.
   During a two-day hearing last week, five medical experts for
Klein testified that pregnancy decreases the chances of recovery and
could threaten Mrs. Klein's life. That testimony was contradicted by
two other medical experts.
   ``Based upon the competent medical testimony and records, the
court finds that Nancy Klein is incapable of communicating and is
declared to be incompetent, and a guardian should be appointed on
her behalf,'' the judge announced today to a packed courtroom.
   ``If he so determines it be in the best interests of Nancy Klein,
(Martin Klein) may sign on her behalf any and all informed consent
and authorization forms for an abortion procedure,'' McCaffrey
continued.
   However, the judge said that testimony at the hearing convinced
him an abortion ``is not medically necessary to preserve the life of
Nancy Klein.''
   Two anti-abortion activists were to appear before an appellate
judge this afternoon to request a 24- to 48-hour stay until a full
appeals court can rule on the matter.
   Klein's attorney, Sidney Schutz, said his client was delighted
with the decision but wished it had been stronger.
   Klein, 34, of Upper Brookville, was accompanied by his in-laws,
Frederick and Anne Zusselman of Del Ray Beach, Fla., who supported
his motion for guardianship. He kissed and embraced his in-laws when
the ruling was handed down.
</TEXT>
