<FIRST>r a AM-ChangingHabits     02-07 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Changing Habits,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smokers Switch To Chewing Tobacco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACELAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The air may be cleaner since smoking during
City Council meetings was banned in November, but now the need for
spittoons is growing.
   ``They stopped smoking and people started chewing tobacco,'' said
Mayor Charles Clarke, who smokes two packs a day. ``That's worse
than smoking. You spill that and you've got a mess.''
   Raceland may be the first town to ban smoking in a public
building in Kentucky, which is the nation's leading producer of
burley tobacco, said Ed Griffin, director of the Kentucky Municipal
League in Lexington.
   There are no plans to regulate tobacco chewing, the mayor said
Tuesday. Two council members are among the chewers, who use any
handy container such as paper cups or soda cans rather than
old-fashioned spittoons in the council meeting room.
   Ron Morris, a regional vice president of the Tobacco Institute
based in Louisville, said he doesn't know of any other towns in
Kentucky that have such policies.
   ``Because of the agricultural importance in Kentucky, it would be
hard to get a policy in place and keep it,'' Morris said.
   Councilman Carl Traylor said he made the motion to institute the
ban for his own health as well as the health of other people. Taylor
said he underwent throat cancer surgery Dec. 30. The former smoker
said his doctor told him cigarettes were the cause of his cancer.
   ``I was taking radium treatments, and I would go to the council
meetings and I would get sick at my stomach,'' he said. ``My doctor
asked if there was a lot of smoking. He said that could be the cause
of it.''
   City Clerk Connie Phelps said the smoke was so bad ``You could
cut it with a knife. We had windows open and air conditioners on.
Nothing helped.''
   Councilman Jack Barker was the only council member to vote
against Traylor's motion, which passed Nov. 8 without discussion.
</TEXT>
