<HEAD>Suspect In Doctor's Slaying Had Picked Out Second Victim, Police
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs with Bellevue saying `Viola' is unknown.
PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Smith pleaded ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man accused of raping and strangling a
pregnant doctor at Bellevue Hospital told detectives he had a second
victim picked out, according to court papers.
   Steven Smith, 22, also told a detective that a ``voice'' ordered
him to kill Dr. Kathryn Hinnant, 33, on Jan. 7, and that she
wouldn't have died if he had received psychiatric help, according to
the detective's report.
   Smith told Detective David Argenzio that ``he had to do it and
that if we hadn't caught him, there would have been another
victim,'' said the report filed in court Monday during Smith's
arraignment.
   ``He said there was a girl known to him as Viola ... (on the 16th
floor of Bellevue) that was his age (who) could well have been his
next victim,'' the report said.
   Smith said he liked the woman, but she made him angry, according
to the report.
   Bellevue officials were unable to determine who that woman might
have been, hospital spokesman Jim Walsh said today.
   ``We asked around up there. Nobody knows of any Viola,'' he said.
   Smith pleaded innocent in state Supreme Court to charges of
murder, rape, sodomy and robbery.
   Argenzio spoke to Smith in the waiting room of the psychiatric
ward of Kings County Hospital on Jan. 9. Smith said that if someone
had given him psychiatric help, ``the lady would still be alive,''
the detective reported.
   Smith reportedly told police he came upon Ms. Hinnant while she
was working late alone in a lab. He said he punched her, robbed her
and strangled her with the help of a man named ``John,'' who then
raped her.
   Smith told Argenzio that the victim asked him why he was
attacking her.
   ``He stated to me, `It was just something I had to do,''' the
detective reported.
   Police said fingerprints and other evidence from Hinnant's office
indicate Smith acted alone.
   Defense lawyer Marvyn Kornberg consented to Smith's giving hair
and blood samples for DNA ``genetic fingerprinting'' tests to
determine conclusively whether he raped the woman.
   DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is a protein molecule found inside
each cell. Identifying a person's blood, semen or saliva through DNA
is virtually 100 percent accurate because each person's DNA pattern
is unique.
</TEXT>
