<HEAD>Bush Nominates Pennsylvania Native as Commander of Georgia Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has nominated Maj. Gen. John J.
Yeosock of the Army for a promotion and new assignment as the deputy
commanding general of the Forces Command, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   In that post, Yeosock also would serve as the commanding general
of the Third U.S. Army at Fort McPherson, Ga. The Forces Command is
responsible during peacetime for the training and equipping of Army
forces posted inside the United States.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Yeosock would receive his third
star and the rank of lieutenant general in moving to the new post.
   The 51-year-old Yeosock is a native of Wilkes-Barre, Pa., and
will replace Lt. Gen. Andrew P. Chambers. The Pentagon announced
Tuesday that Chambers plans to retire on April 1 after more than 34
years of active service.
   Chambers, 57, is a native of Bedford, Va.
