<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSDoctor     02-07 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Doctor,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Health Doctor Says He Has The Deadly Disease He Treats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Lee County's AIDS program has
revealed that he was diagnosed as having AIDS more than three years
ago, but says he'll continue to help his patients as long as he can.
   Dr. Adrian Pollock, 58, who is recovering from a type of
pneumonia associated with the deadly disease, said his decision to
publicly discuss his health came partly from a desire to make clear
that he didn't get AIDS from his patients.
   ``I was reaching a point where I knew I'd have to go public with
it,'' said Pollock. ``The higher power has a way of doing things his
way. This is when I'll find out who my friends are.''
   Pollock, who was married and has a daughter, said he got the
disease through homosexual activity, the most common means of
transmission, but doesn't know from whom.
   ``I had had a few (gay encounters),'' Pollock said. ``I guess
that's the irony of it _ there were so few _ but I have no idea when
or with whom and it doesn't really matter.''
   Pollock, director of epidemiology and communicable diseases for
the county health unit, was diagnosed as having AIDS 3{ years ago.
He said one of the things that has kept him going since then ``is
the feeling that I am doing something good for other people.''
   ``The only thing I know to do is to go ahead and do the best I
can to help the other people who are facing the same things I've
faced,'' he said Monday.
   Dr. William Hill, acting director of the county health unit, said
Pollock's diagnosis won't keep him from continuing to work.
   Pollock became ill in December with his first bout of
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, the most common killer of people
with acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which weakens a person's
immune system and leaves them susceptible to numerous infections.
   ``I went from July into early December with a chronic cough and
post-nasal drip. I thought it was just sinusitis; it's funny how you
can see things in other people you can't see in yourself,'' Pollock
said. ``I had done just what I tell the patients never to do _ I
tapered off on my pentamidine treatments.''
   Pentamidine is a drug that helps prevent pneumonia.
   Pollock has recovered enough that by last week he was back to
six-hour work days.
   Pollock, who worked as a pediatrician in private practice for 20
years before joining the health department, said he didn't know he
had the disease when he first became the county's AIDS surveillance
officer in 1985. He found out shortly afterward when he and a
co-worker decided to test themselves.
   Pollock hopes going public will help promote understanding about
AIDS.
   ``I think the important thing to get across is that I didn't go
out hunting for this disease,'' he said. ``People who have this
disease deserve the same compassion as anyone else suffering from a
terminal illness.''
   In 1987, the Fort Myers News-Press chose Pollock and Dr. Bob
Schwartz, a infectious disease specialist and president of the
Southwest Florida AIDS Task Force, as the region's ``Men of the
Year'' for their work with AIDS patients.
   ``When I tell people there's hope, I think of Adrian,'' said
Schwartz. ``I would hope there would be a flood of respect for him
after this is made public, but God knows what will happen.''
</TEXT>
