<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890207-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Soviet Bjt   02-07 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Soviet, Bjt,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Troops Reflect on Afghanistan's Cost</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOS16, MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MAZAR-I-SHARIF, Afghanistan (AP) _ Soviet soldiers likely to be
among the last to leave Afghanistan say their thoughts are turning
to loved ones, and to comrades who will never share the joy of
homecoming.
   Capt. Sergei Ofitserov of Moscow is dreaming of the son he never
has seen, born during his service in Afghanistan.
   Alexander Morozov, a talkative 23-year-old officer with bright
blue eyes, remembers a friend killed by rebel shelling in August.
   Vis Ali Chagaev, 20, is thinking of his parents' reaction when
they see the changes wrought in him by a year and a half in the
unfinished war.
   All of the troops interviewed Saturday in this outpost guarding
the withdrawal worry over the fate of Afghanistan after the last
Soviet soldier leaves, and whether the nine-year struggle has been
worth the lives of 15,000 comrades. They would not say when they are
leaving, but their positions guarding the rear make it likely they
will be among the last to leave.
   Just 35 miles south of the Soviet border, a few hundred soldiers
aimed heavy machine guns and armor across the flat landscape to
protect the Soviet supply route and final withdrawal.
   The area is quiet and under government control. But it isn't safe.
   ``At any time, any place, there could be an attack,'' said
Ofitserov, a 27-year-old Muscovite from a military family whose name
means ``officer.''
   Backers of the pro-Soviet Afghan government cannot agree on
whether it will be able to hold back U.S.- and Pakistani-backed
Moslem guerrillas, he said.
   ``The Afghans will have to work it out for themselves now,'' he
said. ``We will only get in the way.''
   All Soviet soldiers are to be withdrawn by Feb. 15 under an
agreement signed in Geneva by Afghanistan, the Soviet Union, the
United States and Pakistan in April 1988.
   At an outpost down the road from Ofitserov's unit, Capt. Arkady
Anonich, 30, said the Afghan army was weak in technical expertise
and suffered from low morale.
   Even in northern Afghanistan, near the Soviet border and one of
the areas under firmest government control, the local people
probably don't support the pro-Soviet government in Kabul, Anonich
said.
   The Soviet soldiers stayed away from Marzar-i-Sharif, a city of
170,000 people whose cold and muddy streets surround a magnificent
12th century mosque with blue mosaic walls.
   A few of the stores in Mazar-i-Sharif have Russian names like
``Spring,'' ``Dream,'' or ``The Birch Tree'' printed under their
Arabic names.
   But many of the rest retain English and Arabic signs, and the
area's strong traditions are evident.
   Few women are seen on the streets and fewer still without the
traditional Moslem veil.
   At a field near the airport on Fridays, dozens of horsemen play
the traditional game of buskashi, vying to snatch up a headless goat
and score by dropping it in a circle drawn on the ground.
   Anonich said the Soviet soldiers are not guarding Mazar-i-Sharif,
but its nearby roads and the territory surrounding the airport and
its 30 Afghan air force MiG fighters and Sukhoi ground support jets.
   Despite many complaints by Afghan veterans that their service is
ignored and that they don't fit in after they have returned home,
the soldiers on duty made clear that getting home was the main thing
on their minds.
   Asked what he wants to do, Chagaev said his only goal was to get
home.
   He has been able to send tapes to his parents, who will meet him
in the Soviet border town of Termez a week or so after he returns,
he said.
   Chagaev said he cannot judge how he has changed but that after
military service, a man's priorities are different. A youth has time
to be obsessed with music, but after army service, ``you start to
think about getting married, about a home,'' he said.
   In the Soviet Union, where military service is mandatory, ``it is
thought that if a man hasn't served in the army, he's not a man,''
Ofitserov said.
   A career soldier, Ofitserov would be marking his second
anniversary in Afghanistan two days after the last Soviet soldier is
to leave.
   He said he will be told his new assignment upon returning to the
Soviet Union but hopes first to see his 1{-year-old son, Valerian,
who was born after he left.
   Morozov, a native of Zagorsk, a town northeast of Moscow famous
for its monastery, is the commander of an armored attack vehicle dug
into the brown dirt in front of a mud fort built by Anonich's
soldiers in September.
   Four days after he arrived at Kabul airport to begin his
Afghanistan tour, he and a 42-year-old officer were trapped by
rebels shelling the airport. One shell landed about 20 yards from
Morozov and killed his fellow officer.
   ``We ate together, we lived together,'' he said of his friend,
whom he refused to identify out of respect for his memory. ``It was
completely by chance that I wasn't hit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
