<HEAD>Barbara Bush Visits Philadelphia To Highlight Reading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush read to about 75
elementary school pupils Tuesday, promoting literacy in her first
official visit outsdide Washington.
   Mrs. Bush, a longtime advocate of literacy programs, read from
``Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day'' by
Judith Viorst.
   The children joined in with the first lady during the refrain of
the story about a boy who faces a series of calamities: ``I could
tell it was going to be a terrible, horrible, no good, very bad
day.''
   During a short news conference, Mrs. Bush said Pennsylvania's
illiteracy rate of 29 percent was not unusual.
   ``That's not good enough,'' she said.
   Her reading audience included pupils in grades two through four
from Henry Lawton Elementary School at the Free Library of
Philadelphia as an area Read Together Coalition kicked off its third
annual ``Love Is Reading Together Week.''
   Sheila Whitelaw, executive director of Friends of the Free
Library, first invited Mrs. Bush in early December. She called
repeatedly during December, let up around Christmas and then tried
some more before the inauguration.
   ``The next thing I knew, they called me,'' Ms. Whitelaw said
Monday.
   She said the visit by Mrs. Bush, an advocate of literacy
programs, ``will add a lot of visibility to our program, to literacy
per se and to the focus of what we're trying to do.''
