<FIRST>r a AM-Contras-Linder     02-07 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras-Linder,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Say Linder Death Suit is Political, Not Legal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders Tuesday asked a federal judge to
throw out a $50 million wrongful death lawsuit filed by the family
of an American engineer slain by the rebels in Nicaragua.
   At a hearing on a defense motion to dismiss the case, attorneys
for the Contras told U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus he had no
jurisdiction in the case.
   ``It is not the court's role to determine what is legitimate or
illegitimate warfare,'' said defense attorney John E. Kirkpatrick.
   Benjamin Linder, 27, of Portland, Ore., was shot to death in
Nicaragua in April 1987 when U.S.-backed rebels attacked the rural
hydroelectric project he had volunteered to work on.
   A year later his family sued top Miami-based Contra leaders,
including three members of the current directorate, saying they
authorized a patrol to attack the project, as well as torture and
kill Linder.
   Kirkpatrick said Linder knowingly went into a war zone, and
contended the Linders' lawsuit was motivated by their opposition to
U.S. policy in Nicaragua.
   Outside the courtroom, David Linder, who contends his wounded son
was tortured with a needle to the face before finally being shot to
death, said politics did not enter the case.
   ``We don't consider the torture of our son, or the torture of
anyone, a political issue,'' Linder said.
   The Linders' attorneys disputed a defense contention that the
plaintiffs failed to show the engineer was specifically targeted by
the attack on the project.
   ``The targets were chosen in Miami. It was here the decision was
made to attack and kill Linder,'' said Michael Ratner of the New
York-based Center for Constitutional Rights.
   The judge said he would issue an opinion as soon as possible on
the dismissal motion, but did not give a date.
   The Linders' lawsuit, filed in April 1988, contends their son was
shot at close range by a Contra patrol raiding the hydroelectric
project.
   The action named several Contra leaders, including Nicaraguan
Resistance directors Adolfo Calero and Aristides Sanchez and
military leader Enrique Bermudez.
   The Contras have publicly contended Linder was carrying a weapon
at the time of his death and was shot accidentally in a firefight
between Sandinista militia and the rebels.
   However, The New York Times has reported that the Contras killed
Linder because they mistakenly thought he was a Cuban adviser to
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
