<DOCNO> AP890207-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BakerTrip     02-07 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker Trip,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary Of State To Visit All NATO Capitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Baker III's first foreign trip as
secretary of state will take him to the capitals of 14 of the 15
U.S. allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization in a whirlwind
outing designed to broaden his overseas experience and give the Bush
administration a peppy image.
   He does not intend to overlook the 15th country, Iceland, either.
Baker will stop at the Keflavik air base there for a brief session
with Foreign Minister Steingrmur Hermannsson in an airport lounge.
   Baker will cover a wide range of subjects, including East-West
relations and the outlook for arms control, in his meetings from
Canada to Turkey, but in visits so brief any substantive discussion
obviously will be limited.
   The eight-day trip will mostly get Baker's feet wet _ his
background in foreign policy is scant _ and set the stage for the
summit meeting President Bush and Baker will hold with leaders of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization in the spring.
   Announcing the schedule, Charles E. Redman, the State Department
spokesman, said Baker ``feels it's important to establish contact
with his NATO colleagues, to see them in this case on their home
territories.''
   Usually, talks between the secretary of state and his NATO
counterparts are arranged for NATO headquarters in Brussels with the
allies assembling there to see him.
   Baker sets out Friday with Bush for Canada and meets that evening
in Ottawa with Foreign Minister Joe Clark, even as Bush heads to a
weekend vacation in Maine after his own session with Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney. On Saturday, Baker and a retinue of assistants,
security guards and reporters will fly to Iceland for a few hours of
talks at Keflavik and, later, in London.
   On Sunday, Baker plans to meet with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and with Sir Geoffrey Howe, the British foreign secretary,
and then fly to Bonn for a late afternoon session with West German
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   Allegations that West German firms helped Libya try to produce
chemical weapons is a likely topic. Another is the outlook for talks
due to open in March between NATO and the Warsaw Pact on reducing
non-nuclear armed forces in Europe.
   Baker goes to Copenhagen on Monday to see Danish officials, flies
back to Bonn to spend the night in the West German capital, and
visits three countries on Tuesday _ Turkey, Greece and Italy.
   On Wednesday, the secretary of state goes to Spain and Portugal,
and then to Brussels for talks Thursday with Belgian officials and
with Manfred Woerner, the NATO secretary-general. The same day Bush
makes a quick trip to Luxembourg and The Netherlands and returns to
Brussels for meetings on Friday with leaders of the European
Community.
   Baker's last stop is Paris later Friday for talks with French
President Francois Mitterrand and Foreign Minister Roland Dumas. The
secretry plans to return to Washington Friday evening.
   Five days later, Baker will travel with Bush to Japan for the
funeral of Emperor Hirohito and to China and South Korea for talks
with representatives of those governments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
