<HEAD>Robert Shaw Named Indianapolis Bureau Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Shaw, Associated Press bureau chief in
Oklahoma City for five years, has been named bureau chief in
Indianapolis.
   AP President Louis D. Boccardi announced the appointment Monday.
   Shaw, 47, succeeds Andy Lippman, who recently was named bureau
chief in Los Angeles. Shaw will manage AP's news, photo and
newspaper marketing operations in Indiana.
   A native of Conway, Ark., Shaw began his journalism career on the
Arkansas Gazette in Little Rock. He joined the AP in St. Louis in
1965 and transferred to the Little Rock bureau the following year.
   Shaw was named correspondent in Memphis, Tenn., in 1973 and in
Jackson, Miss., two years later. He became a bureau chief in 1984
when he received the Oklahoma City assignment.
