<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Quake     02-07 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quake,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Robbers, Lack of Building Supplies Plague Rebuilding Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robbers have raided 52 freight trains hauling
earthquake relief supplies to Armenia, Tass said Tuesday.
   Residents of Stepanavan hoping to rebuild on their own are unable
to obtain building materials or discover who is allocating land. And
no one in Armenia is prepared for the imminent shortage of
electricity expected when a nuclear power plant is shut down for
fear of further quakes, the official news agency said.
   The reports were just the latest problems hobbling relief efforts
since the Dec. 7 earthquake that devastated northwestern Armenia and
killed more than 25,000 people.
   Thieves struck at least 52 freight trains bringing in goods to
Armenia, according to Usik Arutyunyan, Armenian minister of Internal
Affairs. Measures have been taken to increase security on the trains.
   Citizens throughout Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia will suffer a
shortage of electricity when the first unit of the Yerevan nuclear
power plant is shut down in two weeks, Tass said, quoting the
Politburo commission on earthquake relief. The commission considered
expanding the use of natural gas and complained that work is
proceeding too slowly on expanding the capacity of a thermal power
plant in Razdan.
   The commission also criticized the Armenian state construction
committee for inadequate management of the reconstruction of
quake-ravaged towns, and for the Stepanavan residents' problems in
undertaking their own rebuilding projects.
   The Stepanavan City Council also was cited for poor organization
of relief, lack of initiative and openness.
