<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Doctors     02-07 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Doctors,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Failed to Report $80 Million in Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Taxation Bureau said Tuesday it discovered
1,574 doctors in Tokyo and neighboring areas failed to declare
income totaling $80 million when they paid their 1987 taxes.
   Reassessed taxes on the undeclared income, plus penalty taxes,
totaled $36 million, up 18 percent from the 1986 figure, said a
bureau official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the amount of unreported income was up 21 percent from
1986.
   The bureau had rechecked 1,724 doctors suspected of tax evasion
in Tokyo and nearby prefectures where 28,442 doctors own hospitals
or clinics, he added.
   Reporting failures resulted from both intention and neglect, and
some doctors had fabricated expenses claimed as deductions, the
spokesman said.
