<SECOND>AM-BRF--France-Cinema,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subsidies for French Movies to be Boosted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France will boost subsidies to encourage production
and distribution of feature films, in order to reverse a drop at the
box office, the culture minister said Tuesday.
   Culture Minister Jack Lang said he hoped to help French producers
make each year about a dozen ``big-spectacle films that could help
movie attendence take off again.''
   The new government program will provide $32.5 million for the
French film industry in the next two years, Lang said.
   The French go to the movies less than they used to, preferring to
stay home and watch films on the six national TV channels.
   In the 1950s, French cinemas recorded 450 million ticket sales a
year. The figure has dropped ever since, hitting 130 million last
year _ a fall of 40 percent just in the past four years. France's
population is 55 million.
   Hundreds of movie houses have been forced to close, but France
still has more than Britain and West Germany combined.
