<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-US     02-07 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-US,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Rejects Criticism of Negroponte as Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government rejected harsh criticism of
John Negroponte and said Tuesday his apparent selection as the new
U.S. ambassador may indicate Washington is ready for better
relations with Mexico.
   ``Contrary to what many think, the designation of Negroponte is
not necessarily bad,'' the government newspaper El Nacional said
Tuesday in a front-page editorial.
   Late Monday night, the Foreign Ministry said it had sent a letter
to Washington accepting the appointment of Negroponte, whose choice
has not been announced officially by the White House.
   ``By sending this letter, the government of Mexico expresses to
the United States of America its wish that the selection of this
career diplomat contribute to the strengthening of bilateral ties
with equality and strict respect for the sovereignty of both
countries,'' a ministry statement said.
   Negroponte, a deputy national security adviser who was ambassador
to Honduras in 1982-85, would be the first career diplomat to serve
as U.S. ambassador to Mexico in a decade. He would replace Charles
J. Pilliod, the third political appointee in a row to hold the job.
   Mexico has opposed U.S. interference in Central America and the
controversy centers on Negroponte's role in U.S. aid for Nicaraguan
rebels fighting the leftist Sandinista government.
   While Negroponte was ambassador in Honduras, it became a base for
the rebels, called Contras, and the U.S. military presence grew
dramatically.
   Mexican critics of Negroponte, many of them on the political
left, have described him as an international meddler.
   He has been the target of scathing news stories, bitter
editorials, cartoons and sarcastic puns on his name, which can be
translated as ``black bridge.''
   Some compare him to Machiavelli and one cartoon depicted him in
formal diplomatic attire fashioned from military camouflage material.
   After reports of the appointment last week, President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's government said nothing while the media
controversy raged.
   In breaking the official silence, the ministry said Negroponte's
appointment was in line with what President Bush and Secretary of
State James A. Baker III have said about improving bilateral
relations.
   El Nacional said it its editorial: ``Negroponte was a faithful
executor of the instructions of a government blinded by apocalyptic,
ideological visions; he may now be one of an administration that
cleans up the broken dishes left by its predecessors.''
   A clearer U.S. vision of a stronger, stable and more prosperous
southern neighbor could mean closer cooperation on pressing problems
like Mexico's huge foreign debt, the paper said.
   Many of Negroponte's critics are troubled by his close contacts
with Gen. Gustavo Alvarez Martinez, a former chief of the Honduran
armed forces.
   Alvarez Martinez is known as the godfather of the Contra movement
and was widely accused of serious human rights violations in the
military effort to quell the Honduran left.
   He commanded the armed forces from 1982 until other senior
officers removed him in 1984. Alvarez Martinez was shot to death
last month in Tegucigalpa, capital of Honduras, and a leftist group
claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
