<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LonesomeDoveFans     02-07 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lonesome Dove Fans,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texans Involved In TV Series As Participants, Namesakes And History
Buffs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nielsens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texans aren't just watching the television
miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' _ they're participants, as actors,
history buffs and members of the real Lonesome Dove church.
   The first part of Larry McMurtry's Pulitzer-winning novel was set
in Texas and much of the movie was filmed here.
   The Austin American-Statesman has printed daily front-page boxes
advising readers on how to spot local scenes and actors appearing in
each night's episode of the four-part miniseries that started Sunday.
   Tuesday's article noted that, as the story's cattle drive moves
north out of Texas, ``the less we'll see of Austin.'' However, some
of Wednesday night's scenes were filmed east of Austin on ``some
property near Lake Walter Long that executive producer-screenwriter
Bill Wittliff used to own,'' the newspaper said.
   Central Texas papers have been interviewing Lonesome Dove stars
and writing about the series for weeks.
   Gov. Bill Clements, a history buff who owns hundreds of volumes
about the state, said McMurtry's novel was the best Texas-related
fiction he'd ever read.
   ``As an amateur student of Texas history ... certainly in my
opinion that's the best novel that's ever been written about early
Texas _ without any question. And the two episodes that I have now
watched I like very, very much,'' Clements said Tuesday.
   The CBS-TV Western tells the story of two retired Texas Rangers
who drive a cattle herd from the fictional town of Lonesome Dove, on
the Rio Grande along the U.S.-Mexican border, to Montana.
   Texas House Speaker Gib Lewis, a Fort Worth resident, said that
when the actors were to be shown in a fictional Fort Worth, ``I'll
be riding in there with them.''
   Despite all the praise, there were a few discouraging words.
   McMurtry, a native Texan, says he got the idea for the title of
his novel after seeing the Lonesome Dove Baptist Church's van pull
into a restaurant at Ponder in Denton County.
   Some members of the church don't like some of the language and
morals in the miniseries.
   ``I didn't care for all the sex,'' said Onalee Cate, 75, one of
about 400 members of the Lonesome Dove Baptist Church in Southlake,
near Fort Worth.
   But she continued: ``There are vulgar parts, but I thought the
action was real good.''
   ``I liked it as a whole, especially the back-to-earth living. I'm
old fashioned, you see,'' she added.
   ``Personally I can't be too proud of it,'' said Joseph ``Bud''
Tanner, 73, a descendant of the settlers who lived in what was known
as the Dove community, founded by a group of Missouri farmers.
   Dove was founded 142 years ago and was an area where farmers grew
cotton and cantaloupe, beans and okra.
   The Rev. Keith Wells, pastor of the Lonesome Dove church, said he
hadn't read all of the novel nor seen the first installment of the
miniseries.
   ``There's some fairly lewd comments within the script,'' said
Wells. ``It's just Hollywood trying to put something out to sell.''
   Despite his enthusiasm for ``Lonesome Dove,'' the governor said
he did have one reservation _ the cattle drive's ultimate
destination of Montana.
   ``That was perhaps the one thing in the novel that I never did
really quite understand,'' Clements said.
   ``My history has told me that an awful lot of Texans at that time
were taking cattle into Kansas and Colorado and Nebraksa, and even
to Wyoming. But really why this author picked out Montana, I'm not
sure. I think that, historically, it was in these other areas that
most of those cattle drives took place and most of the Texans went
and settled.''
</TEXT>
