<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh-Holdings     02-07 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Holdings,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh's Large Stock Portfolio Disqualifies Him From Cases</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ethics Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's extensive
holdings in blue-chip stocks have forced his recusal from a variety
of legal and policy issues since he took office last August.
   The attorney general's stock portfolio, which reads like a roster
of major U.S. corporations, includes AT&amp;T, Westinghouse, H.J. Heinz,
IBM, Atlantic Richfield, Amoco Corp., General Motors, Mobil Corp.,
Proctor and Gamble and Sears Roebuck.
   Before his Senate confirmation last summer, Thornburgh reported
that the value of his stock holdings was between $500,000 and
$700,000, said David Runkel, a spokesman for the attorney general.
   Thornburgh's holdings in large corporations could force him to
recuse himself from a number of issues that may arise during his
tenure as attorney general, Runkel conceded.
   The companies in which Thornburgh invested have diverse
operations that could potentially become the subject of Justice
Department action on any of several fronts, including environmental
enforcement, anti-trust investigations or litigation involving
government contracts.
   Historically, the Justice Department policy and legal activities
involve large corporations, notably its extensive civil anti-trust
investigation of oil companies that ended in 1983.
   Before he took office, Thornburgh asked the agency's various
divisions to determine what cases might pose a conflict-of-interest
for the attorney general, according to Justice Department records.
   Thornburgh agreed to recuse himself ``from participation in any
matter in which he has a financial interest'' to resign as a
corporate director of Rite Aid Corp., Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. and ARCO
Chemical Co., the Office of Government Ethics said in a letter to
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Under the recusal policy he later adopted, Thornburgh
disqualified himself from several legal cases pending before the
department, according to records compiled by the attorney general's
office.
   The law allows Thornburgh to obtain a waiver of disqualification,
but Runkel said he doubted the attorney general would seek such
waivers. So far, the attorney general has not sought any waivers,
Runkel said Tuesday.
   Thornburgh also notified division heads that he would not
participate in decisions involving several other issues that could
involve the agency in litigation or policymaking.
   The most notable case is Thornburgh's blanket recusal from
decisions involving the enforcement of the AT&amp;T divestiture consent
decree.
   Thornburgh also has recused himself from two issues as a result
of his holding of at least $15,000 worth of Westinghouse Electric
Corp. stock.
   He declined involvement in the anti-trust division's review last
summer of Schindler Holding Co.'s proposed acquisition of
Westinghouse's elevator subsidiary.
   He also recused himself from participation from any litigation
that might arise from the cleanup of a government nuclear weapons
plant in Fernald, Ohio, operated by Westinghouse.
   Thornburgh's ownership of at least $5,000 worth of AT&amp;T common
stock in an individual retirement account makes him the third
consecutive attorney general ineligible to oversee the anti-trust
division's role in court cases following divestiture.
   In 1980, before he became President Reagan's first attorney
general, William French Smith and his wife placed their stock and
bond holdings, valued at least $2.3 million, into a blind trust.
   Smith recused himself from AT&amp;T divestiture matters because he
had been a director of Pacific Bell.
   His successor, Edwin Meese III, was criticized last month by an
internal Justice Department report for participating in matters
involving the regional Bell companies while still holding stock in
those companies.
   Thornburgh, meanwhile, also recused himself from any government
involvement in litigation arising from a Jan. 2, 1988, fuel-oil
spill near Pittsburgh because his former law firm, Kirkpatrick and
Lockhart, represents Ashland Oil Co.
   He also recused himself from any policy discussions about whether
the Food and Drug Administration should play a role in implementing
California's Proposition 65.
   The law, adopted by voter referendum in 1986, requires extensive
warnings about toxic chemicals in the workplace and in labeling
prepared foods.
   Thornburgh's biggest single holding is at least $50,000 worth
stock in H.J. Heinz Co., the prepared food manufacturer based in the
attorney general's hometown of Pittsburgh.
   The attorney general also has recused himself from reviewing any
grant application by Harvard University, where his wife, Virginia,
is the univeristy's in-house advocate of the handicapped.
   Before he became attorney general, Thornburgh was the director of
the Institute of Politics at Harvard.
   Thornburgh also recused himself from any involvement in the
government's handling of a suit against the comptroller of the
currency challenging the right of national banks to insure municipal
bonds.
   The government has successfully defended the longstanding lawsuit
by an insurance trade association challenging the comptroller's
decision to allow Citicorp to acquire and operate a municipal bond
insurance business.
   Thornburgh owns at least $5,000 in Citicorp stock and at least
$5,000 worth of notes issued by the bank corporation.
</TEXT>
