<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     02-07 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Debt Grew By $5.4 Billion in December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans obligated themselves to $5.4 billion
more in credit than they paid off in December as consumer debt grew
at an annual rate of 9.9 percent, the government reported Tuesday.
   The Federal Reserve Board said the December increase followed a
revised increase of $4.7 billion in November and a rise of $3.9
billion in October.
   December's 9.9 percent rise in the seasonally adjusted annual
rate of credit growth was up from an 8.5 percent rate in November
and a 7.2 percent increase in October.
   December's increase matched the 9.9 percent rise recorded last
August, which was the highest since a 15.2 percent increase in June.
   The December jump was paced by an increase in outstanding auto
loans, while growth in the category of debt that includes credit
cards slowed from the rapid pace of the preceding two months.
   Consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic
health because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national
product.
   Economist Sandra Shaber of the Futures Group in Washington said
the latest report indicates that consumer finances were healthy in
December and throughout 1988.
   ``Despite the very-often-heard concerns about consumers
staggering under a debt burden, that really is not the case,'' Ms.
Shaber said. ``What we've had for two years now is people borrowing
no more than their income gains were.''
   Auto loans rose by $3 billion in December, a 12.4 percent annual
rate of growth. That followed a 5.7 percent increase during November.
   Revolving credit, the category that includes credit cards,
increased by $1.4 billion in December, a 9.1 percent annual rate of
growth, after having risen 21.1 percent in November.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by
$1.3 billion in December, a 9.5 percent increase in the annual rate,
after having inched up 0.4 percent in November.
   Loans for mobile homes decreased by $221 million, or a 10.3
percent drop, after rising 2.5 percent in the previous month.
   Overall, total consumer debt reached a seasonally adjusted $667.3
billion in December, up 8.9 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
