<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSEducation     02-07 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Education,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pay Defeat Hurts Scientist Recruiting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health experts told a Senate panel Tuesday that
the defeat of the pay raise will hurt their efforts to recruit
scientists to join the government's battle against AIDS.
   They also said more money was needed for government AIDS
education programs.
   Scientists at the Food and Drug Administration ``can leave for
salaries of four and five times'' above government pay levels, FDA
Commissioner Frank Young told the Labor and Human Resources
Committee.
   The pay voted down by Congress on Tuesday would have raised
congressional pay by 51 percent, but it would have also permitted
increases in the top-level pay of executive branch officials,
including government scientists at the FDA and the National
Institutes of Health.
   Young said the FDA is in the same predicament as NIH, which he
said hasn't been able to recruit a senior scientist in the last 10
years.
   ``We're in a difficult position of knowing how to prepare a
budget,'' Young also said, because ``we can't anticipate two years
ahead'' as the budget process requires.
   For example, he said, the FDA hadn't anticipated that the number
of applications for AIDS drug research would double, that there
would be annual instead of biannual inspections of the nation's drug
supply, or that there would be problems with inspections of condoms
and rubber gloves.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
   As of Jan. 2 ,the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta said
there were 32,311 AIDS cases reported in the United States in 1988,
a 57 percent increase in the number of reported AIDS cases from 1987.
   Samuel O. Thier, who heads the Institute of Medicine at the
National Academy of Sciences, said the approximately $1 billion
recommended for education and other health measures by 1990 was
``too low.''
   ``A substantial sum of money will have to be spent, over and
above $1 billion a year, to provide treatment facilities for
IV(intravenous) drug users...to prevent drug abuse and to mitigate
the dangers of shared'' needles, said Thier.
   Despite the shortfall of personnel and money, the experts said
they had made considerable progress in the last year in educating
the public and in creating and expanding programs to provide
services to critically ill AIDS victims.
   Young said the FDA has been successful in its efforts to
streamline the review process of drug treatments for AIDS and
AIDS-related conditions.
   Despite ``a marked increase'' in applications from pharmaceutical
companies to the agency for AIDS drug research and development, the
commissioner said the FDA has cut the review time for AIDS drug
therapies by about 50 percent.
   He cited the examples of two recently approved drugs, flutomide
and an aerosolized pentamidine, used to treat infections and cancers
that are often fatal to AIDS patients,
   The new drug application for flutomide was submitted to the FDA
in October 1988 and approved Jan. 25, while pentamidine was approved
Monday, Young said. As of the beginning of January the FDA had
approved 213 new drug research applications.
   Although Thier could offer no specific data on the effectiveness
of his agency's education programs, he did say National Center for
Health Statistics surveys show 85 percent of adults reporting they
had seen a public service announcement on AIDS between May and
August 1988.
   Other government officials said progress is also being made in
expanding care for the growing population of children stricken with
AIDS, training police and other professionals in dealing with AIDS
victims, and computerizing AIDS information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
