<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Canada     02-07 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Canada,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Hard Bargaining Seen in Ottawa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney will set the tone for future U.S.-Canadian relations in
talks later this week, a top White House aide said Tuesday.
   Previewing talks that Bush will have with Mulroney in Ottawa on
Friday, national security adviser Brent Scowcroft cautioned against
expecting major decisions or developments.
   Bush chose Canada for his first trip abroad, Scowcroft said, ``to
reaffirm the importance we attach to a close and productive
relationship with our neighbor to the north.''
   Scowcroft, a retired Air Force general, said Bush and Mulroney
have agreed beforehand that ``this first meeting is one to set the
tone and the agenda for subsequent meetings.''
   He did say, however, the two leaders are expected to discuss acid
rain, the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement, maritime borders and
military relationships, among other subjects.
   Yet, Scowcroft insisted, ``It is not a negotiating session, as
such, to get down into the nitty-gritty of issues and determine
specific milestones and so forth.''
   He acknowledged that Mulroney has been pressing the United States
hard on the acid rain pollution befouling the air and waters in the
Midwest and parts of Canada and the Great Lakes region.
   But Scowcroft said that while Bush promised to take action on the
environmental problem, the president isn't yet ready to make hard
commitments to the prime minister.
   ``I think he feels that the first step has to be the domestic
part of the acid rain agenda before he's prepared to be all that
specific with the Canadians,'' he said.
   ``This is an initial meeting,'' Scowcroft added. ``It's a very,
kind of private, relaxed meeting to set the tone of the relationship
and to determine the kinds of things that the two will want to be
talking about down the line.''
</TEXT>
