<FIRST>r a AM-Powell     02-07 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Powell,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powell Hospitalized With Respiratory Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Supreme Court Justice Lewis F.
Powell Jr. was listed in stable condition Tuesday, a day after he
entered a hospital with an acute respiratory infection.
   Powell, 81, was undergoing tests Tuesday at Baptist Medical
Center and doctors had not determined when he would be released,
said Cindy Hamilton, a hospital spokeswoman.
   The justice, who was in Jacksonville sitting on a panel of the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, had a dizzy spell Monday and was
taken by ambulance to the hospital.
   Powell had a comfortable night and had no fever nor signs of
pneumonia, Ms. Hamilton said.
   The justice's vital signs were good and there was no evidence of
cardio-vascular problems, she said. Powell took a walk down hospital
corridors Tuesday afternoon, she said.
   The appeals panel continued to hear oral arguments Tuesday. The
arguments were taped so that Powell could hear them and help decide
the cases.
   Powell retired from the nation's highest court June 26, 1987,
citing concerns about his health as one reason. He had suffered from
prostate cancer.
   When he left the high court, Powell took senior judge status,
which allows him to hear cases at his discretion. He has since
participated in a number of cases for the Richmond-based 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   He was 64 when nominated by President Richard Nixon in 1971 and
was sworn in Jan. 7, 1972, replacing Justice Hugo L. Black.
