<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Resignations     02-07 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Resignations,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Replaces Most Reagan Appointees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp, taking control of his large department, has moved to replace
nearly all of HUD's political appointees left over from the Reagan
administration, the department said Tuesday.
   Kemp, who was confirmed by the Senate on Friday, informed most
top officials of the department that day in writing that their
resignations were to be effective March 3.
   The resignations include nearly all the department's political
appointees and other senior executives who do not have
career-employee status. A department official, insisting on
anonymity, placed the number of people being let go at 126,
including most assistant secretaries, deputies and other
high-ranking posts.
   The department said in a statement:
   ``Acceptance of these resignations in no way reflects on these
employees' performance. But the Bush administration has indicated
from the outset its desire to put a new team in place to implement
the Bush-Kemp policies and programs at HUD.''
   The former secretary, Samuel R. Pierce, asked for the
resignations ``at the pleasure of the secretary'' on Jan. 3. Similar
requests for the resignations of political appointees were made
throughout government, although in some departments some officials
are keeping their jobs in the new administration.
   Kemp was sworn in Monday afternoon by the department's general
counsel, J. Michael Dorsey. A formal swearing-in ceremony
administered by President Bush is expected early next week.
   Kemp, who has received enthusiastic support in the new job from
mayors, housing officials and other groups that deal regularly with
HUD, has has announced no replacements. He so far has announced the
appointment of one official, special assistant Mary Brunette, his
former legislative director in Congress.
   Alan J. Greenwald, deputy under secretary for intergovernmental
affairs, who was at the department for the full eight years Pierce
was secretary, said that he was not surprised by the actions but
that some political appointees were upset.
   ``A lot of people are upset,'' he said. ``I don't understand it,
but they are. We've had a long run here, eight years.''
</TEXT>
