<FIRST>r i AM-SnakeMan     02-07 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snake Man,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Lives With Cobras for 14 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dastagir Husini, the Malaysian
``snake king'' who has lived with about 100 poisonous cobras for two
weeks, said Tuesday he will continue his feat for another few days.
   He broke the world record of nine days on Feb. 2, the National
News Agency Bernama reported Tuesday without saying who had held the
record. The Guinness Book of World Records does not list records in
such events.
   Husini, 63, was given a clean bill of health by Dr. A. Ganga
Daran who examined him after he stepped out of a glass cubicle at
the National Museum on Tuesday.
   A snake exhibition also is being held at the museum in
conjunction with the event, and visitors have paid more than $27,500
since he started his feat. Museum Director-General Shahrum Yub said
the proceeds would be divided equally between Husini and the museum.
   ``I am fine and ready to prolong my stay with the snakes for
another two or three days,'' Husini said at a news conference
outside the cubicle.
   ``But there should not be any condition, no pressure from anybody
for me to continue or to call off the act any time I may feel like
doing it,'' he said, adding that he was not having any problems so
far either from the snakes, museum management or the visitors.
   ``I am taking some vitamins, prescribed by the doctor, to keep up
my strength and have been one happy entertainer before huge crowds
who turn up even at the week hours, especially on weekends,'' he
added.
   The visitors came from all over the country as well as from
Singapore and Thailand and India, where snake acts are common.
   The glass cubicle measures 12.99 feet by 10 feet by 10 feet. He
steps out of it for 15 minutes every hour for his meals and vitamins.
   The cobras are fed eggs at night, and there is a bucket of water
in the cubicle.
   Husini learned how to handle snakes from his father, a snake
charmer. Husini has taught his children the art, and he said he
hoped one of his sons, Mohamad Ali, 25, would shoot for his record.
   Husini said the secret of his feat is that the cobras normally
don't attack people unless provoked.
</TEXT>
