<SECOND>AM-Preacher Sentencing,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child-Molesting Preacher Chastised By Judge For Lying, Sentenced
For Sodomy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preacher who authorities say has seduced and
abused 100 boys for at least two decades was sentenced Tuesday to 2{
years in prison for child sodomy.
   Mario ``Tony'' Leyva, a self-ordained pentecostal preacher who
still faces a sentencing on federal charges, took the stand in
Roanoke County Circuit Court and apologized for lying in September
when he told jurors he had never committed any homosexual acts with
minors.
   But Judge Kenneth Trabue chastised Leyva as he upheld the
sentence jurors had recommended when they convicted him of
performing oral sodomy on two teen-age boys.
   ``I suppose the thing that troubles me most is somebody of the
cloth, who knows the truth, has openly and flagrantly lied,'' Trabue
told Leyva, 43, of Columbus, Ga. ``There was an overt effort to
poison the jury on your behalf.''
   Assistant Commonwealth's Attorney Randy Leach agreed not to press
perjury charges against Leyva as part of a deal in which Leyva and
two fellow preachers pleaded guilty to federal charges that they
shipped young boys across state lines on the southern revival
circuit to use them in illegal sex acts.
   Leyva, Rias Edward Morris and Freddie M. Herring could be
sentenced by late February or early March in U.S. District Court.
The three ministers pleaded guilty in October to charges they used
the Tony Leyva Evangelistic Association Inc., based in Columbus, to
gain access to young boys through the years.
   Leyva had been abusing boys since at least the 1960s, when he was
a preacher in North Carolina, the FBI said. Morris, 47, was Leyva's
ministry organist, and Herring, 50, was founder of the Lighthouse
Assembly in Douglasville, Ga. Their plea agreements call for maximum
sentences of 20 years in prison for Leyva and 15 years each for
Morris and Herring.
   Morris and Herring were not charged in the state case.
   During Leyva's state trial in September, he called his young
accusers liars and said their stories of sexual abuse were prompted
by people out to get him. But when Leyva decided to reach a plea
bargain with federal prosecutors, the FBI made him provide a
detailed account of the sex acts that had gone on for years in his
ministry.
   Lawyers said that since Leyva's testimony in federal court
contradicted his sworn claim of innocence in state court, he had to
recant the earlier testimony.
   ``I've recanted on the statements and wish to beg the court's
forgiveness for the statements, which were not true,'' Leyva told
the judge Tuesday.
</TEXT>
