<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists seeking a special souvenir of
their visit to Music City can get just the thing at the Music Row
Wedding Chapel _ a spouse.
   For those who prefer the more mundane, T-shirts are also
available.
   ``We felt like tourists would find it unique to be married on
Music Row,'' said Ellie Mead, one of the partners in the wedding
chapel business.
   The chapel has a steeple, six on-call ministers and piped-in
music. T-shirts for sale in the gift shop announce ``We Rang the
Bell on Music Row.''
   The owners foresee more wedding centers around the country,
franchised under the name Wedding Chapels of America.
   The Music Row chapel seats 40 and has a raised stage in the front
with electric logs glowing in the background. Two stained glass
windows feature magnolias and doves.
   A no-frills wedding with music, boutonniere and corsage is $95
and takes less than half an hour.
   The chapel's office take appointments during the day, and there
is usually a minister on call from 3 to 5 p.m. for walk-in business,
said publicist Jane Billingsley, a partner in the venture.
   ``That's for the people who come in and want to get married right
now, I mean right now.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texans love their Blue Bell ice cream _ even when
the temperature outdoors is colder than the frost on their dessert
spoons.
   Blue Bell officials say that during the icy weather last weekend
they sold 600,000 gallons of ice cream _ a record for this time of
year _ at grocery and convenience stores in the Dallas area.
   ``We did more in those four days than we normally do in a week,''
division manager Melvin Ziegenbein said Monday. ``Today our phone is
ringing off the wall from people out of ice cream.''
   Supplies at Dallas-area stores are dwindling and officials are
not sure if they will be able to keep up with the unprecedented
demand.
   The branch manager of Blue Bell's distribution office in suburban
Mesquite had a simple explanation for the seemingly irrational
cold-weather craving.
   ``People stock up on food and stay home and sit by the fire and
eat ice cream,'' said Jerry Ferguson.
