<HEAD>Body Found on Abandoned Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A body was discovered on an abandoned, burned-out
ship being towed to port on the Washington coast, Coast Guard
officials said Tuesday.
   The Zhe-Sheng, a 180-foot Taiwanese fishing vessel that drifted
on the high seas for more than seven months, also has 40,000 gallons
of diesel oil on board, Petty Officer Andre Billeaudeaux said.
   Billeaudeaux said the body would be turned over to authorities
after the ship is towed to the Coast Guard station at Port Angeles.
The fuel will be salvaged, he said.
   The Zhe-Sheng had drifted about 2,800 nautical miles since it was
abandoned about 300 miles north of Midway Island after a fire last
June. Seventeen members of the 18-man crew survived, Billeaudeaux
said.
   Officials knew before the discovery of the body that one of the
crewmen was unaccounted for, but had no information about his
possible fate, Billeaudeaux said.
   The ship was spotted by a tanker Sunday about 400 miles off Cape
Flattery on the northwest Washington coast. The body was discovered
after the crew of the Active boarded the vessel Monday, Billeaudeaux
said.
