<FIRST>r w AM-SeasideSparrow 1stLd-Writethru a0663 02-07 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seaside Sparrow, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dusky Seaside Sparrow May Not Have Been True Subspecies, Expert Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New graf 6, bgng ``Elizabeth Lipscomb,'' inserts agency comment;
deletes now-unneeded penultimate graf pvs, bgng ``The public''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dusky seaside sparrow, a small Florida bird
that became extinct despite a multimillion-dollar effort to preserve
it, may not have been a true subspecies after all, but just a
routine member of a bird family still thriving all along the
Atlantic coast.
   John C. Avise, a University of Georgia professor of genetics,
said Tuesday that a comparison of random samples of genes from the
dusky with those of other Atlantic coast seaside sparrows shows
almost no difference, suggesting that efforts to prevent the dusky's
extinction were not justified.
   ``The genetic results suggest that the magnitude of genetic
distinction of the dusky from other Atlantic coast populations of
seaside sparrows is very small,'' said Avise. ``In fact, we didn't
detect any differences, really.''
   The professor said the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service was
required by law to try to protect the small bird because the sparrow
was officially identified as a true subspecies. But Avise said that
based on a modern comparison of the bird's genetic makeup, it
appears the sparrow known as dusky was not unique.
   ``At the time they (the Fish and Wildlife Service) acted, it was
appropriate to try to save the dusky based on the available
information that they had,'' said Avise. ``In hindsight, it may have
been questionable as to whether the distinctiveness of that
population was sufficiently great to have warranted the attention
that it received.''
   Elizabeth Lipscomb, a Fish and Wildlife Service spokeswoman, said
experts with the federal agency are familiar with Avise's study but
believe ``it's a little preliminary to consider the dusky to not be
a subspecies because it (genetic research) is such a new
technique.'' She said the agency has ``delisted'' dusky, which she
said means the bird is considered a distinct and extinct subspecies.
   Avise said the efforts to save the dusky were based on the
existing classification, or taxonomy, of the bird.
   ``Many of those taxonomies were erected back the last century or
early in this century on sometimes very questionable, very limited
data bases,'' he said. If genetic relationships had been established
using modern molecular science, the dusky probably would not have
been identified as a subspecies and ``it probably would not have
been given any special consideration,'' said Avise.
   Avise and a colleague, William S. Nelson, report in this week's
journal Science that they compared the pattern of 11 genetic markers
in the dusky seaside sparrow with the pattern found in five other
seaside sparrow subspecies.
   The research showed, the report said, that the dusky had
essentially no difference in evolutionary history and genetic
pattern than ``other Atlantic coast populations of ammondramus
maritimus (seaside sparrow).''
   Based on the genetic pattern comparison, the study said, the last
dusky seaside sparrow ``appears to have been a routine example of
the Atlantic coast phylad of seaside sparrow.''
   Cape Canaveral in Florida was the only known natural habitat for
the dusky seaside sparrow. The bird was numerous until the 1940s
when spraying for mosquitoes and draining of swampland led to its
decline. At one point, a 5,000-acre reserve, costing $3 million, was
purchased in an effort to save the dusky.
   The last five dusky seaside sparrows, all males, were captured
several years ago and taken to a refuge on Discovery Island in Walt
Disney World. The last of these birds died last June.
   Science is the journal for the American Association for the
Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890207-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-BaldKids     02-07 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Bald Kids,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Blame Thallium Poisoning For Children's Hair Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thallium poisoning, possibly from acid rain, caused
the mysterious hair loss suffered by 150 children under the age of
14 in a Ukrainian city near the Romanian border, Tass on Tuesday
quoted officials as saying.
   But three months after the initial reports, the Ukrainian Health
Ministry is still unable to calm parents in Chernovtsy because it
has been unable to determine where the thallium came from, the
official news agency reported.
   The toxic metal has polluted the air and soil in the area since
July, and children have lost hair and suffered mild nervous and
mental problems such as irritation and hallucinations, Tass said.
   Four children remain under treatment, two at the Kiev Institute
of Pediarics and two in a sanatorium near Kiev, Tass said.
   Pravda, the Communist Party newspaper, said in November that
authorities suspected thallium as the cause of the children's
ailment. Soviet media speculated that contaminated gasoline or acid
rain created by a Romanian chemical plant might be at fault.
   Chernovtsy authorities are trying to reduce the amount of
thallium in the air and soil by regularly washing downtown streets,
allowing only local drivers into the city center and banning all
traffic one day a week, Tass said.
   In addition, all children in the city aged 5 to 14 will be sent
to sanatoriums and ``pioneer camps'' during summer vacation.
   Thallium, a rare, poisonous, bluish-white, soft metallic element,
is used in antiknock compounds, photoelectric cells, rat poisons and
other products.
</TEXT>
