<FIRST>u w AM-US-Pakistan-Nuclear     02-07 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Pakistan-Nuclear,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistani Says Nation Won't Build A-Bomb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan's ambassador to the United States said
Tuesday his nation is on the threshold of developing nuclear weapons
but does not intend to build them, preferring to seek accord with
neighboring India.
   ``It is right to say that we are one of the `threshold' states,''
said Ambassador Jamsheed K.A. Marker in what appeared to be the most
explicit acknowledgement to date that Pakistan is moving ahead on
its nuclear weapons program and could develop the bomb if it chose.
   ``We have deliberately chosen not to take the final step, to
build a bomb and test it, because we don't think it is right,''
Marker said in an interview on the program, ``American Interests,''
produced by public broadcasting stations WETA-TV of Washington and
WNET-TV of New York. The interview is to be broadcast this weekend.
   Marker's description of the Pakistani program differed from past
statements by officials of his government. A press release from the
Pakistani Embassy last Thursday, for example, said emphasized what
it called ``the peaceful nature of Pakistan's nuclear program,'' and
did not use such phrases as ``threshold states,'' or ``final step,''
or even acknowledge the existence of a military nuclear program.
   U.S. observers were uncertain how to interpret Marker's comments.
State Department, non-government and foreign diplomatic experts said
they did not believe Marker had intended to go beyond statements
made in December by Pakistani Prime Benazir Bhutto that Pakistan had
a purely peaceful nuclear program.
   ``If it is a new formulation of the Pakistani position, it would
be significant at this moment,'' said Leonard Spector, an expert at
the Carnegie Endowment who closely follows proliferation issues.
   ``I would say it is a surprising statement,'' said Spector. ``I
would say it was a slip of the tongue rather than a new policy.''
   Bhutto and her Indian counterpart, Rajiv Ghandi, met in Islamabad
Dec. 31 and signed an agreement not to attack each other's nuclear
facilities, viewed as a possible first step to a regional
non-proliferation accord.
   Neither Pakistan nor India have signed the 1968 Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty and they have fought three wars since
achieving independence from Britain in 1947.
   A knowledgeable diplomatic source said Marker had not intended to
go beyond Bhutto's formulation.
   ``What he meant to say was the capability was there,'' said the
diplomat, who spoke on condition he not be further identified. ``It
was in the form of questions and answer, so it may have given the
impression that he went further'' than Bhutto.
   Pakistan wants to make sure it receives the same treatment in the
international community as India, which claims not to have an atomic
arsenal but exploded what it called a peaceful nuclear device in
1974.
   ``To us, it sounded like a bomb,'' said Marker. ``We are
exercising our nuclear option. We will not remove this option until
we get assurances of equality.''
   Marker also said he was confident that Pakistan would be
certified as a non-nuclear nation by the Bush administration, a
requirement Congress has set before it will allow that nation to
receive further military assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
