<SECOND>AM-Raise Supporters,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Why They Voted For a Pay Hike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pay Raise, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few members of Congress spoke out for raising
their pay Tuesday as the proposal was soundly defeated, but one who
did presented his argument in human terms that won a large round of
applause.
   ``You know how hard you work and you shouldn't be embarrassed to
say it,'' Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., told the House before it
voted 380-48 to reject the 51 percent raise and the Senate followed
suit, 94-6.
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee reminded
colleagues, ``The hardest thing you do is tell your families that
they must sacrifice year in and year out.''
   ``Sure there are perquisites that come with the job,'' he said,
his voice rising. ``But you know as well as I do that perks can't
make up for the birthdays, ball games, holidays and meals that we
miss. When was the last time you skipped a town meeting for a school
play? If you can't remember, ask your spouse.
   ``You maintain two households but you're never home.''
   The House majority whip, Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said
Congress was ``engaged in an action that is surely self-defeating.''
   By not taking the raise and coupling the increase with
eliminating honoraria, Coelho said, Congress would continue ``a
system of compensation that revolves around special interest money.
This is no victory. It is a loss for the concept of leadership.''
   ``The score is easy to read: Ralph Nader 1, national interest
0,'' Coelho added, referring to the consumer advocate who was an
outspoken opponent of the raise, which had been proposed by a
presidential commission and supported both by Ronald Reagan and
President Bush.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., joined other speakers in
predicting that federal executives and judges would leave federal
service without more money.
   Countering arguments that judicial candidates are waiting in line
to be nominated, Early said, ``Our concern should be who's in line.''
   He criticized colleagues for making re-election ``more important
in this House than anything else.'' The most important thing, he
said, is ``long-range good government.''
   Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., introduced the resolution to reject the
raise but said he did so only to ``face reality.'' He then voted
against his own rejection resolution.
   He said that despite support from Common Cause, the self-styled
citizens' lobby, ``We fell prey to the deception of the rabble
rousers. We became cartoon cannon fodder for trash television and
talk radio.''
   He added, ``There are Supreme Court justices who make less than
their clerks the day after they (the clerks) retire and go into
private practice.''
