<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Banks-InvestmentFirms     02-07 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Investment Firms,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comptroller Warns Banks Against Accepting Financial Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials on Tuesday warned banks
against accepting benefits from financial management firms in
exchange for placing bank funds in investments sponsored by those
firms.
   The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, in a circular sent
to national banks and examiners, said ``a number of national bank
trust departments'' may have accepted incentives from firms that
sponsor mutual funds or other investment funds in return for putting
bank assets in funds offered by the firms.
   It said the incentives appear to have included discounts or
rebates on fees for other services such as accounting and
administrative work, computer goods or services, and seminars and
travel expenses for bank personnel.
   The memo reminded banks that their investment decisions should be
``based exclusively on the best interest of trust customers.''
   It said bank laws prohibit bank trust departments ``from
receiving any financial benefits, including discounts or rebates on
goods or services purchased, or other items of value, in exchange
for investing trust funds in particular investments.''
   ``Trustees must not place themselves in a position where their
judgments concerning the optimal investment for trust accounts may
be influenced by the trustee's receipt of financial benefits for
selecting a particular investment,'' the banking circular said.
   The comptroller said banks that accept prohibited financial
benefits may be subject to ``significant liability'' for breaching
their duty and to enforcement action by the comptroller's office and
may be required to provide reimbursement for the benefits.
</TEXT>
