<FIRST>r a AM-WrightHometown     02-07 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Hometown,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Constituents Unhappy with House Speaker Wright</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While House Speaker Jim Wright rapped
his gavel in Washington for a vote rejecting the congessional pay
raise, some of his constituents in Texas were sounding off against
the man they put in office.
   Calls by Fort Worth residents to a KLIF-AM radio talk show
Tuesday were highly critical of Wright's handling of the proposed
increase. The callers were not required to identify themselves, and
few did.
   ``I'm very disgusted in Jim Wright,'' said one caller. ``... I'm
going to work as hard as I can to get him out of office.''
   Another caller told listeners: ``If there's someone running
against him (Wright) who has some decent qualifications, there's no
doubt that I would probably think twice about voting for Jim
Wright.''
   Wright had planned to let the $45,500 increase take effect
automatically on Wednesday without a vote in the House. But pressure
from his colleagues and public outrage finally forced his hand, and
on Tuesday the pay raise was overwhelmingly voted down.
   Some callers to the radio show were disturbed that Wright was not
explaining his position to them.
   ``I really feel that Jim Wright's opinion of my opinion doesn't
amount to a bucket of warm spit,'' a caller said. ``I wrote him; I
sent him a tea bag; I called his office. And, so far, I've gotten
two copies of the same letter saying he wasn't going to do
anything.''
   Wright told the Fort Worth Star Telegram on Jan. 26 that he
expected to be ridiculed for some of his decisions.
   ``The speaker is supposed to take some heat. If you're a leader
in an institution, you're expected to be a lightning rod. ... I'm
doing the best I can to put it in perspective. Sometimes that is
difficult for a congressional leader.''
   Letters to the Star Telegram's opinion-editorial page over the
past few days have said Wright has lost sight of what his job should
be in Washington.
   Kester M. Hearn of Fort Worth wrote in a letter published Sunday:
``Speaker Jim Wright is preventing members of Congress from being
representatives by denying them a right to vote on the raise.
Therefore he must be opposed to representative government. ... he
should quit posing as a representative and come home.''
   Wright has enjoyed tremendous support over the years from voters
in his home district. In November he was elected to an 18th term
without opposition, despite being the subject of an ethics
investigation by his House colleagues.
</TEXT>
