<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Mayors     02-07 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Mayors,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Feds Have Anti-Drug Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National drug director-designate William J.
Bennett told the U.S. Conference of Mayors on Tuesday the war on
drugs is ``emphatically the business of the federal government,''
not just the states and cities.
   ``I don't have any ambiguity about the federal role in the war on
drugs,'' said Bennett, who, as education secretary under former
President Reagan, argued that schools were chiefly the
responsibility of state and local authorities.
   ``This is serious business,'' he said. ``This is the business of
state and local governments. But it is emphatically the business of
the federal government.''
   The gathering of mayors _ including several who asked
specifically for federal money to be granted directly to local
governments to help fight drugs _ applauded Bennett's remarks.
   But Bennett didn't say how much money he intends to try to
provide to local authorities.
   Questioned later, Bennett said budget decisions will have to wait
until he completes a national drug control strategy report. It is
due six months after he is confirmed by the Senate as director of
National Drug Control Policy.
   ``Certainly some of the effort is going to take money. ... You're
going to see some progress and some movement on this issue very
soon. The six-month report is the critical document to me.''
   He told the mayors the report ``will be straight. As secretary of
education, I played it straight, called them as I saw them. I will
call this as I see it. There will be no politics in this report.''
   The mayors are extremely worried about money because while the
drug bill called for $275 million to be spent for Justice Assistance
programs _ grants to state and local agencies _ in the current
fiscal year, only $220 million has been appropriated by Congress.
   Reagan's budget proposal for fiscal 1990 proposed no money for
justice assistance, although the drug bill called for $350 million.
   Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., chairman of the House
subcommittee on crime, told the mayors that while Congress has
passed a lot of legislation, ``What we really have not done is we
have not funded the programs realistically. ...
   ``We have to get our fiscal house in order so we can
realistically fund programs like the Justice Assistance programs so
that we are once again full partners with state and local units of
government. ... That's where the battle takes place. Ninety percent
of our enforcement takes place at the state and local level.''
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee who fought for creation of a drug czar position for eight
years, told the mayors, ``It's about time we stop kidding the
American people ... about what we will be able to do legislatively
to end this problem. ... We have enough laws at the federal level.
We have to see if they work.''
   Biden said the drug bill could be fully funded by raising taxes
on cigarettes, beer and liquor, saying, ``We're still 60 percent
behind what the tax was in 1954 on those commodities. ... If you
have a better idea, suggest it, or stop saying you support the drug
bill.''
   He predicted that Congress would fully fund the drug bill,
approving legislation already introduced in both houses to add $1.6
billion to this year's spending. The bills do not specify how to pay
for that spending.
   Bennett said he will pay attention to the law enforcement end of
the drug war but, ``In the end, in the real long run, this is a
question of values. ...
   ``It's asking an awful lot in moral courage to ask a 13-year-old
to give up what he's been hearing for a large part of his 13 years
is the good life, material goods, money, cars, clothes,'' he said.
   Bennett said Bush ``is serious about this. It's his number one
priority.''
</TEXT>
