<SECOND>AM-Soviet-ECC,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say East and West Should Work for United Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East and West should discard past conflicts and
work toward a united Europe, Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
told EEC representatives on Tuesday.
   Shevardnadze met with diplomats of the 12 nations of the European
Economic Community, with which the Soviets established formal
relations last summer.
   ``There are no issues that are beyond the interests of Europe,''
Shevardnadze was quoted as saying by the official news agency Tass.
   He said the goal should be ``unity of European peoples, of all
countries that participate in the all-European process toward the
establishment of moral and legal principles that would be common for
all.''
   ``Today we're beginning to do what we should have done
yesterday,'' he said. ``To make up for the lost time we will have to
act in a resolute way, make vigorous strides and get rid of the
burden of the past.
   ``Although the integration in the East and West of Europe is
based on economic processes, both we and you feel that rapprochement
can be achieved through adding dynamism to the political dialogue.''
   Shevardnadze said discussions should address ``prospects for
Europe's participation in the life of the international community .
.. efficient participation in efforts to solve global problems, such
as poverty or ecoological degradation, and heal the bleeding wounds
of regional conflicts.''
   The 12 Common Market members are Belgium, Britain, Denmark,
France, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal, Spain and West Germany.
