<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Romero     02-07 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Romero,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>D'Aubuisson Denies Romero Assassination Involvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rightist political leader
Roberto D'Abuisson on Tuesday denied the government's renewed charge
that he masterminded the 1980 assassination of Roman Catholic
Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero.
   ``I have put up with the basest slanders for eight years, and God
and my conscience know that I had nothing to do with this
reprehensible assassination,'' he was quoted in an interview
published Tuesday in the daily La Prensa Grafica.
   D'Abuisson said the Christian Democratic administration revived
the accusation as a political maneuver before the March 19
presidential election. D'Abuisson is founder of the rightist
National Republican Alliance, known as Arena, leads the Christian
Democrats in recent polls.
   The government long has said D'Abuisson was the architect of the
assassination but never cited any specific evidence backing up the
charge.
   On Sunday, a government television program said a commission
investigating Romero's death identified the gunman as Hector Antonio
Regalado.
   Regalado, a dentist, was security chief for the Legislative
Assembly when D'Abuisson was assembly speaker. News reports have
linked Regalado to the death squads D'Abuisson has been accused of
organizing. D'Abuisson also denies any role in the death squads.
   Romero, an outspoken critic of death squad activity and human
rights abuses by the military, was killed by a lone marksman as he
was saying Mass in a chapel in the capital on March 24, 1980.
   Nobody has been held in the slaying, and Regalado's whereabouts
were not immediately known.
   The commission said Amado Antonio Garay, the driver for a former
army captain, Alvaro Saravia, identified Regalado from photographs
as the gunman.
   Garay said Saravia was the other passsenger on the day of the
shooting and described D'Abuisson as the mastermind of the
assassination.
   Saravia was arrested on immigration charges in Miami in 1987, and
the Salvadoran government requested his extradition.
   But the Salvadoran Supreme Court in December overturned the
extradition request before Saravia could be returned to El Salvador,
saying testimony linking him to the assassination was not credible.
   Saravia, 46, was released last month from a Miami jail and lives
in the Miami suburb of Kendall. His attorney says he is seeking
political asylum.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
commission's ``announcement may reflect the Salvadoran government's
deep frustration with the failure of the judicial system to
prosecute this notorious and longstanding case.''
   ``In light of the Salvadoran Supreme Court action in withdrawing
the extradition warrant for ex-Capt. Saravia in December _ he was a
potential witness in the case _ the government of El Salvador,
through its Minister of Justice, has evidently decided to make the
facts known to the public,'' he said.
   Redman said the United States believed the Salvadoran Supreme
Court made a ``serious'' error.
   ``If that extradition warrant had been allowed to proceed, the
government of El Salvador could have obtained critical information
by which to prosecute this case. We would hope that all leads would
be investigated in this case in order to finally bring to justice
those accused of committing this crime.''
   D'Abuisson is a legislator, which gives him immunity from
prosecution.
</TEXT>
