<FIRST>r a AM-PancakeRace     02-07 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pancake Race,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Olney Wins Seventh Straight In Annual Pancake Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBERAL, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gym instructor who trained on a Welsh
mountainside bested an aerobics teacher Tuesday in the annual Shrove
Tuesday pancake race, keeping the championship in English hands for
the seventh consecutive year.
   Lesley Byrne, 26, of Olney, England, ran her hometown, 415-yard
course, carrying a frying pan with a pancake, in 62 seconds. On the
Kansas course, Donetta Schindler, 23, won with a time of 65.91
seconds.
   Mrs. Byrne, who also won last year, said she trained by running
down the highest mountain in the Snowdonia range, the 3,560-foot
Snowdon in northern Wales.
   ``I'm thrilled to have won but I think the wind stopped me from
breaking the record,'' she said. ``My legs feel really bad. I
thought I was fitter because I'd been training. I'll be coming back
next year to try for the hat-trick (three wins).''
   Mrs. Schindler passed 14 competitors in Liberal.
   ``I felt like I was in good position,'' said Mrs. Schindler, a
former star tennis player at Liberal High School. ``I was ready for
it, but I had not trained that much.''
   Most of her training for the race, which she was running for the
first time, came from her job, she said.
   Mrs. Schindler's sister, Sheila Turner, set the record for the
Liberal pancake race in 1975 with a time of 58.5 seconds. The Olney
record is 59.8 seconds.
   According to legend, the race has been run in Olney since 1445,
when a harassed housewife dashed to church on Shrove Tuesday still
clutching her frying pan with a pancake in it. Others say pancakes
may have been a form of bribe to the bellringer to ring the bell
sooner to signal the beginning of the feast day celebrations.
   After a lapse during World War II, Olney revived the race in
1948. Two years later, the women of Liberal in southwest Kansas
challenged the English to see who could come up with the best time.
   Liberal won nine straight in the 1970s to build up a 19-13 lead,
but Olney now holds the edge at 20-19.
   After Tuesday's race in Liberal was finished shortly after noon,
officials here telephoned England with the results, and the winners
exchanged congratulations.
   About 1,000 spectators turned out for the Liberal race, in spite
of the temperature of around 20 degrees.
   The weather at Olney, 50 miles northwest of London, was sunny
with temperatures in the mid 50s, and about 2,500 spectators turned
out.
   Second place in Liberal was won by Lori Sharp, who led the 1988
race before falling in the final yards. ``I'm just happy to finish
the race this year standing up,'' Mrs. Sharp said.
   Runners in both races wore the traditional garb of skirt, apron
and headscarf. The winners exchange inscribed silver trays from the
two towns and other prizes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890207-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Carnival     02-07 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carnival,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carnival Festivities Enter Fourth and Final Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nursing hangovers and sore feet,
Brazilians and tourists Tuesday reveled in a final round of Brazil's
world-famous carnival _ four days of practically non-stop dancing,
partying and seemingly endless parades.
   Throughout Latin America's largest country, from the steamy
Amazon to the concrete jungles of industrial Sao Paulo, people shed
their inhibitions and clothes to dance in the streets and in private
clubs to the rhythmic and almost hypnotic beat of samba drums.
   The merrymaking will continue through noon on Ash Wednesday, when
Carnival officially ends and stores, banks and government offices
reopen.
   Police in Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo, Brazil's two most
important cities, were still compiling crime rate figures but
reported that this year's carnival was mostly peaceful.
   As usual, the most lavish, unrestrained and colorful partying
took place in Rio de Janeiro which once again hosted a spectacular
parade of ``samba schools,'' actually neighborhood groups from poor
and mainly black districts.
   For hours on end, from Sunday to Tuesday, tens of thousands of
cheering spectators watched these schools march down the city's
brightly lit ``sambadrome,'' a parade ground flanked by huge
concrete grandstands.
   The ``schools'' of up to 4,000 members each work the whole year
on their colorful costumes and floats and rehearse the original
lyrics and dance steps for the big parade.
   The parades always have a strong dose of eroticism as beautiful
women, either barebreasted or scantily clad in string bikinis dance
exuberantly along the parade route or on top of the floats.
   Along Rio de Janeiro's famous Copacabana and Ipanema beaches
Brazilians and foreigners danced to the throbbing beat of impromptu
samba bands and occasionally took a dip in the ocean.
   The wealthy partied in private clubs that threw wild and
glittering balls in which feathers or strings of beads passed as
costumes.
   More than 1,000 miles northeast of Rio, the pre-Lenten holiday
was also celebrated with the same exuberance in the cities of
Salvador and Recife _ the country's two other popular carnival
centers.
   In Salvador, thousands took to the streets to dance behind
specially built sound trucks that roamed the city blaring out
carnival music. In Recife, large crowds danced behind 10-foot-high
papier mache dolls as cups of ``cachaca,'' a potent rum-like drink,
were handed out from trucks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
