<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MichaelJackson-School     02-07 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Michael Jackson-School,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Michael Jackson Visits Scene Of Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Xzavier in 9th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson thrilled hundreds of
youngsters Tuesday in a lightning visit to Cleveland Elementary
School, where five students were killed and 30 injured by a demented
drifter armed with a rifle.
   ``I think they'll remember this for a long time,'' said Stockton
Unified School District spokesman John Klose.
   Later, the entertainer paid a brief visit to San Joaquin General
Hospital, where two young victims of the attack are still being
treated.
   Hundreds of people gathered outside the school hoping to spot the
pop superstar, but he was whisked into a rear entrance in a
limousine and left the same way after about 20 minutes inside.
   He visited classrooms where kindergarten, first-, second- and
third-grade students were gathered, then dropped in on an assembly
of fourth- through sixth-graders. No reporters or photographers were
allowed to watch as Jackson met with the youngsters.
   ``He just smiled and that's it,'' said 6-year-old Lanisha, who
said she couldn't remember her last name. ``And then he left.''
   Hannah Schardt, 11, of Stockton, attends another school but came
with her mother to see Jackson.
   ``He just made a peace sign and left right away after about five
seconds,'' she said. ``He just kind of said `Hi' and nodded.''
   Barbara Knox of Stockton brought her 2-year-old son, Xzavier,
``to see Michael Jackson, to get a glimpse of him, his hair, his
glove, it doesn't matter.''
   Jackson, wearing a dark military-style jacket with red epaulets,
spent a few minutes at the hospital with Vann Sa, 7, and Long Keo, 6.
   ``It was not what I would call a dialogue,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Sharon Booker. ``It was an appearance. But five to seven
minutes with Michael Jackson _ what can you compare it to?''
   ``He was very warm, very pleasant with the children,'' said
Booker. ``They were very excited to see him.''
   Booker said Vann Sa would remain in the hospital for another week
or so; Long Keo was scheduled to be released Wednesday.
   Monday night, the Stockton City Council voted 9-0 for an
ordinance outlawing the possession or sale inside the city limits of
assault rifles like the Soviet-designed AK-47 that Patrick Edward
Purdy used to attack the school on Jan. 17 before when he killed
himself. The Los Angeles City Council voted likewise Tuesday.
   The Stockton ordinance is a misdemeanor carrying only a $500 fine
and a maximum of six months in jail, maximum penalties for a city
ordinance. It takes effect in seven days, after which any
semiautomatic weapon found in the city would be confiscated as
contraband and destroyed. Opponents said they would try to have the
ban overturned.
</TEXT>
