<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Organs     02-07 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Organs,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Plans To Ban Sale Of Human Organs For Transplants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain will ban the sale of human organs for
transplants, the government announced Tuesday after controversy over
the sales of kidneys by poor people in Turkey.
   Health minister Roger Freeman described the sale of human organs
as ``abhorrent and absolutely disgusting.''
   ``We are considering very urgently the need for legislation. We
are working on a draft bill. ... We take this very seriously and we
want to move quickly,'' Freeman said.
   Within hours, the private Humana Wellington Hospital in north
London, where kidney-for-sale transplants reportedly took place,
said it was suspending the kidney transplants. It denied it was
involved in payment to kidney donors.
   Ronald Hytoff, the hospital's executive director, said he looked
forward to legislation to ban the sale of transplant organs and to
official guidelines on transplants. He said hospital policy was to
use only organs from relatives.
   Investigations into the organ sales are being conducted by the
Department of Health and the profession's disciplinary body, the
General Medical Council, following news reports that a Turkish
organization had arranged the sale of kidneys.
   The Turkish press carried advertisements for donors, the reports
said.
   A West German businessman. Rainer Rebe Count Adelmann van
Adlemannsfelden, said on a British TV program on Jan. 28 that he
earned $8,650 for every organ deal he arranged abroad and he
expected to sell nearly 100 kidneys in 12 months.
</TEXT>
