<FIRST>u a AM-Husband-Guardian 1stLd-Writethru a0715 02-07 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Husband-Guardian, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband Named Guardian of Comatose, Pregnant Wife; Right-to-Lifers
Challenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with appeals court judge granting
stay; picks up 8th graf, `Upon hearing...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge empowered a man Tuesday to authorize
an abortion for his comatose wife in an effort to improve her
chances of recovery, but right-to-life advocates immediately moved
to overturn the decision.
   Three hours after state Supreme Court Justice Bernard McCaffrey
named Martin Klein as his wife's guardian, an appeals court judge
granted two anti-abortionists a stay blocking the ruling until an
appeals panel could review it.
   ``This has been very stressful and very tiring,'' said a
haggard-looking Klein, who had told reporters after the McCaffrey
decision that ``all I want to do is save my wife's life.''
   His wife, Nancy, 32, who is about 17 weeks pregnant, has been in
a coma at North Shore University Hospital in Manhasset since a Dec.
13 car accident.
   Klein, 34, of Upper Brookville, sought an abortion for his wife
after some physicians who examined her said an abortion could save
her life and assist in her recovery. The hospital told Klein it
would need a court order to perform the abortion.
   Appellate Division Judge Vincent Balletta Jr. granted the stay to
anti-abortion activists John Short of Farmingdale and John Broderick
of Syosset. The full Appellate Division will rule on the case by the
end of this week, he said.
   Balletta issued the stay despite an appeal from Elizabeth
Bradford of the state attorney general's office on behalf of Klein.
The two activists hope to become legal guardians of both Mrs. Klein
and the fetus to block the abortion.
   ``This case is not an abortion case, it's a guardianship case,''
said Ms. Bradford. ``Clearly, if Mrs. Klein was given the choice of
husband of nine years versus a stranger ... she would opt for her
husband.''
   Klein's attorney, Sidney Schutz, has labeled the pair
``interlopers in a private family tragedy.''
   Short, the founder of the Long Island Right-To-Life Committee,
said Mrs. Klein was ``closer to delivering a live child. I hope that
five years from now this child will be celebrating its fifth
birthday.''
   Earlier, McCaffrey issued his decision in a courtroom packed with
supporters and opponents of abortion, reporters and relatives.
   Upon hearing the decision, Klein kissed and embraced his wife's
parents, Anne and Frederick Zusselman of Delray Beach, Fla.
   McCaffrey's ruling followed a two-day hearing last week.
   The judge said that, based on medical testimony and records, Mrs.
Klein is incompetent and a guardian should be appointed.
   He gave Klein permission to authorize any medical procedures that
may be necessary to preserve his wife's life, specifically ruling
that Klein is authorized to approve an abortion.
   Five medical experts testified on Klein's behalf that pregnancy
increased the risks for the comatose patient and could possibly
threaten her life. But the Nassau County district attorney produced
medical experts who testified the pregnancy was not life-threatening.
   McCaffrey decided that an abortion was not medically necessary to
save Mrs. Klein's life.
   He noted that if Mrs. Klein were competent, it would be her sole
decision to continue or terminate the pregnancy up to a 24-week
period for any reason without a judicial determination. Under law, a
fetus is considered viable _ meaning it can survive outside the womb
_ after 24 weeks.
</TEXT>
