<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-Contras     02-07 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Contras,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Embassy Denies Involvement In Contra Leader's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua on Tuesday denied
allegations by two men charged in the slaying of a Nicaraguan rebel
leader that its diplomats planned the assassination.
   ``The accusations are ridiculous and completely removed from the
truth,'' said Nicaraguan Embassy spokesman Juan Jose Membrano. ``We
deny all involvement by our embassy in the assassination of the
Contra chief.''
   Manuel Rugama, the rebel commander, was shot and killed Jan. 7.
Luis Fernando Ordonez Reyes, one of the arrested, told an
army-arranged news conference Monday that ``the plan to eliminate
Rugama was prepared by the Nicaraguan Embassy in Tegucigalpa.''
   Rugama, a physician, was a regional commander of the U.S.-backed
rebels known as Contras and had been a rebel for nine years in the
war to bring down the leftist Sandinista government in Managua.
   Officers who found his body, riddled with 26 bullets, said he
apparently was alone when he was shot while driving on a highway
west of the Honduran capital.
   The Contras blamed the Nicaraguan government for Rugama's
slaying, saying he was scheduled to meet with other Contra leaders
that day.
   At the news conference, Ordonez said he introduced Jose de Jesus
Pena, whom he identified as the Nicaraguan Embassy security chief,
to one of his employees, a former police officer named Rigoberto
Matute.
   Ordonez, a Nicaraguan who operated a money exchange in
Tegucigalpa, said Pena often visited his business and paid him
between $500 and $1,500 for information about anti-Sandinista rebels
in Honduras.
   Membrano said the Nicaraguan Embassy has no security chief and
that no one named Jose de Jesus Pena worked there.
   Juan Bautista Nunez, a former detective for the Honduran National
Police, said at the news conference that Matute offered to pay him
$20,000 to help in the killing.
   ``I was the first to fire at Rugama,'' Bautista said. He said
Matute and a third man he knew only by his last name _ Cano Arteaga
_ then joined in killing Rugama.
   Matute, Nunez and Ordonez are being held in the killing. But
there was no indication why Matute did not attend the news
conference.
</TEXT>
