<FIRST>u a AM-TVPurchase     02-07 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Purchase,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama House Defeats Resolution Opposing State Purchase Of TV Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL POOVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A resolution opposing the purchase of
Montgomery's dominant commercial television station by the state
pension system failed to pass the Alabama House on Tuesday.
   The resolution was turned back after a debate pitting concern
over government control of the news media versus the possibility of
financial losses by the agency overseeing teacher and government
pensions.
   Gov. Guy Hunt filed a petition Monday with the Federal
Communications Commission to block the license transfer of WSFA-TV
to the Retirement Systems of Alabama, which has agreed to purchase
the station for $70 million.
   The House resolution, sponsored by Rep. Richard Laird of Roanoke,
required a four-fifths majority to pass. It got a majority, 33-27,
but not a big enough margin for approval.
   ``We too often have government entities financed with taxpayers'
money competing with the private sector, the free enterprise system.
That's the bottom line,'' Laird said of the purchase. ``It is wrong.
We need to keep government out of the free enterprise system.''
   Rep. Roy Johnson of Tuscaloosa urged the lawmakers to leave the
battle to Hunt and David Bronner, who is in charge of investing the
state pension system's $8 billion portfolio.
   Bronner has said the state pension system would lose $10 million,
now held in escrow, if the state defaults on the acquisition of WSFA
from Cosmos Broadcasting Inc. of Greenville, S.C.
   ``There's ... some concern on the part of literally thousands of
retirees across the state who look at the prospects of losing $10
million,'' Johnson said.
   But Rep. Morris ``Mo'' Brooks of Huntsville, said the transaction
strikes at ``the heart of democracy.''
   ``In no way should the state of Alabama, the United States of
America or any other governmental entity get into the business of
controlling, directly or indirectly, what can or cannot be printed
in our media or spoken on our news in the radio and TV markets,''
said Brooks.
</TEXT>
