<FIRST>r i AM-Geneva-Disarmament     02-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geneva-Disarmament,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Says Those Without Chemical Weapons Must Have Guarantees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France said Tuesday that global support for a ban
on chemical weapons depends on effective security guarantees for the
nations without them.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas told the 40-nation Geneva
disarmament conference quick agreement on that issue could convince
nations that now hesitate over the proposed treaty.
   Swedish delegate Maj Britt said at the first 1989 session the
conference is ``racing against time'' because ``further refinement,
development and spread of chemical weapons seriously undermine our
efforts.''
   A treaty can be ready ``in 1990 or even earlier'' if all
participants have the ``political will,'' she said.
   Dumas said it is ``absolutely crucial'' that a comprehensive
approach be taken to ``undiminished security'' for all countries
during the initial 10-year treaty period in which all stocks of
chemical weapons would be destroyed.
   That would require plans ranging from an order of destruction for
existing stocks to sanctions on countries ``which delay the process
or evade their obligactions,'' he declared.
   France has dropped a proposal, which obtained no other support,
that each country be allowed a ``security stock'' of chemical
weapons during the 10-year destruction period.
   The French abandoned the idea after President Francois Mitterrand
announced to the U.N. General Assembly last fall that his country
does not have chemical weapons and will not produce any when a
treaty takes effect.
   Dumas told a news conference Tuesday his government hopes the
Geneva negotiations, which began in 1980, will finish soon with a
treaty that can take effect quickly.
   Although it does not envisage production of chemical weapons, he
said, France must limit its commitments because ``it cannot exclude
a failure of the negotiations.''
   Tuesday's session began with an appeal by Javier Perez de
Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general, for more rapid progress.
   He said the special conference on chemical weapons, attended by
149 nations in Paris last month, reflected the world's consensus to
conclude a treaty ``at the earliest date.''
   ``I very much hope that this commitment, undertaken at such a
high political level, will accelerate the pace of your
negotiations,'' his message said.
   Max Friedersdorf, chief U.S. delegate, told the conference the
Paris meeting provided ``real impetus.''
   ``It is our challenge now to seize this moment and to search for
practical solutions to the problems that remain,'' he said in his
brief speech. Monitoring complience is ``clearly the major
difficulty,'' Friedersdorf said.
</TEXT>
