<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Nuclear     02-07 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Nuclear,0163</SECOND>
<UNK>1,000 Workers Strike At Nuclear Weapons Plant</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 workers went on strike at the
Aldermaston Atomic Weapons Research Establishment on Tuesday in a
pay dispute and formed a picket line outside the main gate, union
officials said.
   The Ministry of Defense confirmed the numbers involved.
   The plant, 45 miles west of London, produces nuclear weapons and
carries out research. Almost all its activity is secret, and labor
disputes are rare.
   Union officials said the walkout followed a breakdown of
negotiations on a new productivity agreement and the sending home of
about 50 staffers who refused to carry out tasks covered by the
existing contract.
   Bryan Reynolds, the plant's chief administration officer, said
there was no threat to safety and no risk of radioactive materials
leaking. He said the affected areas were maintenance, crafts,
cleaning and driving.
   The plant has been a target for demonstrations by the Campaign
for Nuclear Disarmament since 1958.
