<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Bombing     02-07 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Bombing,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Convicted In Retrial Of Killing Three In Train Station Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rochester, N.Y., man was found guilty of three
counts of first-degree murder Tuesday in the 1984 Labor Day bombing
of a train station that killed three people and injured 47 others.
   The 12-member jury convicted Thomas Brigham, a 69-year-old
drifter with a history of mental problems, in a retrial ordered
after his 1985 conviction was thrown out last June.
   Brigham smiled, stood and leaned against the prisoner's box
before giving a five-minute speech to the court after the verdict
was announced.
   ``I appreciate the great difficulty it has been for the jury,
court, police and the media to understand what happened,'' Brigham
said. ``I don't want the jury to feel bad about its decision,
because it really doesn't matter.''
   Judge Charles Phelan of the Quebec Superior Court sentenced
Brigham to the mandatory term of life imprisonment with no
eligibilty for parole for 25 years.
   Brigham, a father of 11 whose marriage ended in divorce after 28
years, has been held at the Pinel Institute for the criminally
insane in Montreal.
   Brigham told the court he has been doing a lot of writing in
Pinel and said ``the documents go to the White House, the Vatican
and Ottawa.''
   Witnesses during the two-week trial testified Brigham told them
before the Sept. 3, 1984 bombing that Pope John Paul II would never
make it to Montreal for his visit that was scheduled to begin that
Labor Day weekend.
   Witnesses also said Brigham told them: ``If you hear of an
explosion, you will know it was me.''
   A powerful pipe bomb hidden in a locker exploded in Central
Station, Montreal's main train station, killing three French
tourists.
   Brigham was arrested hours after the bombing and the pope visited
Montreal the next day as scheduled.
   In the May 1985 trial, Brigham's ex-wife, Marjorie Keenan,
testified he was committed to psychiatric hospitals four times since
1975 because he believed he was Jesus Christ and had other delusions.
   Brigham was declared mentally incompetent by an Ohio court in
1973.
   Authorities said U.S. records showed he was a
bombardier-navigator in the U.S. Army Air Force during World War II.
His plane was shot down and he was held prisoner in Nazi Germany for
one year.
   Several witnesses during the retrial testified that Brigham
claimed to be a writer and said cosmic voices warned him of such
disasters as the eruption of the Mount St. Helens volcano in 1980,
which left 57 people dead or missing.
   After Tuesday's verdict, Brigham continued to prophesize that the
Soviet policy of glasnost, or openness, signaled a more peaceful
world by the year 2001, telling the court that people had 12 years
to adjust.
   At his first trial, Brigham also was convicted of three counts of
first-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison. Last June, the
Quebec Court of Appeal ordered a new trial, citing four errors made
by the presiding judge.
   Brigham was found competent to stand trial on the charges, and
the defense did not plead insanity.
</TEXT>
