<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Election     02-07 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Election,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Counsels Against Rebel Election Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister argued
Tuesday against accepting a rebel proposal to delay the March 19
presidential election and said he thought the rebels were trying to
drive a wedge between the military and civilians.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti Liberation Front said earlier Tuesday
that the armed forces make up the ``real power'' in El Salvador and
that the proposal would fail without military support.
   The defense chief, Gen. Carlos Eugenio Vides Casanova, said
postponing the election from March to September, as the rebels
suggested, could mean defeat for mainstream presidential candidates
and hamper the military in its 9-year-old war against the leftist
guerrillas.
   On Friday, U.S. Vice President Dan Quayle said during a one-day
visit to El Salvador that the Bush administration will back
President Jose Napoleon Duarte if he agrees to the rebel request for
a six-month election postponement.
   Duarte initially attacked the rebels' Jan. 23 proposal as
unconstitutional because it would change the constitutionally
mandated March election date.
   U.S. officials, however, felt the proposal was worth looking into
because of the insurgents' first-ever offer to join the election
process without demanding power-sharing as a precondition.
   In a telephone call from Nicaragua broadcast by a local radio
station, a rebel spokesman on Tuesday read a statement asking the
armed forces to take a public position on postponing the election.
   Vides Casanova obliged during a news conference.
   He said the armed forces do not ``believe this is a serious
proposal.''
   ``If you want your candidates to lose, go ahead and do it,'' he
said in remarks directed to politicians now considering the
postponement.
   El Salvador's political parties are trying to arrive at a joint
position on the rebel proposal.
   Vides Casanova said the military would stand behind whatever
decision political leaders reached but he cautioned that postponing
the election would ``hand over all the advantages'' to the left.
   The Farabundo Marti offered to abandon its longstanding election
boycott and take an indirect role in the electoral process if
balloting is postponed six months. The rebels said they would abide
by election results if their conditions are met.
   They added an offer to negotiate a 60-day cease-fire with the
armed forces in the broadcast Tuesday.
   Vides Casanova said he suspected the rebels of a ``divide and
conquer'' strategy.
   ``We think they are trying to create a division between the armed
forces and the organs of state and an internal division within the
armed forces,'' he said.
   By the Farabundo Marti's own assessment, Vides Casanova's
negative reaction to the rebel proposal could sound the death knell
for the plan.
   ``If this proposal could really bring peace to the nation, we
would be obliged to accept it,'' the general said. ``But it is our
judgment that it is not going to bring peace, that it is only going
to aggravate ... conditions in the country.''
</TEXT>
