<DOCNO> AP890207-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StrandedDancers     02-07 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stranded Dancers,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gifts Pour in for Stranded Soviet Dancers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donated meals and gifts poured in Tuesday for a
Soviet ballet troupe whose U.S. debut tour is in danger of
cancellation after the pullout of top investors.
   Organizers of the 15-city tour announced the Donetsk Ballet from
the Ukraine would give a ``Thank You, Baltimore'' fund-raising
performance Wednesday so the dancers, most under age 25, can
continue their performances through April as scheduled.
   As producer Jan Urdzik of California-based Heart of the Art Inc.
met with Soviet Embassy representatives, troupe officials and a
member of Goskontsert, the Soviet concert managers, meals, snacks
and gifts arrived at the downtown hotel where the dancers were
staying.
   Vadim Pisarev, the ballet's top soloist, wearing fur leg warmers
as he sat by a flower-filled Russian champagne bottle at the hotel,
expressed his gratitude.
   ``I am very happy with the people of Baltimore,'' he said,
showing a letter signed by ``an adoring ballet fan'' in Baltimore,
comparing him to two of the greatest Russian male dancers, Mikhail
Baryshnikov and Rudolf Nureyev. With it, the man enclosed a gold
pinky ring he'd received years ago from his wife.
   ``You, sir, are among the stars and a worthy successor to the
others,'' the fan wrote.
   Pisarev, 24, earned the 1988 prize for best dancer in the Soviet
Union and won the gold medal at the prestigious International Ballet
Competition in Jackson, Miss., in 1986.
   Despite his prominence, good reviews and standing ovations from
small Baltimore audiences last week, Mexican and American investors
withheld $200,000 from the tour upon learning that stars from
well-known Soviet troupes such as the Kirov Ballet could not leave
the Soviet Union to join the tour, organizers said.
   The dancers were scheduled for performances in Detroit, Chicago,
and Columbus, Ohio.
   As Ms. Urdzik tried to extend the group's stay in Baltimore to
Thursday, the Howard Gilman Foundation of New York pledged an
undisclosed sum and worked to attract other donors to save the
troupe from loss of face on its American tour.
   ``This was one year in planning with no salary,'' said Ms.
Urdzik, who also promoted a Moscow Ballet tour in 1987. ``My home is
on the line,'' because she committed her own money to the project,
she said.
   ``They (the Soviets) don't understand business in America,'' she
said, referring to the decision to keep the Kirov stars away and its
impact on private funding, as opposed to the state-supported arts in
communist countries. Meanwhile, the dancers had dinner Tuesday at
the Belvedere Hotel courtesy of Anne C. Dodds of St. Louis, who
donated $1,000. Baltimore fans dropped off cases of vodka, and Lyric
Opera president Robert M. Pomory said he would pay the group's hotel
bill for two days.
   ``Morale is very good; these kids are really troopers,'' Pomory
said.
   Lyric workers donated fruit and breakfasts and the Belvedere
provided two dinners, at a cost of about $500, managing director Joe
Kreit said, noting the dancers ate such typical American fare as
turkey with gravy and chocolate cake.
   ``When they see chocolate cake, they forget about everything
else,'' Kreit said.
   The Lyric underwrote some hotel expenses, which were discounted
as a courtesy, but Pomory, who moved into the hotel to watch over
the dancers, said he was donating some of his own money to help.
   ``If I had room in my house I'd take them all home,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
