<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Military     02-07 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Military,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC: US Preparing Latin Anti-Drug Moves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush Administration is preparing a major
drug interdiction plan that will put ``several hundred'' U.S. troops
in South America to destroy drug laboratories, NBC News reported
Tuesday.
   Citing unidentified Pentagon officials for the information, NBC
reported that the troops would be Special Operations commandos who
will be placed in several South American nations.
   The Pentagon duty officer Tuesday night, Cmdr. David Thomas, said
he was unaware of any such plans.
   Meanwhile, a Defense Department source, speaking on grounds of
anonymity, said the Pentagon has named two Coast Guard admirals to
key leadership positions in the department's expanded drug
interdiction mission as called for in the 1989 Defense Authorization
Act.
   Rear Adm. William P. Leahy Jr. will head the drug interdiction
efforts in the Pacific Theater, while Vice Adm. James C. Irwin will
lead those efforts in the Atlantic, the source said. They will be
supervised by the commanders in chief of the Pacific and Atlantic
commands.
   The Pentagon also anticipates placing high-ranking U.S. Customs
Service officials in other key leadership roles in the
drug-interdiction efforts, the source said.
   The authorization act included $300 million for the Pentagon's
new drug-interdiction tasks that were added to the supporting role
it has played for several years.
   Those tasks include serving as the federal government's lead
agency for detection and monitoring of aerial and maritime transport
of illegal drugs into the United States.
   The Pentagon also is to create an effective communications
network by integrating communications supporting U.S. command,
control, communications and technical intelligence assets dedicated
to drug interdiction.
   In addition, the Pentagon is to approve and fund plans by state
governors for expanded use of the National Guard to support
drug-enforcement activities while the Guard remains under the
control of the governors.
</TEXT>
