<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-07 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dome of Arctic Air Covers Most of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the nation was under a dome of arctic air on Tuesday with
the coldest spots in California, Colorado and Utah, where readings
were as low as minus 50.
   Several record lows were set or tied, including one in Richfield,
Utah, which for the second straight day reached its all-time low of
33 degrees below zero.
   Other record lows in Utah were recorded in Delta, minus 27, and
Dugway, minus 29. Record-tying lows were set in Bryce Canyon, Utah,
minus 32 and Vernal, Utah, minus 38.
   Utah's low was 50 below at Logan Canyon. Roosevelt and Woodruff
both recorded minus 44.
   Numerous records were also set in California. Travis Air Force
base at Fairfield recorded 24 degrees, a record low for February,
and Boca Reservoir near Truckee was 43 degrees below zero, the
coldest February reading ever in California and 2 degrees shy of the
state's all-time low.
   Other records lows for the date included: Alexandria, La., 23
degrees; Bakersfield, Calif., 26; Colorado Springs, Colo., minus 11;
Ely, Nev., minus 29; Eugene, Ore., 7; Fresno, Calif., 24; Las Vegas,
16; Oakland, Calif., 34; Reno, Nev., minus 16; Sacramento, Calif.,
23; San Francisco, 34; and Seattle, 20.
   The cold air extended to Brownsville, Texas, which had 28
consecutive hours below freezing.
   Strong, gusty winds in the northern Plains caused blowing snow
conditions and reduced visibilities to near zero in some areas.
   Lake-effect snow continued across eastern portions of the lower
Great Lakes over New York state. Some 9.5 inches fell in Buffalo.
   Showers and some thunderstorms were scattered ahead of a cold
front from northwest Florida to eastern North Carolina.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11
degrees below zero at Baker, Ore., to 84 degrees at Avon Park, Fla.
The low in the nation Tuesday morning was 50 degrees below zero at
Logan Canyon, Utah.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for rain showers scattered over
northern Florida and coastal sections of southern California and
rain along with some freezing rain scattered over portions of
Alabama and Mississippi. Snow showers were expected over northern
portions of the upper Great Lakes, all of the lower Great Lakes and
northern New England. Winds were to be strong and gusty along the
east slopes of the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were to remain below zero over northern
Minnesota; in the single digits over much of the upper Mississippi
Valley, the northern Plains, western Wyoming and southeast Idaho; in
the teens and 20s from the northern and central Intermountain
region, the northern and central Rockies, the central Plains,
Oklahoma, the middle Mississippi Valley, Arkansas, much of the Great
Lakes and the Ohio Valley to northern New England; in the 50s and
60s over coastal sections of central and southern California,
southern Arizona, northern Florida, southern Georgia and coastal
portions of the Carolinas; and in the 70s and 80s over the southern
Florida peninsula. Much of the remainder of the nation was expected
to have high temperatures in the 30s and 40s.
</TEXT>
