<HEAD>Winner Says He Will Go On Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who won nearly $7
million playing the California lottery said Tuesday he plans to go
away to a retreat and reflect on God's will.
   Father Boleslaw Wdowiak, who goes by the nickname ``Father
Bosco,'' said he was ``happy, confused and thankful the Lord has
been good to me all of my life.''
   ``I have tried to serve him as a priest and this I will continue
to do. Because of the new responsibilities the prize creates for me,
I'm going away on retreat to pray and reflect on God's will for
me,'' he told a reporter.
   Wdowiak, a priest at St. Joseph's Parish in Auburn, will receive
his prize in 20 annual payments of $276,000 after taxes. He won the
jackpot in last Saturday's Lotto 6-49 drawing with a ``Quick Pick''
ticket, in which a computer randomly selects the player's numbers.
   Auburn is a Sierra Nevada foothills community about 100 air miles
northeast of San Francisco.
