<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strike     02-07 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strike,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Strike Over Pay in Central Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 workers have gone on strike for
higher pay at a coal mine and electric power plant in central
Poland, government and union spokesmen said Tuesday.
   The stoppage began Monday at the Belchatow brown coal mine and
power plant about 90 miles southwest of Warsaw. But it has not
interrupted electric service provided by the plant, one of the
largest generating stations in Poland.
   On strike are employees in the plant's repair department and
workers who deliver coal to the power station from the mine, said
government spokesman Jerzy Urban.
   They are seeking pay increases of $59 a month, an amount
considered ``unfeasible'' by management, the state PAP news service
said. It was not immediately known what the workers' current wages
are.
   The mine continued to function Tuesday during negotiations with
management, said Wojciech Maziarski, a spokesman in Warsaw for the
outlawed Solidarity trade union movement. But workers have
threatened to shut down the mine beginning Wednesday unless their
demands are met, he said.
   Maziarski said the Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, meeting with
communist government officials in an effort to legalize the
organization, is sending two personal representatives to the
strikers, presumably to try to moderate in the dispute.
   Urban said the strike was symptomatic of ``alarming'' wage
pressures breaking out across Poland. He said 173 pay disputes were
reported to the government in January, compared to about a third
that number in December.
   Thirty-nine of the January disputes resulted in strikes, the
longest lasting four days, he said.
   ``The government consistently applies the principle that these
disputes are between the management and the workers, and the
management should pay as much as it can'' without threatening an
enterprise's finances, Urban said.
</TEXT>
