<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoralDebate 1stLd-Writethru a0737 02-07 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral Debate, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0737,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayoral Candidates Head Into Only Three-Way Debate Before Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with comments from the debate.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, `But one...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer denied he is beholden to the
City Council members who elected him, saying Tuesday in the city's
only mayoral campaign debate that ``nobody has pushed me around.''
   Sawyer went on the defensive quickly in the televised debate with
front-running Richard Daley, the Cook County state's attorney and
son of the late longtime Mayor Richard J. Daley.
   Alderman Lawrence Bloom, a long-shot challenger, opened by
attacking Sawyer. He contended the mayor's policies have been swayed
by old-guard aldermen who elected him 14 months ago and are
resistant to reform.
   ``Nobody has pushed me around, nobody will push me around,''
Sawyer countered at the start of the live debate televised by public
TV station WTTW.
   Bloom also charged that electing either Sawyer or Daley probably
will racially polarize the city.
   ``People say, `White people are voting for Daley becuase he's
white ... black people are voting for Sawyer because he's black,'''
Bloom said, maintaining that he, a white alderman from the heavily
black South Side, is the only candidate who can unite the city.
   Despite repeated complaints from Bloom that he was not answering
the questions, Daley refused to spar, saying the public was
concerned about issues, such as education, crime, housing and taxes.
   ``They're sick and tired of a council fighting ... the personal
attacks,'' he said. ``People are saying `Let's get on and talk about
the real issues.'''
   The 90-minute debate was the only one scheduled among the three
candidates before the Feb. 28 Democratic primary.
   Bloom, 45, had the most to gain from the debate, observers said
prior to the event.
   ``Let's just say it's very important,'' said Michael Meshenberg,
Bloom's campaign coordinator.
   Sawyer, 54, had a technical advantage as the winner of two
drawings that enabled him to deliver the opening and closing
statements.
   But one pundit said Sawyer may have hurt his chances by
unleashing a series of TV ads criticizing Daley's intelligence on
Monday.
   ``The debate is overrated. But Sawyer raised the stakes by those
commercials. And in effect Daley can put him away by not doing
anything more than acting like a regular candidate,'' said Paul
Green, a political analyst at suburban Governor's State University.
   Sawyer's strategists defended the commercials Tuesday.
   ``People have enjoyed the humor'' in the ads, said Horist. ``The
humor, however, is designed to draw attention to the point _ that
Daley is a trained candidate, that he is being handled.''
   Halperin said the the 44-year-old Daley, who is white, was
confident, but not complacent because of his front-runner status.
   Recent polls have shown Daley with a commanding lead. Support for
the county's top prosecutor has been hovering at about 50 percent,
against about 30 percent for Sawyer, 10 percent for Bloom and 10
percent undecided. The winner of the primary will face independent
candidate Alderman Timothy Evans and the Republican candidate chosen
in the GOP primary in an April 4 special election to serve the
two-year balance of the late Mayor Harold Washington's unfinished
term. Washington died of a heart attack in November 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
