<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Libya     02-07 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Chemical Plant Owner Said To Be Consultant To Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman under criminal
investigation in the Libyan chemical plant case said he has been a
consultant for the North African nation since 1984, the West German
news magazine Stern said Tuesday.
   Stern also quoted Iraqi-born Ihsan Barbouti, owner of the
now-defunct Frankfurt company I.B.I. Engineering, as saying he is an
avid admirer of radical Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   ``If you really understood him, you would idolize him,'' Stern
quoted Barbouti as saying.
   Barbouti said he has had a five-year consultancy contract with
Libya's Energy Ministry since 1984 and that Libya has approached him
about renewing it, according to the magazine.
   Barbouti said he receives about $266,000 from Libya a year
``whether I do anything or not'' and is provided a 16-room house,
six servants and a ``great chef'' on his visits to Tripoli, the
Libyan capital, Stern said.
   Stern said its report would appear in its Thursday editions. The
magazine telexed the report to other news organizations in advance
of publication.
   Alleged participation by German firms in helping Libya build a
suspected poison gas factory has embarrassed the Bonn government and
strained U.S.-West German ties. Washington says the plant at Rabta,
60 miles south of Tripoli, can make chemical weapons. Libya says the
plant produces pharmaceuticals.
   Barbouti, who lives in London, is suspected of organizing
involvement by several West German companies in building the plant.
   Stern quoted Barbouti as acknowledging that his company delivered
construction materials for the Libyan plant but as denying the
factory was for producing poison gases or that he had done anything
wrong.
   In 1986, Barbouti told his company manager at I.B.I. Engineering
that ``Libya wants certain construction materials for a
pharmaceuticals project,'' Stern reported. The company closed down
its office in Frankfurt last summer.
   According to Barbouti, Libya plans to produce ``about 40
different pharmaceutical products'' at the Rabta complex for sale to
European and Arab countries, Stern reported.
   Barbouti said he was last in Tripoli in January, according to
Stern.
</TEXT>
