<FIRST>r a AM-MichaelReagan     02-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Michael Reagan,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Officer Will Decide Whether to Charge Michael Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Reagan, the former
president's son, met Tuesday with a hearing officer who will decide
whether he should be prosecuted for allegedly making a threatening
call to a photographer.
   Reagan, 43, arrived for the hearing at the City Attorney's Office
with his sister, Maureen, said office spokesman Ted Goldstein.
   ``She was here for moral support for her brother,'' Goldstein
said.
   Reagan and free-lance photojournalist Roger Sandler, who filed a
criminal complaint against him, attended a 35-minute meeting with
court hearing officer Connie Seim.
   ``It seemed to be a civil, congenial meeting. The door was
open,'' Goldstein said.
   Seim will decide within 10 days whether Reagan should be charged
with a misdemeanor crime, Goldstein said.
   Details of the meeting were not disclosed.
   Afterwards, Reagan and his sister were met by photographers as
they tried to leave, but Maureen Reagan blocked a stairwell to
prevent them from pursuing her brother, Goldstein said.
   Sandler filed his complaint after a caller identifying himself as
Reagan left an obscene and threatening message on Sandler's
answering machine Jan. 15.
   The caller threatened Sandler with physical harm and said ``I
hope your (expletive) family dies in a plane crash with you in it.''
   Reagan has acknowledged leaving a message on Sandler's machine
and apologized.
   ``I lost my cool, which I should not have done,'' Reagan said.
   The call was made after Reagan received a subpoena from Sandler.
In a small claims action, the photographer is seeking $1,500 for
copyright infringement over the use of two pictures in Reagan's 1988
book, ``On the Outside Looking In.''
   Under California law, it is a misdemeanor for a person to call
another individual with intent to annoy and use obscene language or
threaten to inflict injury. The charge carries a maximum six-month
jail term and a $1,000 fine upon conviction.
</TEXT>
