<FIRST>r i AM-NewGuinea-Rampage     02-07 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Guinea-Rampage,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Rampage In Pay Grievance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of troops
infuriated over the size of a pay award rampaged through the streets
of the capital Wednesday, assaulting people and destroying
government property and a police vehicle.
   Witnesses said the soldiers blocked traffic and attacked
journalists who tried to cover the rally and stole their cameras.
Local radio said police fired tear gas to disperse the troops when
they arrived at Parliament House from the Murray Barracks.
   The reports said the soldiers tore up trees and plants and
smashed traffic signals as the government met in emergency session
to discuss their grievances.
   The witnesses spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Australian Associated Press said the soldiers were angry over a
pay raise they claimed benefited only officers. It said the pay
increase was the first since independence in 1975. It gave no
comparative figures.
   Prime Minister Rabbie Namaliu was out of town but was reported
flying back to Port Moresby because of the outbreak.
   A former U.N. Australian trust territory, Papua New Guinea became
a fully independent state on Sept. 16, 1975. Its more than 3 million
inhabitants occupy the east half of New Guinea island and nearby
islands in the southwest Pacific.
