<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0652 02-07 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Bomb Blast Damages Honduran Telephone Exchange</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with leftist group claiming responsibility for
shooting at U.S. convoy.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in the northern city
of San Pedro Sula on Tuesday, damaging a telephone exchange and
nearby buildings. A leftist terrorist group claimed responsibility.
   No one was hurt in the pre-dawn blast and one man found under
suspicious circumstances in the area was arrested for questioning,
according to police sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. The
sources refused to elaborate.
   Isidoro Martinez, the telephone company manager, said in a
telephone interview the explosion at 4:45 a.m. (5:45 a.m. EST) badly
damaged the two-story exchange building, a movie theater on the
first floor and a hospital across the street.
   The blast also smashed window panes in the area, Martinez said.
   Martinez said the explosion caused more than $25,000 in damage
and cut communications service in a large area in San Pedro Sulas,
Honduras' second-largest city about 125 miles north of Tegucigalpa.
He said it will take about a week to restore service.
   An anonymous telephone call to San Pedro Sula's Radio Norte a few
hours later said the ``Cinchonero'' Popular Liberation Movement, a
small leftist terrorist group, claimed responsibility for the attack.
   The group has claimed responsibility for kidnappings,
assassinations and bombings in Honduras in the past eight years, and
such anonymous claims have usually turned out to be true.
   ``Cinchonero'' is Spanish slang for a make of horse saddle-belts
and the group takes its name from Serapio Romero, a saddle-belt
maker who led an abortive peasant revolution and was executed by
firing squad in 1869.
   The ``Cinchoneros'' and other small leftist groups have been
protesting the Honduran government's policy of supporting the United
State in trying to isolate the leftist Sandinista government in
neighboring Nicaragua.
   The U.S.-supported Contra rebels, fighting the Sandinistas for
the past seven years, are allowed by the military to keep supply and
training bases inside Honduras, along the Nicaraguan border.
   As part of that police, the United States maintains a permanent
military presence in Honduras and troops hold joint exercises
regularly.
   Also Tuesday, a leftist group claimed responsiblity for a
shooting attack last week on a convoy of about 30 U.S. soldiers.
   ``We will not rest until we have kicked out all the Yankee
troops,'' an anonymous caller, claiming to be a member of the
Morazanist Patriotic Front, told The Associated Press on Tuesday.
   No one was injured in the Feb. 1 incident in Yoro province, about
125 miles of Tegucigalpa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890207-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FinancialFlight     02-07 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Financial Flight,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Adviser Pleads Guilty To Embezzlement, Wire Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial planner Henry Gherman, who fled to the Far
East last summer with nearly $10 million in investors' money,
pleaded guilty Tuesday to federal embezzlement and mail fraud
charges.
   Under a plea bargain agreement negotiated by federal officials
and Gherman's attorney, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark,
the defendant faces a possible maximum penalty of 35 years in prison.
   Gherman, 52, also could be fined $1.75 million. The question of
restitution depends on bankruptcy court proceedings, according to
U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Crockett.
   Although Gherman was arrested in Tokyo in early October 1988 and
was returned to Miami late last December, he had never been indicted
by a federal grand jury when plea negotiations got under way.
   The plea agreement was filed Tuesday with the U.S. Attorney's
office, and is subject to approval by a federal judge, who will hand
down the actual sentence.
   The court document charged that Gherman ``willfully and
unlawfully devised a scheme to defraud, obtain money and property
from clients'' of Financial and Investment Planning Inc. in North
Miami Beach.
   At one point, the document said, Gherman made false claims to
solicit funds from clients, most of them prominent southern Florida
physicians.
   From December 1982 to August 1983, Gherman embezzled
approximately $9.8 million in funds entrusted to him, according to
the information. Of those funds, about $7.5 million were from
retirement plans he set up for clients, the document said.
   Soon after fleeing the United States early last August, he set up
offshore bank accounts at the Swiss-American National Bank in
Antigua, West Indies, to transfer and launder the embezzled money,
the document said.
   But even as he entered the guilty plea, Gherman told U.S.
District Judge Stanley Marcus, ``I didn't solicit any money. The
money did go into'' Financial and Investment Planning.
   ``I'm guilty of all the charges, but I was not hustling money. I
didn't go out and live it up.''
   Gherman, who had left behind photocopied notes apologizing to his
clients, was first located in Taiwan and later arrested at a posh
Tokyo hotel.
   ``With this guilty plea the ends of justice have been served,''
said Dexter Lehtinen, U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of
Florida. ``This is a very stiff possible sentence for white-collar
crime.''
   The judge set sentencing for April 26.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
