<DOCNO> AP890207-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-RadarShutsDown Adv12   02-07 1268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Radar Shuts Down, Adv12,1296</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Air Force Locates $90 Million Radar Too Close to Runway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the control tower at Robins Air Force Base,
Master Sgt. George Green asks a key question when the pilot of any
fighter, attack or bomber aircraft seeks permission for an
unscheduled landing at the airfield in central Georgia.
   ``Are you carrying external electroexplosive devices?''
   If the answer is yes, chief controller Green picks up a direct
line to the operator of the PAVE PAWS radar installation two miles
south of the airfield.
   The radar operator flips a switch, and for several minutes until
the plane lands safely, one-half of the $90 million radar, built to
provide instantaneous warning of any submarine-launched missile off
the southeastern United States, is shut down.
   Since November 1987, the Air Force now acknowledges, the north
face of PAVE PAWS at Robins has been turned off an average of 14
times a month _ for a total down time of about an hour a month _ to
allow planes carrying externally mounted EEDs to land.
   The interruptions in the operation of the high-tech strategic
defense system are intended to avoid accidental detonations of the
EEDs, tiny explosive charges that are found in virtually every
military weapons system and in the planes and ships that deliver
them.
   EEDs are used, among other things, to trigger weapons, drop
bombs, or jettison fuel tanks. They normally are detonated by an
electrical circuit, but they also can be set off by high levels of
electromagnetic energy from such environmental sources as radio
waves, radar emissions, static electricity and lightning.
   The Air Force insists that the periodic interruptions of the
Robins PAVE PAWS have not hindered the effectiveness of the nation's
early warning system, because the shutdowns are random and other
radars are available as backups. Routine maintenance, the Air Force
says, shuts the radar down for about 40 hours a month.
   ``Our primary concern at Robins with PAVE PAWS is safety of
flight,'' said Lt. Col. John Harmon, commander of the base
communications squadron. ``We want to make sure that we have
procedures in effect so there is no possibility of any plane having
externally mounted EEDs flying in a dangerous situation.''
   PAVE PAWS stands for Precision Acquisition Vehicle Entry Phased
Array Warning System. The 10-story, pyramid shaped installation at
Robins, one of four PAVE PAWS facilities nationwide, consists of
thousands of computer-directed antennas that can scan 240 degrees
for 3,000 miles. The radar reportedly can identify an object the
size of a basketball 1,500 miles away.
   The radar near Robins is the only one located near an active
runway; there have been no problems reported near the others.
   PAVE PAWS had been in operation for a year at Robins before top
Air Force officials became convinced that its powerful
electromagnetic emissions might endanger their aircraft.
   They then instituted the periodic shutdown procedures and
established a restricted zone around the radar of one nautical mile,
about 6,000 feet, for all aircraft flying at or below 6,400 feet.
   The Air Force contends it has taken a conservative, safety
conscious approach at Robins. But critics, such as Patricia Axelrod,
coordinator of the HERO Project, charge that the location of the
radar, near a runway and a base where ordnance is handled, is a
disaster waiting to happen. The air base, Georgia's largest, is
located near the community of Warner-Robins, population 40,000.
   The HERO Project, which derives its name from the Navy acronym
Hazard of Electromagnetic Radiation to Ordnance, is part of a
coalition that has filed suit in federal court in Washington
alleging that the military has not shielded its weaponry
sufficiently to prevent accidents.
   Axelrod, and the defense specialists who are assisting her in the
lawsuit, contend that the 6,000-foot hazard zone around PAVE PAWS is
not sufficient. She cited Navy documents recommending that the EA-6
Prowler airplane, laden with electronic-warfare equipment far less
powerful than PAVE PAWS, be kept at least 8,000 feet away from areas
where ordnance is handled.
   Axelrod also argues that the flight restrictions at Robins force
pilots into ``a trapeze act without a net'' because of the
possibility of human error in the chain of communication required to
shut down the radar when an at-risk plane is landing.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, also has criticized the restrictions because of their
reliance ``on the potentially fallible human links between the
pilot, control tower, and PAVE PAWS radar operators.''
   Nunn has asked the Air Force for an official evaluation of the
potential hazards of the radar emissions to aircraft flight safety
at Robins and the long-term adequacy of the current procedures for
minimizing that hazard.
   Lt. Gen. Donald J. Kutyna, who heads the Air Force Space Command
that has jurisdiction over PAVE PAWS, acknowledged in a recent
interview that he would rather have the radar someplace else.
   ``Based on what I know today, the radar may not hurt anything,
but there is some concern, otherwise there wouldn't be any flight
restrictions,'' he said. ``If I had the choice, all things being
equal, I would put the radar where I would not have to impose any
safety zone.''
   The Air Force said the initial environmental assessment for PAVE
PAWS concluded that the restricted zone needed around the radar
would not interfere with the flight paths of any aircraft using the
Robins runway.
   That conclusion was changed in 1987 when new calculations were
done while the Air Force was developing plans to triple the power of
PAVE PAWS to enhance its other mission, tracking satellites in
space. The new calculations indicated that a larger restricted zone
was needed.
   The key difference in the new calculation was the way the radar's
power was determined. The first assessment used the average power of
the radar pulses over time, while the later one used the peak power
of each pulse.
   Air Force officials acknowledge that the contractor who did the
initial assessment recommended using peak power to calculate the
restricted zone. The recommendation was rejected because Air Force
experts at the time did not believe brief exposure of and EED to the
radar pulses would constitute a hazard.
   ``We were on the cutting edge of technology with PAVE PAWS at the
time we made that initial environmental assessment,'' Kutyna said.
``To have learned something new since that time does not say that
you were making a mistake before.''
   The Air Force already has spent $600,000 on a study of the
problem by the Raytheon Corp., which built the radar system. The
study recommended moving the installation, at a cost of $37.7
million, or modifying it, at a cost of $27 million, so it would shut
down automatically if a plane breached the restricted zone.
   Kutyna said moving the radar is not a viable option but the
modification proposal remains under consideration. He said a panel
of senior Air Force officers has been convened to make
recommendations by June on a permanent solution that will end the
flight restrictions.
   In the meantime, the Air Force has shelved plans to triple the
radar's power so it could take over the space tracking functions of
the outdated radar system at Eglin Air Force Base in Florida, at an
annual savings of $11 million.
   ``Unless there is a solution in the books that comes out of this
study, I would say the chances of putting that upgrade on there at
this time are not high,'' Kutyna said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 12</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
