<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GAFTrial     02-07 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Trial,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jefferies Says GAF Arranged Stock Fix; Defense Charges Evidence Destruction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense in the first Wall Street fraud case
to go to trial is suggesting that disgraced broker and star
prosecution witness Boyd L. Jefferies may have obstructed justice
with the government's knowledge.
   Defense attorney Arthur Liman asserted in the GAF Corp. stock
manipulation case Monday that Jefferies threw out notes about his
dealings in violation of a subpoena and shortly after reaching a
plea agreement with the government.
   Liman implied before a federal jury that Jefferies intentionally
disposed of daily notes he wrote on yellow legal pads.
   Nervous under cross-examination, Jefferies said he had informed
prosecutors he was going to clear out his office.
   ``No one said you had to preserve the yellow pads?'' Liman asked.
   ``Not that I recall,'' the witness said.
   Jefferies, 58, also testified anew that GAF in October 1986 asked
him and his Los Angeles-based securities firm to manipulate the
stock price of Union Carbide Corp. and agreed to pay $40,000 to
cover losses in the deal.
   The case in federal court in Manhattan has been viewed as a key
test of the government's ability to obtain criminal convictions from
a spinoff of the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal.
   U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe last month declared a
mistrial in the case after concluding that prosecutors withheld a
key piece of evidence from the defense.
   GAF, a manufacturer of specialty chemicals and building
materials, and its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin, were indicted
last July for allegedly trying to inflate the price of Union Carbide
stock.
   The purpose of the alleged manipulation was to maximize GAF's
gain from the sale of its holding in Carbide after a failed attempt
to take over the much larger chemical company.
   Appearing confident under questioning from Assistant U.S.
Attorney Carl Loewenson Jr., Jefferies said he bought shares of
Union Carbide in late October 1986 at Sherwin's request to boost the
price to $22 a share. Sherwin guaranteed to cover any losses
sustained by Jefferies &amp; Co.
   ``Mr. Sherwin said if we wanted Union Carbide to close at a
specific price or higher for a few days, do you think you will be
able to do that? I said yes,'' Jefferies testified.
   Jeffries offered similar testimony at the original trial.
   Under cross-examination, Jefferies testified that on March 30,
1987, he emptied his office of notes on his daily activities after
October 1986. Liman seized on the matter to point out that Jefferies
earlier that month had agreed to cooperate with the government.
   Liman said Jefferies' subpoena from the Securities and Exchange
Commission called for all notes relevant to his activities from
January 1984 to the present.
   ``Are you saying that you don't recall whether you threw out
notes that were under subpoena?,'' Liman asked.
   ``I know I did not throw out anything when I left the company on
March 30 that pertained to any request from the government, from the
SEC,'' Jefferies countered. ``I have nothing to hide, Mr. Liman.''
   Possibly seeking to question the government's relationship with
Jefferies, Liman said destroying subpoenaed notes would constitute
obstruction of justice and said Jefferies had not been granted
immunity for destroying the notes.
   Jefferies struck a plea agreement with the government after he
was implicated in the scandal with Boesky, the jailed speculator who
agreed to turn state's evidence in late 1986.
   Jefferies agreed to plead guilty in March 1987 two securities law
violations, to quit his brokerage and to stay out of the securities
business for at least five years. He awaits sentencing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
