<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 0330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BankAmerica Bjt   02-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BankAmerica, Bjt,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Dividend In 3 Years Signals Confidence In Turnaround</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp.'s decision to resume paying
dividends to stockholders signals management's confidence that the
company has bounced back from three years of losses, the bank's top
executive said.
   The holding company for Bank of America, the nation's
third-largest bank, announced Monday it would pay a dividend of 15
cents per share of common stock, the first such payment since the
fourth quarter of 1985. Preferred stock dividends also will resume,
the bank's chief executive said.
   ``By reinstating our cash dividend we're marking a very important
milestone in our financial recovery,'' A.W. Clausen, the company's
chairman and chief executive officer, told reporters. ``It assures
our customers that BankAmerica has put behind it a very difficult
period in our history.''
   The San Francisco-based bank has for several months been
pronouncing itself cured of a variety of financial ills that brought
three years of red ink starting in 1985. The problems are traced to
losses on a variety of loans, including Third World debt and real
estate and farm lending in this country.
   BankAmerica returned to the black last year, posting a year-end
profit of $726 million, or $3.79 a share, in contrast with a $955
million loss the previous year. The 1987 results were depressed by
the addition of $1.1 billion to the bank's loan-loss reserve.
   The common stock dividend is payable March 10 to stockholders of
record Feb. 23. It was declared by the board of directors at a
meeting here.
   BankAmerica's last dividend was paid in the fourth quarter of
1985. The dividend reached a high of 38 cents a quarter in 1984, and
was reduced the following year.
   BankAmerica stock closed at $20.50 a share in composite trading,
down 37{ cents from Friday's close.
   Analysts had expected a resumption of the dividend, said Dan
Williams, who follows the company for Sutro &amp; Co. in San Francisco,
and stockholders could be expected to begin agitating for dividends
given the bank's recent strong performance.
   The move signals management confidence, he reasoned, since
executives would be unlikely to risk being forced to reduce or stop
dividends once they are restarted.
   Clausen said the bank's directors decided to pay the dividend
because the institution had returned to profitability through its
daily operations, as opposed to profits sustained through the sale
of assets.
   In December 1986, the company sold its retail bank in Italy for
$603 million; in February of 1987, it agreed to sell the Charles
Schwab discount brokerage company for $230 million. The company also
closed various branches and eliminated thousands of jobs over the
past two years.
   Clausen said the bank's base of assets has been rebuilt to the
point that it exceeds federal regulators' minimum requirement for
risk-based capital for year-end 1992.
</TEXT>
