   News of a dividend increase at General Motors set
a positive tone on Wall Street today and moved stock prices higher.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 5.89 at
2,326.96 as of 11 a.m. EST.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a margin of about
2 to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 751 higher, 390 lower
and 582 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 58.66 million shares as of 11 a.m.
   GM announced after the market closed Monday it was sharply
raising the dividend on all three classes of its common stock. While
the move was anticipated, it came earlier than expected.
   GM, a component of the Dow Jones industrial average, was up 3 to
92{ in heavy trading.
   Investors remained concerned about high rates on short-term debt
securities such as Treasury bills. Those high rates hamper the stock
market by providing an attractive alternative to investors.
   Today, for the first time since April 1982, yields on three-month
Treasury bills were even higher than rates on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year bond.
   The yield of the long bond stood at 8.85 percent in morning
trading. Meanwhile, the bond-equivalent yield of the three-month
Treasury bill was at 8.87 percent.
   The dollar, which often provides direction for stock prices,
failed to do so today as foreign exchange markets sought a trend of
their own.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Union Carbide, up
\ to 28\.
   Burlington Resources, which rose nearly 10 a share on Monday, was
off 2] to 46}. The stock had jumped after Pennzoil said it acquired
8 percent of the company's shares.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.60 at 166.79. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.80 at 325.80.
