<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Pepsico     02-07 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Pepsico,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsico Earnings Rise 28 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. said its earnings rose 28 percent in
the fourth quarter, with improved results in its soft drink and
snack food businesses and flat earnings from restaurants.
   Pepsico said its quarterly profit rose to $187.7 million, or 72
cents a share, from $147 million, or 56 cents a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose 22 percent to $4.19 billion from $3.44 billion.
   Besides Pepsi, holdings of the Purchase, N.Y.-based company
include Frito-Lay, Pizza Hut, Kentucky Fried Chicken and Taco Bell.
   For the full year, Pepsico said its profit rose 28 percent to
$762.2 million, or $2.90 a share, from $594.8 million, or $2.26 a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 14 percent to $13 billion from
$11.4 billion.
   Contributing to the increases, the latest quarterly and annual
reporting periods were longer than the preceding ones. The quarter
had 17 weeks, compared with 16, and the year had 53 weeks, compared
with 52.
   By segment in the fourth quarter, Pepsico said snack foods'
operating profit rose 26 percent on a 17 percent increase in sales;
soft drink operating profit rose 31 percent on a 30 percent increase
in sales; and restaurant operating profit was flat on a 19 percent
increase in sales.
   For the full year, Pepsico said, all three business segments
posted stronger results. Operating profit was up 16 percent in snack
foods, 22 percent in soft drinks and 10 percent in restaurants.
</TEXT>
