<FIRST>u f PM-Cooper-Champion 2ndLd-Writethru   02-07 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cooper-Champion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cooper Industries Enters Bidding For Champion Spark Plug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with Champion board deciding to explore
Cooper offer; ADDS new 4th graf with spokesman quote; picks up 4th graf
pvs, ``Cooper's proposal ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say a bidding contest for Champion Spark
Plug Co. may follow Cooper Industries' $800 million cash buyout
proposal, which tops Champion's earlier agreement for a $590 million
takeover by Dana Corp.
   Cooper, a diversified maker of commercial and industrial
products, announced its $21 a share buyout proposal on Monday and
indicated it might be prepared to bid even higher.
   Champion's board of directors met today in a previously scheduled
session, and company spokesman Anthony Mougey said the board agreed
to consider the Cooper offer.
   ``No definitive action was taken by the board at a regularly
scheduled meeting today beyond the decision to explore the Cooper
proposal,'' he said.
   Cooper's proposal sent Champion's stock up $3.25 to $22.62{ a
share on the New York Stock Exchange Monday on speculation that Dana
might have to raise its $17.50 a share cash-and-stock buyout offer.
   Cooper's offer still is subject to confirmation by the company's
board of directors, which next meets Feb. 21.
   Dana, an automotive parts manufacturer based in Toledo, Ohio,
signed an agreement last month under which it would pay $17.50 in
cash and securities for Champion's outstanding shares.
   Robert Cizik, chairman and president of Cooper, said Monday he
had no objection to Champion's agreement to pay Dana $15 million if
their buyout fell through.
   Cizik also said in a letter to Champion's board of directors that
Cooper ``would be prepared to increase the purchase price of our
proposal if you and your advisers can demonstrate to us additional
values inherent in Champion Spark Plug Co.''
   Dana spokesman Don Decker said the company had no comment on
Cooper's action and declined to say if Dana would increase its bid.
   
   Champion is the world's leading manufacturer of spark plugs for
all types of internal combustion engines. It also manufactures Anco
windshield wiper blades and a variety of other fuel system and
automotive maintenance products. It has annual revenue of about $720
million and employs about 9,200 people worldwide.
   ``Strategically, this is a significant opportunity for Cooper,''
Cizik said.
   ``Champion has strong brand recognition and market leadership and
would provide an excellent entry into its two market segments,'' he
said.
   Under the Dana agreement, Dana would pay $17.50 cash per share up
to half of Chamption's outstanding common shares, with the rest
being exchanged for Dana stock with a value of $17.50 a share.
   Wall Street analysts have said Dana's attempt to buy Champion may
be hampered because Champion's stock remains above $17.50. Some
analysts say Dana is buying Champion for a bargain price.
   A member of Champion's founding family, Stephen Stranahan,
recently quit the board because he was unhappy with the Dana deal.
   The Stranahan family in 1986 established the Chinook Partners
L.P. to maintain a dominant voice in Champion's affairs. Chinook
controls 35 percent of Champion's common stock.
   Chinook has yet to tender its shares to Dana, which some Wall
Street analysts have said would have locked up the deal.
   Houston-based Cooper, with 1988 revenue of $4.3 billion, is a
diversified, worldwide manufacturer of products for the electrical,
electronic, commercial, industrial, compression and drilling market.
   Dana, which had 1987 sales of $4.9 billion, makes a variety of
automotive parts including drive-train components, engine parts and
chassis products.
   The two companies have said the merger would unite Champion's
famous name with Dana's far-flung distribution system.
</TEXT>
