<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, then turned narrowly mixed with
little fresh news to influence prices.
   The slight early losses reflected some follow-through selling
after Monday's steep declines in the corn and soybean pits.
   Analysts said forecasts for more snow this week in the Great
Plains and the Midwest have put grain traders on the defensive.
   The snow means more moisture in areas stricken by last summer's
drought.
   ``There is a growing realization among traders that the odds of a
back-to-back crop adversity in Midwest are extremely small,'' said
Richard Feltes, director of commodities research with Refco Inc., a
Chicago-based commodities brokerage firm.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to } cent lower with March at $2.66 a bushel; oats were 1{
cents to 2} cents lower with March at $2.13 a bushel; soybeans were
2 cents lower to { cent higher with March at $7.53{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .15 cent lower with February at
75.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent lower
with March at 84.25 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent to .55
cent lower with February at 42.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .72 cent to .95 cent lower with February at 38.10 cents a pound.
   Pork futures prices fell sharply Monday on indications that the
movement of hogs to market had not been slowed by adverse weather in
the Midwest. Cattle futures settled mixed on Monday.
