<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Volcker-S&amp;Ls     02-07 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Volcker-S&amp;Ls,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Fed Chairman Endorses S&amp;L Bailout Plan in Principle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-S&amp;Ls Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker
today gave a general endorsement to the Bush administration's effort
to rescue the savings and loan industry, as members of Congress said
they intended to act on a bailout package as quickly as possible.
   Volcker, testifying before the Senate Banking Committee, said
that while he had not had a chance to review the Bush proposal in
detail he believed that it addressed all of the major problems
facing the S&amp;L industry.
   ``I welcome the administration's initiative this early in the
(congressional) session,'' Volcker said. ``The president's program
provides a very good base for your consideration of legislation.''
   Volcker said he was concerned that the deposit insurance premiums
on savings and loans and the nation's commercial 13,000 banks not be
raised so high that it put the institutions at a competitive
disadvantage with other financial entities.
   ``My sense is that the increased insurance premiums goes to the
edge of viability in terms of not undermining the health of the
financial industry, which is under heavy competition,'' he said.
   Volcker also said he disagreed with the administration's proposal
to abolish the Federal Home Loan Bank Board as an independent
regulatory agency. President Bush's plan would retain only the
chairman of the bank board, making him the head of an S&amp;L regulatory
agency that would be placed under the jurisdiction of the Treasury
Department.
   Volcker said that instead of abolishing the three-member bank
board he would prefer leaving it as an independent regulatory agency
but split off its oversight of the S&amp;L deposit insurance fund.
   Committee Chairman Donald Riegle, D-Mich., said he and Sen. Jake
Garn of Utah, the panel's ranking Republican, plan to introduce the
administration's package as soon as it was submitted and schedule
early hearings in an effort to vote the measure out in as short a
time as possible.
   ``I am determined to see us act quickly in the committee to match
the speed of the administration,'' Riegle said at the beginning of
the hearing. Both Riegle and Garn called on the other committee
members to set aside partisan differences and work with dispatch to
report a bill to the full Senate.
   ``This problem is serious enough that we don't have time to be
partisan about it,'' Garn said. ``I hope we can get together in the
next few months to pass legislation.''
   Volcker said the problem was of such a serious nature that if
necessary Congress should consider exempting the necessary
government spending from the overall deficit limits established by
the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law.
   He said this could be justified because sale of the government
bonds being used to finance the bailout effort was different from
ordinary government expenditures and would not have the same
inflationary impact on the economy as raising spending in such areas
as defense.
   On the question of raising the deposit insurance premiums,
Volcker did not provide a specific amount that he would like to see.
But he said the Bush recommendation came very close to the limits
that the banks could bear.
   ``The banks are having enough trouble competing now and I don't
like to see any additional burdens put on them,'' Volcker said.
``This goes toward the limits of what is tolerable.''
</TEXT>
