<FIRST>r f PM-IC-Prospect     02-07 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IC-Prospect,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Central Neutral On Prospect's Bid, Will Seek Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospect Group Inc. is calling ``constructive'' a
move by the Illinois Central Transportation Co. that could raise the
railroad's price tag above the $436 million that Prospect is
offering.
   Illinois Central said Monday it was taking a neutral stance on
Prospect's unsolicited $20-per-share cash tender offer and indicated
it would entertain competing bids.
   The Chicago-based railroad said it was exploring ``alternatives
which might result in greater shareholder values'' and that it had
directed its financial adviser, Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.,
to begin discussions with New York-based Prospect and other parties.
   Illinois Central spokesman Frank Allston would not expand on the
company's carefully worded statement.
   In New York, Prospect Chairman W. Wallace McDowell Jr. issued a
statement saying: ``We welcome the constructive response from
Illinois Central and look forward to talking with the company and
its investment bankers.''
   An industry analyst said the railroad appeared to be inviting
other bids.
   ``They are opening the door and they want to make sure anyone
interested can take advantage of that if they're so inclined,'' said
John Landschulz, a transportation-industry analyst with Cowen &amp; Co.
in Chicago.
   Prospect, a conglomerate that operates a regional railroad in the
Southeast, launched its tender offer for Illinois Central on Jan.
27. Illinois Central has 21.8 million shares outstanding.
   Illinois Central's stock price rose $1 Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange, closing at $22.
   Analysts say the firm's high stock price relative to the Prospect
offer indicates that Wall Street expects a higher bid for the
company.
   Prospect owns about 4.7 percent of Illinois Central, a spin-off
of the Whitman Corp. that began trading as an independent company on
Jan. 3 at $11 a share.
   Illinois Central is a major carrier of freight between Chicago
and the Gulf of Mexico.
   One of the railroad's largest customers, grain-processing giant
Archer-Daniels-Midland Co. of Decatur, has also been an active buyer
of Illinois Central's stock.
   ADM owned 9.8 percent of Illinois Central at the end of January
and has indicated its intention to to increase its stake to 25
percent.
   But ADM has maintained that its acquisition of the railroad's
stock is for investment purposes only, and analysts have said they
do not believe ADM wants to own the railroad.
   In addition to MidSouth, a railroad that Prospect built partly
from track purchased from Illinois Central, Prospect owns Murray
Bakery Products Inc., the largest supplier of cookies to the Girl
Scouts of America; Children's Discovery Centers Inc., the country's
fifth-largest daycare chain; Forschner Group Inc., which distributes
Swiss Army knives; and Ivy Insurance Corp., a casualty insurance
company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
