<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     02-07 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0370</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices advanced broadly on Wall Street today on
news of a dividend increase at General Motors and in anticipation
that Congress and top government officials will be denied a pay
raise.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 18.22 at
2,339.29 as of noon EST.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a margin of better
than 2 to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 872 stocks higher,
415 lower and 528 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 88.76 million shares at midday.
   Jack Barbanel, a vice president with Gruntal &amp; Co., said the
market's advance was due in part to an expected vote in Congress
that would kill a pay raise for House and Senate members and top
Bush administration officials. A pay increase was expected to have
worsened the federal budget deficit.
   Prices also moved higher in response to President Bush's
announcement of a bailout plan for the savings and loan industry
although the proposal would put pressure on the bond market,
Barbanel said. Bush's plan called for the issuing of $50 billion in
new government bonds.
   The bond market displayed some resilience today, as did the
dollar, and this spilled over to stocks, Barbanel said.
   The market also got a boost from GM's announcement that it was
sharply raising the dividend on all three classes of its common
stock. While the move announced late Monday was anticipated, it came
earlier than expected.
   GM, a component of the Dow Jones industrial average, was up 3| to
93[ in heavy trading.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Union Carbide, up
2 to 30.
   Burlington Resources, which rose nearly 10 a share on Monday,
fell 2[ to 47. The stock had jumped after Pennzoil said it acquired
8 percent of the company's shares.
   IBM was up 1\ to 127~ after announcing improvements for its
mainframe computers.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
1.03 at 167.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.99 at 325.47.
</TEXT>
