<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AmericanJets 2ndLd-Writethru   02-07 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American Jets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Gets Big Order from American</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES extraneous words, `The smaller MD-80s' at end of 6th
graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines announced one of the biggest
aircraft orders in history today, calling for the carrier to acquire
at least eight new long-range McDonnell Douglas Corp. jetliners with
options to buy another 42 plus options for 100 smaller planes.
   The order announced in New York by senior executives of both
companies will make American the first U.S. carrier to obtain
delivery of the MD-11, a widebody, long-haul plane designed to
replace the older DC-10. The smaller MD-80 would replace the Boeing
727.
   Neither company would place a value on the deal but it is
potentially worth several billion dollars and marks a major coup for
McDonnell Douglas, which has been aggressively seeking orders for
the MD-11 in the high-stakes aircraft competition with Boeing Co.
and the Airbus Industrie consortium of Europe.
   The Fort Worth, Texas-based airline's aircraft acquisitions come
amid rising concern about aging U.S. commercial aircraft fleets and
whether older planes are less safe.
   The new aircraft will replace some older planes in American's
fleet, which is an average of 9.4 years old, compared with 12.4
industrywide.
   The MD-11s have a list price of $100 million, but analysts said
American's actual purchase price will probably be in the range of
$80 million to $85 million per plane.
   ``American has done quite a lot of expansion since deregulation,
entered the international service, opened new hubs, and has
announced further intentions to expand further in the international
service. That's what the purchases are all about,'' said Lee Howard,
executive vice president of Airline Economics Inc. in Washington.
   ``Knowing how tough American is about demanding favorable terms
on these purchases, my guess is McDonnell Douglas must be giving
them a good deal,'' said Andrew B.S. Kim, an analyst with Robert
Fleming Inc. in New York.
   ``They (American officials) are doing this to get a younger
fleet,'' said Julius Maldutis, a Salomon Brothers Inc. analyst in
New York. ``What it does simply is to position American Airlines for
the rest of the decade (the 1990s) and gives them enormous
flexibility because of the maintenance problems everyone else is
having with their older fleets.''
   But Robert J. Joedicke, an advisory director for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York, downplayed airline safety as an issue
behind the purchase.
   ``I recognize the public perception. But aircraft do not wear out
as long as they are properly maintained,'' he said. ``It does cost
too much money to maintain the older planes. But an aircraft does
not become unsafe. American will be looking at lower unit costs and
aircraft more dedicated to the operations they have with the new
planes.
   ``American is doing a lot more overseas operations,'' Joedicke
continued. ``The MD-11 is better suited to the routes that American
does fly overseas, based on the density of the routes.''
   Kim said the MD-11s are long-haul aircraft that will replace
American's DC-10 fleet. The DC-10 was the predecessor of the MD-11.
   He said the MD-80s are short-haul twinjets that will help replace
American's Boeing 727s, which comprise the largest percentage of
American's 470-jet fleet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
