market's advance also was due in part to an expected vote in
Congress that would kill a pay raise for House and Senate members
and top Bush administration officials. A pay increase was expected
to have worsened the federal budget deficit.
   The House voted down the raise today and sent it to the Senate.
   Prices also moved higher in response to President Bush's
announcement of a bailout plan for the savings and loan industry
although the proposal would put pressure on the bond market,
Barbanel said. Bush's plan called for the issuing of $50 billion in
new government bonds.
   ``You couldn't get much more positive news across the board,''
Baker said.
   Program buying added to today's gains, he said.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Union Carbide, up
1~ to 29~. Analysts said the chemical company was the subject of
takeover rumors, but a chunk of the buying came from investors
trying to take advantage of Carbide's upcoming dividend payment.
   Burlington Resources, which rose nearly 10 on Monday, fell 2[ to
47. The stock had jumped after Pennzoil said it acquired 8 percent
