<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Cooper-Champion     02-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cooper-Champion,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Champion Board Considering Cooper's Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Champion Spark Plug Co.'s directors met
Tuesday to consider an $800 million cash takeover offer from Cooper
Industries Inc., and there were indications a deal could be worked
out.
   A Cooper takeover of Champion would derail a previously announced
$590 million cash-and-securities deal for Toledo-based Dana Corp. to
acquire the spark plug maker.
   ``No definitive action was taken by the board at a regularly
scheduled meeting today beyond the decision to explore the Cooper
proposal,'' Champion spokesman Anthony Mougey said.
   But Mougey added that Champion has begun meeting with Cooper to
discuss the deal.
   O. Lee Henry, Champion's president and chief executive officer,
met Monday with Cooper officials at Cooper's Houston headquarters.
Henry agreed to Cooper's request for access to confidential
financial information, as well as granting access to its plants and
offices.
   Cooper on Monday offered to buy Champion for at least $21 a
share, outbidding Dana's $17.50 a share agreement to acquire the
company announced last month.
   A member of Champion's founding family, who also is chairman of
the board, said he would probably go along with Cooper's offer.
   ``I haven't had time to digest it,'' said Robert Stranahan Jr.,
74. ``But they've been around for a good many years, and they've
diversified a great deal, have a lot of different products and are a
very strong company.''
   Stranahan said he couldn't predict whether Champion's board or a
family run limited partnership that controls 35 percent of the
company's stock would approve the deal. The Stranahan family in 1986
established the partnership to maintain a dominant voice in
Champion's affairs.
   Cooper, a diversified maker of commercial and industrial
products, indicated it might bid even higher for the company.
Spokeswoman Ellen Myers said the two sides were moving forward with
the deal.
   Dana spokesman Don Decker declined comment on Cooper's offer and
would not say whether the automotive parts maker would increase its
bid.
   Joseph Phillippi, an automotive industry analyst wih Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York, said Champion would fit well into
Cooper's product lines.
   ``There's no product overlap, and spark plugs provide them with
another product line for the automotive aftermarket,'' he said.
   Phillippi also said Cooper is aggressive in reducing costs.
   ``Saying they do a lot of streamlining is putting it mildly,'' he
said.
   Cooper has owned Toledo-area companies. The company closed Magnum
Electric Co. of Erie, Mich., and Magnum Tool of Toledo, a division
of its Belden Eletronic Wiring &amp; Cable unit in 1986, idling 120
workers.
   Ms. Meyers said Cooper probably would move Champion's corporate
headquarters from Toledo to Houston and keep the Toledo plant intact.
   Champion is the world's leading manufacturer of spark plugs for
all types of internal combustion engines. It also makes Anco
windshield wiper blades and a variety of other fuel system and
automotive maintenance products. It has annual revenue of about $720
million and employs about 9,200 people worldwide.
   Cooper, with 1988 revenue of $4.3 billion, is a diversified,
worldwide manufacturer of products for the electrical, electronic,
commercial, industrial, compression and drilling market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
