<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Debt Bjt   02-07 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Cuts A Must To Overcome Mexican Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government must further slash its budget
deficit and raise $36 billion in fresh foreign credits over the next
six years to pull Mexico out of an economic crisis, a private study
concluded Tuesday.
   The study by the Panamerican Private Management Institute was
released as Mexico's Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe was in Washington
attempting to renegotiate payment terms on Mexico's $106 billion
foreign debt. Mexico has rejected a $3.5 billion aid package in U.S.
short-term loans as too onerous.
   The Panamerican institute said the government must lower its
budget deficit to at least 6.4 percent of gross national product,
the value of the total output of goods and services, from 14.9
percent in 1987 and estimated 10 percent this year.
   It also said President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's administration
should seek an average of $6 billion annually over the next six
years in long-term loans from abroad so the economy, which remained
virtually stagnant during the preceding administration, can resume
growth.
   The institute is an arm of the private, highly regarded
Panamerican University. Its findings appeared to reinforce Salinas's
prescription of strong medicine for the sick economy.
   The study also said the administration must sharply restrict the
money supply to restrain inflation, which hit an all-time high of
159 percent in 1987.
   It dropped to 51.7 percent last year as a result of tight
restrictions on wage and retail price increases that began in the
last year of President Miguel de la Madrid's six-year
administration. The plan was extended for another six months by
Salinas when he took office Dec. 1.
   A Treasury official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said a
recent interview Mexico would not use the U.S. loan offered in
October because it would mean even more burdensome debt payments.
   Instead of borrowing more money, Aspe is reportedly trying to
reduce the existing debt as well as lower interest payments.
   Mexico has paid a total of $18 billion in principal and interest
to foreign creditors in the past two years, money that could have
been used for investment and public works.
   The study warned that unless the deficit was cut and new money
brought in ``inflation will start growing again, at an enormous
political cost that would result in social unrest and loss of
control by the government over its economic policies.''
   A measure of relief is apparently in sight with recent increases
in world prices for crude oil, a major source of Mexico's foreign
income, the newspaper El Financiero said Tuesday.
   Mexico exports an average of 1.325 million barrels a day, about
half of it to the United States. Price drops in 1987 cut oil income
from $7.8 billion to about $5.2 billion in 1988.
   El Financiero also quoted unnamed government officials as saying
the government plans to crack down on tax evaders so that tax
revenues this year ``will surpass the income from oil exports.''
   Tax collecting became increasingly lax during the de la Madrid
administration, mostly because people and businesses were short of
money because of the crisis, which began in 1982 when the bottom
fell out of the international oil market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
