<FIRST>u f AM-AmericanJets Bjt   02-07 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Jets, Bjt,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Signs Big Aircraft Order with McDonnell Douglas, GE</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. and General Electric
Corp. emerged as the big winners Tuesday in an American Airlines
contract for up to 142 planes, potentially one of the biggest
aircraft orders in history.
   American said it signed an agreement with McDonnell Douglas to
acquire at least eight new long-range MD-ll jetliners with options
to buy another 42. The airline also took options on 100 MD-80s, a
smaller plane designed to replace the Boeing 727.
   The order will make American the first U.S. airline to obtain
delivery of the MD-11, a widebody aircraft designed to replace the
older DC-10, company officials told a news conference.
   Company officials wouldn't disclose the value of the deal, but
industry experts estimate it could total around $7 billion. It marks
a major coup for McDonnell Douglas, which has been aggressively
seeking orders for the MD-11 in the high-stakes aircraft competition
with Boeing Co. and the Airbus Industrie consortium of Europe.
   American also announced that it has signed an agreement with
General Electric to acquire up to 200 CF6-80C2 engines for use on
most of its widebody jets, including the MD-11.
   American had considered competing engines made by Pratt &amp; Whitney
and Britain's Rolls-Royce PLC, American officials said, but decided
that the GE engines provide more flexibility since they can be used
on both the MD-11 and other aircraft.
   In a related development Tuesday, McDonnell Douglas announced
that in addition to American, four other airlines have signed orders
for new MD-11s. The four carriers _ Air Europe of Britain, Aero
Lloyd of West Germany, ZAS Airline of Egypt and Finnair, the
national airline of Finland _ have ordered a total of 26 MD-11s, the
aircraft maker said.
   American chose the MD-11 over Boeing Co.'s rival 747-400 largely
because the McDonnell Douglas aircraft will be available sooner,
said Robert L. Crandall, American's chairman and president.
   The acquisitions by American, the nation's second-largest
carrier, come amid rising concern about aging U.S. commercial
aircraft fleets and whether older planes are less safe.
   Some airline analysts view the purchases as part of an innovative
marketing strategy at American to reassure the public about safety.
   The new aircraft will replace some older planes in American's
fleet, which is an average of 9.4 years old, compared with 12.4
years industrywide.
   The agreement gives American great flexibility in planning for
fleet growth and aircraft replacement in the 1990s and beyond,
Crandall said.
   ``One of the most valuable commodities an airline has is the
confidence of the flying public,'' he said. In addition to upgrading
its fleet, American also is paying strict attention to inspecting
and maintaining its older aircraft, he noted.
   As a result of the new acquisitions, American's fleet will be the
youngest in the U.S. airline industry by the end of 1991, Crandall
said.
   American plans to spend around $10.5 billion through the end of
1993 to modernize its fleet, Donald J. Carty, the airline's senior
vice president for planning and finance, told the news conference.
</TEXT>
