<FIRST>r f AM-ThunderbirdProduction     02-07 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thunderbird Production,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderbird-Cougar Problem Found, Delivery Resuming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has resumed delivery of
Thunderbird and Cougar automobiles after holding thousands of them
because of a bad bolt in the steering gear mount, the company said
Tuesday.
   Spokesman John Spelich said about 10,600 cars were withheld after
being built at the company's assembly plant in Lorain, Ohio, after a
rattle found by inspectors Jan. 25 and by two customers later.
   Delivery off the assembly line resumed Monday, Spelich said.
   Inspectors will check each of the cars that were withheld and if
defective bolts are found, they will be replaced, Spelich said. Most
of the cars withheld were parked at a lot at the Cedar Point
amusement park, about 30 miles west of Lorain.
   The rattle, noticed in all versions of the Ford Thunderbird and
Mercury Cougar, was caused by a bad bolt in a small percentage of
the cars being checked, Spelich said. He declined to specify how
many cars had the defective bolts.
   He said Ford officials knew of no safety problems or accidents
linked to the problem.
   There are no plans for recalling the cars, Spelich added.
   The steering mount bolt was the latest piece of bad news for the
plant. Production of the Thunderbird SC and Cougar XR7 has been
curtailed pending a changeover from cast to forged crankshafts on
the supercharged engines both cars carry.
   Spelich said the company expects to resume full production of the
two models next month. The Thunderbird SC last month was named Motor
Trend magazine's ``Car of the Year.''
</TEXT>
