<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Salomon     02-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Salomon,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salomon Posts Fourth-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Inc. on Tuesday reported a $38 million
loss in the fourth quarter, due to a special $150 million charge for
repatriating foreign earnings to the United States.
   The financial services and commodity trading company said the
loss for the three months ended Dec. 31 resulted from a previously
announced decision to remit more than $1 billion in foreign earnings
to the United States and pay taxes on those earnings.
   Partly offsetting that $180 million charge was a $30 million
reduction in loan-loss reserves ``permitted by a significant
reduction in the lending activities of the commercial finance
segment.'' Before the charge, the company's net income was $112
million.
   In the year-ago fourth quarter, Salomon had reported a $74
million loss. Revenue totaled $1.8 billion, up from $1.3 billion in
the fourth quarter of 1987.
   For all of 1988, Salomon's net income nearly doubled to $280
million, or $1.65 a share, from $142 million, or 86 cents a share,
in 1987. Revenue rose to $6.15 billion from $6 billion the previous
year.
   Salomon said the company's 1988 earnings were bolstered by strong
results from its oil operations.
   ``The performance of the energy segment was exceptional, and
provided a counterbalance to sluggish securities markets,'' said
John Gutfreund, Salomon chairman and chief executive officer.
   The fourth-quarter results, despite the loss, were helped by the
energy division's record $143 million pre-tax earnings versus $4
million in the same period of 1987.
   The company's Salomon Brothers financial subsidiary earned $68
million before taxes compared with a $90 million loss in the 1987
quarter. Its commercial finance unit earned $83 million, including
the $30 million reduction in loan-loss reserves, up from $45 million
in the year-earlier quarter.
   Partly offsetting those improvements was a decline in the
commodities unit's pre-tax earnings to $16 million from $57 million
in the 1987 quarter, Salomon said.
</TEXT>
