<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-07 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices End Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures rebounded Tuesday after an
early slide.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
32 cents higher at $17.70 a barrel after trading as low as $17.22
during the session. On Monday, the contract lost 15 cents. Other
contract months also ended the day higher.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the March contract
for domestic heating oil fell 0.49 cent to close the day at 49.87
cents a gallon. Other contract months also lost ground.
   Unleaded gasoline for March delivery closed up 0.52 cent at 49.26
cents a gallon with other contract months ending the day mixed.
   Market observers said the gains were partly to internal market
influences of supply and demand.
   But a combination of mostly OPEC-related factors also influenced
the market, including speculation over the possibility of a new
price-stabilization agreement emerging from the the cartel's
price-monitoring committee meeting scheduled for March, said Nauman
Barakat of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Investors also are anticipating a meeting of non-OPEC producers
that may include the Soviet Union could also result in higher
prices, he said.
   ``The fact that they want to meet again is keeping the market
excited,'' Barakat said.
   Several non-OPEC oil producers met last month with Soviet
representatives attending as observers. The meeting produced no
substantial results, but the group said it hoped to find ways to
help the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries stabilize
world oil prices.
</TEXT>
