<FIRST>r f AM-SpendingPlans     02-07 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Plans,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Spending Plans Are Up, Survey Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hold for release 6 p.m. EST; time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half the companies in a national survey
plan to increase their capital spending this year, more than in the
past two years, Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. said Tuesday.
   About 46 percent of the 5,000 companies surveyed planned higher
spending in 1989, reflecting the strength of the economy, according
to Joseph W. Duncan, Dun &amp; Bradstreet's corporate economist.
   In contrast, 33 percent had projected higher spending for 1987
and 41 percent for 1988. Consistent results are not available for
earlier years.
   ``To keep pace with the growing export market for U.S. goods and
services, U.S. businesses are continuing to increase investments to
modernize and expand productivity,'' Duncan said in a statement.
   Among particular sectors of the economy, 50 percent of
manufacturers planned to increase spending, as did 49 percent of
service companies, 40 percent of construction firms, and 39 percent
of wholesale and retail companies.
   The survey was conducted in late November and was statistically
representative of companies of all sizes in all industries.
</TEXT>
