<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Schlumberger     02-07 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Schlumberger,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schlumberger Reports Drop In Fourth-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schlumberger Ltd.'s 1988 fourth-quarter earnings
tumbled 62 percent because of weaker oil prices although its
full-year earnings rose, the energy exploration giant said Tuesday.
   For the three months ended Dec. 31, Schlumberger's net income
totaled $118.95 million, or 49 cents a share, down from $315.8
million, or $1.15 a share in the same 1987 period. Operating revenue
was flat at $1.24 billion, compared with $1.23 billion in the fourth
quarter of 1987.
   For all of 1988, the New York-based energy concern said earnings
rose 35 percent to $476 million, or $1.80 a share, from $352.6
million, or $1.27 a share, in 1987.
   Its operating revenue rose 12 percent to $4.9 billion from $4.4
billion in 1987.
   Schlumberger said the year's earnings included the sale of one
division and a one-time gain of $22 million from an award by the
Iran-U.S. Claims Tribunal, formed to resolve property disputes
between Iran and the United States after relations deteriorated in
1979.
   Schlumberger's chairman Euan Baird earlier had predicted that
weak oil prices would have a negative impact on the company's
exploraton and development budgets.
</TEXT>
