<SECOND>AM-Bush-Acquisition,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Decides Against Intervening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush refused to prohibit a proposed
acquisition of Monsanto Electronic Materials Co. by a German firm
because the deal posed no national security threat, the White House
said Tuesday.
   Bush's decision against intervening in the proposed purchase of
Monsanto by Huels AG of West Germany came after an investigation _
the first to be carried out under trade legislation passed by
Congress last year.
   Monsanto Electronic Materials Co. manufactures silicon wafers for
use in making semiconductors, the building blocks of computers.
   The investigation was carried out by the Committee on Foreign
Investment in the United States, headed by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady. The probe looked at various issues related to
silicon wafers, including reliability of supply and technology
transfer.
   During the investigation, U.S. officials met with representatives
of Monsanto and Huels.
   A provision in the legislation which overhauled U.S. trade laws
authorizes the president to investigate and, if necessary, to
suspend or prohibit a foreign acquisition of a U.S. business engaged
in interstate commerce.
</TEXT>
