<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Continue Rally As Supply Fears Reawaken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures rallied for the fourth straight day Tuesday as
reawakened fears of tightening supplies stirred New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange.
   On other markets, copper futures prices gained following an
extended string of losses, gold and silver futures fell, livestock
and meat, energy, and grain and soybean futures were mixed.
   Coffee futures settled 1.55 cents to 3.34 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $1.4134 a pound, the first close
above the psychologically important $1.40 level since Jan. 23.
   The March contract has risen by 9.23 cents a pound, a gain of
nearly 7 percent, over the past four sessions. The advance has been
fueled partly by concerns about the tight availability of coffee for
delivery against the March contract and partly by fears that a
continuation of the sharp price decline witnessed during the last
two weeks of January could trigger a cutback in producer shipments.
   The International Coffee Organization, a price-control group
composed of the largest coffee producer and consumer countries,
would be required to order a 1-million-bag reduction in exports of
robusta coffee beans if an indicator based on the 15-day moving
average of cash coffee prices falls to $1.20 a pound.
   The indicator stood at $1.2259 at the close of business on
Tuesday.
   Although the indicator would have to drop even further before
affecting shipments of the arabica coffee beans traded in New York,
``it makes some people apprenhensive that if the cut were imposed,
it would lead to shortages,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The prospect of a general labor strike in Brazil, the world's
largest coffee producer, also contributed to the bullish tone.
Brazil's two major unions have scheduled a meeting on Feb. 13 to set
a strke date.
   Copper futures surged on New York's Commodity Exchange after
falling sharply in five of the six previous sessions.
   Analysts attributed the advance to technical factors and
increased buying of actual copper.
   Copper settled 1.15 cents to 2.60 cents higher with March at
$1.315 a pound.
   Gold and silver futures slipped lower on the Commodity Exchange
in reaction to the dollar's gains against other major currencies and
the continuing outlook for low inflation.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $1.70 lower with April at $395.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.9 cents to 4.7 cents lower with March at $5.89 a
troy ounce.
   Hog futures prices steadied on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
following Monday's steep decline but pork belly futures fell again
on selling linked to an unexpected increase in hog slaughters.
   Most cattle futures moved higher, boosted by strong cash markets.
   Live cattle settled .22 cent to .45 cent higher with February at
75.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with March at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .40 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with February at 42.30 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .22 cent to .92 cent lower with February at
38.60 cents a pound.
   Among energy futures traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .15 cent to .32 cent
higher with March at $17.70 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent to
.49 cent lower with March at 49.87 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .04 cent lower to .52 cent higher with March at 49.26 cents a
gallon.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, soybean and corn futures advanced
late in response to firmer cash prices for soybeans and soybean
meal. Wheat finished narrowly mixed.
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 1} cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $4.27\ a bushel; corn was { cent to 1{
cents higher with March at $2.67 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents lower with March at $2.14 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 3{
cents higher with March at $7.57{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
