<FIRST>r f AM-ChicagoAutoShow     02-07 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Auto Show,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Show Opens Saturday; Japanese Sports Cars In Spotlight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The automobile spotlight turns to Chicago this
week as the nation's oldest auto show gets under way Saturday,
featuring a trio of new Japanese sports cars.
   Mazda Motor Corp., Honda Motor Co. and Nissan Motor Corp. each
have scheduled introductions of two-seaters for the nine-day show.
   Mazda's MX-5 is, in some sense, a throwback to a simpler time in
motoring history. Honda's offering is a futuristic-looking new model
for its upscale Acura line, and Nissan's is an updated version of
its 300ZX.
   General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp. market small numbers of
two-seaters in the United States. GM sells the Buick Reatta, the
Chevrolet Corvette and the Cadillac Allante, whose body is made in
Italy. Chrysler offers the TC, made by Maserati of Italy using many
Chrysler parts.
   Ford got out of the two-seater business earlier in the 1980s when
it dropped its Escort EXP to devote production capacity to its
regular Escort line of subcompacts.
   ``They're all two-seaters, but they're different classes,'' auto
analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
said of the U.S. cars.
   ``It's a niche here and a niche there,'' she said. ``Everybody is
going to be niched to death.''
   The new Acura will have an estimated sticker price of $55,000.
Honda has released few details on the model.
   Mazda's latest entry into the two-seater market resembles the
Lotus Elan from the 1960s, inside and out, according to photos in
trade and auto-buff magazines. Missing is a lot of today's glitzy
digital instrumentation, replaced by basic dials and gauges. It's
expected to cost about $13,000 when it arrives in showrooms this
summer.
   The 300ZX is a new design under an old name. It's shorter and
wider than the current 300ZX, the latest in a series of ``Z-cars''
that began in 1969 with the 240Z, then a Datsun.
   Nissan also will exhibit for the first time its Axxess minivan
the company plans to import from Japan later this year. The
minivan's future is cloudy, however.
   The Treasury Department may rule that imported sport-utility
vehicles and minivans, including the Axxess, will be subject to a
25-percent tariff that now is imposed on vehicles classified as
trucks. Nissan's Thomas Mignanelli, executive vice president for
U.S. operations, has said that the company may keep the Axxess out
of America if it is subject to the tariff.
   Few new products from U.S. manufacturers are expected at the
Chicago show, which is being challenged by a restyled auto show in
Detroit. That show, which ran Jan. 7-15, attracted more than a dozen
concept cars and a variety of new-car introductions, including those
of two Japanese luxury lines.
   Organizers of the Detroit show said they wanted to bring the
biggest and best auto show in the country back to Motor City. It
attracted more than 636,722 people this year, 35 percent more than
the show record set in 1986.
   But the Chicago show, in its 81st year, consistently has outdrawn
the Detroit show and has been the nation's foremost display of new
vehicles. Last year it drew 974,432 people.
   Both shows are sponsored by local automobile dealer associations,
but the Chicago show also includes displays from allied industries _
from car-wax companies to drag-racer makers.
   More than 1,000 vehicles will be on display in Chicago, about 300
more than in Detroit.
   Organizers in Detroit argue they are limited by the size of Cobo
Center, which opened a 200,000-square-foot addition just in time for
the show, giving the center a total of 600,000 square feet of
display space. The Chicago show uses McCormick Place, which is
slightly larger at 650,000 square feet.
</TEXT>
