<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;LPlan-Texas     02-07 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Plan-Texas,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savers See Little Difference Between One Bailout Plan or Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's proposal for bailing out the
savings and loan industry is receiving a lukewarm reaction from
Texas depositors, but many in the state worst hit by the crisis say
they're glad to see some action.
   S&amp;L depositors visiting downtown Dallas branches Tuesday said
they know that any bailout plan will cost them, whether through the
institution they use or as taxpayers.
   ``One way or another, we'll still end up paying for it _ either
through lower interest rates (on accounts) or higher service
charges,'' said Jeff Estrachan, a depositor at Murray Savings, which
has been losing money but is not insolvent.
   Estrachan said he doesn't know if anyone will find a better way
to solve the thrift crisis, which has afflicted many savings
institutions in Texas, ``but I'm glad somebody's doing something.''
   Cheryl Harris, 33, another Murray depositor, is worried about
interest on her savings account. ``I can finally put something
(savings) away and now it looks like it won't be worth it.
   ``It'll probably end up the money I save will go to new taxes,''
she said.
   Under Bush's plan, insurance premiums paid by S&amp;Ls would increase
from 20.8 cents to 23 cents per $100 deposit. The premiums on bank
deposits would rise from 8.3 cents per $100 to 12 cents.
   The thrift plan would make the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
the insurer or thrifts as well as banks.
   It also would tighten S&amp;L regulatory procedures and boost funding
for investigation of wrongdoing by $50 million.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said any plan now is worth looking at.
``This program does face up to it (the S&amp;L crisis), but it's sort of
like kissing your mother-in-law.''
   Kevin Bain, a depositor at Sunbelt Savings,, a new thrift that
resulted from the merger of eight troubled savings institutions
rescued by the government last year, blames Congress for the
deepening crisis.
   ``A policy gets put into place to protect us,'' he said. ``Then
some crook finds a way around it and everyonepays. The warning signs
were out there for Congress years ago.''
   ``Now it looks like we'll (the taxpayers) get screwed again,''
Bain said.
   All three thrift customers agreed that fraud within the system is
not being handled well by the justice system.
   ``It's just like armed robbery,'' Estrachan said. ``Those guys
ought to be sent to Huntsville (prison), just like any other felon.''
   ``They seem to be going too slow on catching the guys
responsible,'' Harris said.
   Gramm, reached in Washington on Tuesday, said he will support
Bush's proposal, but predicted it will be hard to sell to the
industry and taxpayers.
   ``After looking at every option, I like this better than any
alternative,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
