<FILEID>AP-NR-02-07-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Polaroid     02-07 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Polaroid,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Loses $7.5 Million in 1988 Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. on Tuesday posted a $7.5
million loss in the fourth quarter of 1988 it attributed to the
costs of a corporate restructuring earlier in the year.
   Polaroid, which has been battling to fend off a hostile takeover
bid by Shamrock Holdings Inc., said sales for the period totaled
$533 million, up 4.7 percent from $509 million in the corresponding
1987 quarter.
   The loss included a $54.9 million charge to cover remaining costs
the restructuring, which included elimination of 1,300 workers under
a voluntary severance plan, planned global distribution of 35mm film
and a $300 million employee stock ownership plan.
   The loss compared to earnings of $42.3 million in the same
quarter the previous year.
   For the full year, Polaroid said it lost $22.6 million on sales
of $1.86 billion, compared with earnings of $125 million, or $2.02
cents a share, on revenue of $1.76 billion in 1987.
   The full year figures include a $152 million charge for the
restructuring, which was announced in July, and other expenses to
fend off Disney family-owned Shamrock, the instant camera company
said.
</TEXT>
