<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Denies Polaroid Motion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Tuesday denied Polaroid Corp.'s
request to block a hostile takeover bid by Shamrock Holdings Inc.,
which the camera giant had accused of violating federal securities
laws.
   Polaroid last week sought a preliminary injunction against the
bid, charging that Burbank, Calif.-based Shamrock made false and
misleading statements in soliciting proxies from Polaroid
shareholders.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Harrington also denied Polaroid's
motion for expedited proceedings.
   ``The lawsuit will continue and will proceed in due course,''
Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said.
   Shamrock, the investment vehicle of the Roy E. Disney family, is
offering $45 a share in a bid that values Polaroid at $3.2 billion.
Shamrock has vowed a proxy fight for control of the Cambridge-based
company's board of directtors.
   Shamrock has filed suit against Polaroid in Delaware Chancery
Court asking that Polaroid be barred from implementing a proposed
stock buyback and a new stock issue.
   The takeover battle between the two companies began last July.
</TEXT>
