<HEAD>Demand High In Commercial Jet Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 5th graf Demand is...to RESTORE Boeing
estimate of new plane market.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few industry analysts expect a repeat of last
year's record orders for commercial jets, but one manufacturer says
the demand to replace aging aircraft is high enough to cover $450
billion in new orders by 2005.
   American Airlines got the 1989 sales year off to a big start
Tuesday by announcing a contract with McDonnell Douglas Corp. for up
to 142 planes. The deal was estimated to be worth as much as $7
billion.
   The order, potentially one of the biggest ever, could eclipse
last September's order by Delta Air Lines for up to 215 planes from
Boeing Co. and McDonell Douglas, valued at $6 billion to $10 billion.
   Boeing and Airbus Industrie, the European consortium and third
player in the commercial airliner manufacturing market, split a
$5.04 billion order for 130 planes placed last May by International
Lease Finance Corp. for 130 planes.
   Demand is outpacing production at all three, say analysts who
noted that American's order from McDonnell Douglas ensures the
carrier will have planes ready in the near future.
   Furthermore, the overall new plane market shows signs of strength
in coming years, according to Boeing. The company estimates the n`we're
essentially sold out on
that airplane up to the '92-93 period,'' he said.
   Boeing spokesman David Jimenez said Monday there is a waiting
period for new Boeing jets, negotiable with each order, but
``usually a couple of years out.''
   Don Hanson, McDonnell Douglas spokesman in Long Beach, Calif.,
said his company's delivery dates generally extend into 1993.
   ``However, there are always ways to be able to swap delivery
positions to satisfy a customer,'' Hanson said.
